<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President-Elect Vows to Crack Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Vice President and
President-Elect Joseph Estrada Tuesday vowed to crack down on all
big-time tax evaders, particularly those in the top 200
corporations and the rich class.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing, Estrada said his administration will not
impose additional taxes, but will concentrate on collecting the
amount due to the government to raise additional funds for the
government.
</P>
<P>
"I don't have any intention of increasing taxes but what I have
in mind is to have an official tax collection," he said, stressing
that the government could increase its revenues simply by going
after the tax-evaders, starting with the big corporations.
</P>
<P>
But he explained that a tax amnesty may be granted to those who
will be willing to declare their true net worth and disclose their
actual total assets to enable the government to collect the right
amount of taxes.
</P>
<P>
"Whoever they are, regardless of whoever get hit, we will apply
the full force of the law and see to it that these tax evaders
will go to jail," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the same shall apply to business tycoon
Lucio Tan who is facing tax evasion charges filed by the Bureau of
Internal Revenue, the incoming president said, "Of course there is
no exemption to the rule."
</P>
<P>
He said a one-year grace period shall be given to those who are
willing to declare their actual net worth and their total assets,
but after that, they will be required to pay the full amount of
taxes due.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear, however, who among the suspected tax evaders
in the country will serve as an example of Estrada's crackdown and
will face a jail term for failing to pay what is due to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Estrada observed that the Philippines has the lowest tax
collection among Asian countries, due to evasion, adding that "no
less than 90 percent (of the taxpayers) are not paying the correct
taxes in this country."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he vowed to review the tax exemptions given
to several big corporations, noting that this scheme has allowed
these companies to evade the payment of their actual taxes.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of tax exemption is among the controversial
issues raised in the congress during a debate on the Comprehensive
Tax Reform Program, which is strongly opposed by big corporations.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who won the May 11 elections, is scheduled to be sworn
in on June 30 to succeed outgoing President Fidel Ramos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
