<HEADLINE> Greece's Current Account Surplus Grows in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Greece's current account surplus
grew in January this year, rising for the fourth consecutive
month, Greece's central bank, the Bank of Greece, said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Greece's current account in January showed a surplus of 158
million U.S. dollars compared with a surplus of 19.3 million
dollars in the corresponding month of last year.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the surplus to the result of a drop in
January's trade deficit by 64.2 million dollars combined with an
increase in the invisibles surplus by 74.5 million dollars in the
same month of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserves at the end of January
stood at 13.9 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
