<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Secretary of State on Sino-U.S. Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Illustrative of the steps taken to realize a "strategic
partnership" is the establishment of a direct telephone "hot" line
between the two governments, Haig said.
</P>
<P>
This telephone link enables the leaders of both countries to
establish a dialogue on critical issues in a timely fashion.
</P>
<P>
This important new link was first used by President Jiang and
President Clinton last month to explore diplomatic means for
defusing the crisis between Indian and Pakistan, the general said.
</P>
<P>
Since the summit, Haig continued, the defense establishments of
the U.S. and China have initiated an official consultation
mechanism for an exchange of views on international and regional
security issues, including the strengthening of military safety at
sea, by avoiding accidents and misunderstandings that could lead
to improper decisions.
</P>
<P>
"The increases in high level military exchanges between the
countries, as with high level dialogues on political and economic
issues, represent the essence of a 'constructive strategic
partnership,' " he said.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about how to enhance cooperation while
seeking common ground in areas of differences, Haig said that
frequent high level exchanges between the leaders of China and
the United States are the most important steps that can be taken.
</P>
<P>
"We need to better understand each other in order to find
common ground on issues where historical realities might have
created differences," he said. "Differences cannot be simply
shunted aside in the interest of diplomatic harmony."
</P>
<P>
It is inevitable that great nations have their own national
interests which may clash with the interests of other great
nations, Haig said. "However, these differences can often be
managed if addressed prudently in an open-minded and cordial
fashion."
</P>
<P>
"I often think back on the differences that divided us
in the early 1970s. In less than 30 years, consider how far we
have come in addressing differences through communications and
enhanced cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Asked how to increase mutual understanding, Haig said, "I've
never believed that respect was lacking between the Chinese and
American peoples. In fact, the Chinese enjoy the high regard and
admiration of the American people."
</P>
<P>
But, admittedly, there are politicians and leaders representing
narrow special interest groups whose careers have been built by
adopting anti-China rhetorical themes, he said.
</P>
<P>
Misinformation and misunderstandings on the part of individuals
from both countries and from third countries as well need to be
worked on, he added.
</P>
<P>
Progress is achieved through more contacts between peoples, by
visits of Chinese to the United States, Americans to China, by student
exchanges, educational exchanges and by increased communications with
opinion leaders who might unknowingly be spreading misinformation and
half truths, he continued.
</P>
<P>
"Our leaders also need to do a better job in explaining why a
strong, positive U.S.-China relationship is in the interest of not
only China and the U.S., but of the world at large."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the Sino-U.S. relationship's impact on regional and
global issues, the general said the positive effects of a
strengthened U.S.-China relationship have been evident on numerous
issues since the two presidents met in October 1997 in Washington
D.C.
</P>
<P>
"China and the United States have taken leadership roles in
shoring up the economies of several of the Asian countries that
teetered on collapse.
</P>
<P>
"China's unilateral action in aiding the government of Thailand
last year and China's refraining from currency devaluation despite
market pressures have earned great respect.
</P>
<P>
"Just as the U.S. through the International Monetary Fund
sought to shore up the economies of several Asian countries, so
too has China taken the lead in demonstrating its sense of
responsibility as a stabilizing force in the global economy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Affirmation of the positive effect of a strengthened U.S.-China
relationship is no more evident than in the cooperation shown
between President Clinton and President Jiang in seeking to
strengthen stability on the South Asian subcontinent following
independent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan, Haig said.
</P>
<P>
Haig expressed the view that as the world looks to China and
the U.S. for leadership through the Clinton-Jiang Summit in
Beijing later this month, people should bear in mind the dividends
of peace and stability and unprecedented economic growth that have
been made possible by the strengthened U.S. China relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
