<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Warns Against Foreign Military Intervention in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Russian President Boris
Yeltsin Tuesday warned against a possible Western military
intervention in the Serbian province of Kosovo while pledging to
use his influence on Belgrade to seek a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
"Power intervention from outside holds the danger that the
conflict could spread beyond the borders. This would lead to
destabilization in the Balkans with unpredictable consequences for
the whole of Europe," Yeltsin told a press conference after
meeting German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
"The more gently we proceed, the more chances we will have," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that he would meet with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to seek measures to prevent the current
conflict in Kosovo from escalating into a war. But he did not name
the date and venue of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the news conference, Kohl said he and Yeltsin
had agreed to make joint efforts to put a stop to the escalating
violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"It is our common belief that everything must be done to stop
the bloodshed as soon as possible. Every form of violence must be
rejected," said Kohl.
</P>
<P>
But the chancellor noted that a possible military intervention
by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) had not been
discussed during his summit with Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
The German leader also stressed that Germany would continue to
support Russia's reforms led by Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the tough measures introduced by the
Russian government to fight financial turbulence would contribute
significantly to increasing the confidence of foreign investors in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Reports said earlier that Yeltsin may use his visit to appeal
to Bonn to back efforts to secure more Western credits to Russia.
</P>
<P>
A German government spokesman, however, said that there was no
plan for a new German aid package to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Germany and other European Union countries would work through
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank to help
Russia, Kohl told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is in Bonn along with seven Russian government
ministers to attend the first high-level government consultations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the two-day talks, both sides expressed
satisfaction about the new form of contact. The talks will be held
once a year in the future.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after arriving in Bonn, German and Russian ministers
signed two agreements to promote bilateral cooperation in the
nuclear power industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
