<HEADLINE> U.S. Praises Calm Situation in Nigeria After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Tuesday
that it was pleased to see Nigeria was calm following the death of
its leader Sani Abacha, and that it hoped the country would move
to civil rule.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased to see that Nigerians have reacted calmly to
the death of Abacha. And we think it's very important that Nigeria
move forward in the transition to civil rule, democratic
elections, as Nigeria has committed itself to do by October,"
White House spokesman Eric Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, 54, died of heart attack Monday and Gen. Abdusalam
Abubakar, chief of the defense staff, was sworn in Tuesday to
succeed him.
</P>
<P>
Rubin would not say whether the United States was disappointed
that Abubakar was named to replace Abacha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
