<HEADLINE> PNA Minister: Israeli Occupation Must End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) minister said Tuesday that Israel must end its occupation of
the Palestinian lands to prevent deterioration of the Mideast
peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Cairo-based Voice of Arabs Radio over
the telephone from Jerusalem, PNA Minister for Jerusalem Affairs
Faisal Husseini accused Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
of "attempting to cancel altogether the last stage of the Israeli
redeployment in the West Bank."
</P>
<P>
He said Netanyahu is "sort of manoevering to change the clauses
included in the new U.S. initiative."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has proposed that Israel pull back from 13.1 percent
of the West Bank as a second stage redeployment in return for
PNA's better security guarantee. But Israel rejected the
percentage as too large and resisted any further pullbacks before
the final status talks begin.
</P>
<P>
Husseini said Israel's policy at this stage aims to encircle
Jerusalem with settlements that would isolate the holy city from
the West Bank, adding that "confrontations will not cease so long
as the Israeli occupation continues."
</P>
<P>
Husseini was hit on the head and slightly injured on Monday in
clashes between Jewish settlers and the protesting Palestinian and
Israeli peace activists in a village near the Old City of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Several Israeli settlers stormed four houses in the Silwan
neighborhood in East Jerusalem Sunday night and claimed they had
bought them from their Arab owners.
</P>
<P>
Israeli peace activists say 16 Jewish families have moved into
Silwan, home to 30,000 Palestinians over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March
last year over the construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
