<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Summit Urges Nigeria's New Leader to Pursue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) Tuesday called on Nigeria's new head of state
General Abdusalam Abubakar to pursue democracy in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here, the OAU summit participants
appealed to "General Abubakar, the Nigerian government and people
of Nigeria to do all in their power to maintain peace and
security nationwide, strive to achieve democracy as a nation and
also uphold the unity and integrity of their great country."
</P>
<P>
"It is a challenge that all Nigerians should rise to," the
release said.
</P>
<P>
The African leaders paid tribute to the late head of state
General Sani Abacha who reportedly died early Monday of a hear
attack.
</P>
<P>
They received the news of the sudden passing away of Abacha
with "great shock and deep sorrow," the release said.
</P>
<P>
The OAU summit called General Abacha as "a true Pan-Africanist
who worked tirelessly for the dignity and security of the entire
continent of Africa and who will be remembered for the energy and
resources that he committed toward the restoration of stability
in the west Africa sub-region."
</P>
<P>
Nigerian-led troops helped restore the legitimate government
of Tejan Kabbah in Sierra Leone in March after ending the civil
war in Liberia and helping elect a government in the country last
year.
</P>
<P>
The African leaders praised Abacha for his bold initiative of
launching the process of transition aimed at restoring democratic
governance to Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
