<HEADLINE> Hussein Leaves for U.S. to Meet Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan left here
Tuesday for the United States to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Mideast peace process
and bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The king will discuss with Clinton and other
U.S. administration officials on bilateral relations, ways of
promoting them as well as the latest developments in the Middle
East peace process, especially those on the Palestinian-Israeli
track, Jordan's official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This is Hussein's second official visit to the U.S. this year
to seek ways of enhancing bilateral ties and saving the
long-stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
His visit comes two days after Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai arrived in Amman to brief him on the Israeli
government's latest ideas about a U.S. proposal aimed at
restoring the peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. peace plan calls on Israel to hand over 13 per cent
more of the West Bank to the Palestinian National Authority in
tandem with specific Palestinian security measures to be
monitored by the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Hussein paid his first official visit to the U.S. this year
on March 12. 
