<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian President Dissolves Electoral Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President Bakili Muluzi
has dissolved the country's electoral commission to "pave way for
the appointment of a new commission for next year's presidential
and parliamentary elections."
</P>
<P>
However, Monday's premature dissolution of the commission
appointed in September 1994 whose term was expected to expire in
September 1998 has received mixed reactions from other corners,
the Malawi News Agency MANA reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The dissolution was timely as it will "give the new commission
enough time to prepare for next year's general elections," MANA
quoted a government spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the electoral commission's chairperson, Justice Anastazia
Msosa and her members have challenged the dissolution as
"unconstitutional and can spark a constitutional crisis," MANA
reported, in a dispatch to Xinhua based here in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
"It is a surprise because the constitution does not provide
for the dissolution of either the electoral commission itself or
its members by any person or institution created by the
constitution," Msosa said.
</P>
<P>
"The commissioners can only be removed by the president on
recommendations of parliament's public appointments committee for
incompetence of incapacity or its members automatically leave
office after a four-year term," she noted.
</P>
<P>
The chairperson said that before the expiry of a four-year
term of office, nobody has powers to dissolve it unless the
procedures provided by the constitution are complied with.
</P>
<P>
Msosa has put her foot down that following the constitution's
provision, her commission will continue in office until the
expiry of the term.
</P>
<P>
"We view the step taken by the government as an interference
in the work of the commission and has serious consequences on the
independence of the electoral commission and the future of
democracy in Malawi," she added.
</P>
<P>
One of the commissioners, Charles Joya, said it is also wrong
for the president just to dissolve the commission unilaterally
without consultation with other stake-holders.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to consult because everyone has his own
interpretation of the constitution. Therefore, if the president
never consulted with the other players in the electoral process,
it could spark a constitutional crisis," said Joya, apparently
referring to consultation with leaders in opposition.
</P>
<P>
However, in another interpretation, the country's main
opposition Malawi Congress Party (MCP) has welcomed the
dissolution as "it has cleared the way for stamping out
fraudulent electoral process."
</P>
<P>
The MCP and second largest opposition in parliament, Alliance
for Democracy (AFORD) have on many occasions attacked the
commission for allegedly allowing fraudulent acts by the ruling
United Democratic Front (UDF) during by-elections.
</P>
<P>
"This commission had been toothless, standing aside and
watching while electoral fraud was taking place right in their
face. We can only hope that they will not come back or be placed
by another toothless lot," said MCP President Gwanda Chakuamby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
