<HEADLINE> Hemingway Movie to Be Shot in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A film on late American writer
Ernest Hemingway is set to be produced in Kenya later this year,
Sergio Dow, a Colombian film director, told Xinhua Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The film, entitled "Hemingway: Hunter of Death," is based on a
novel by an Afro-Colombian writer and anthropologist Manuel
Zapata Olivella.
</P>
<P>
Hemingway spent some of his early life in Kenya in 1930s, said
Dow.
</P>
<P>
The story's narrative includes episode derived from Kikuyu (a
tribe in Kenya) legends, said co-producer Charles Simpson, chief
of the Film Studios Ltd., the largest Kenyan firm of this kind.
</P>
<P>
The film, which will also show Kenya's game parks and
wildlife, is estimated to be made on a cost of 10 million U.S.
Dollars, said Simpson.
</P>
<P>
It will also be the first ever film co-produced by Kenya and
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
British actor Albert Finney, who starred in the films "Tom
Jones" and "Under the Volcano", has been picked for the leading
role.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has issued 428 filming licenses in the
past two years to boost local film industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
