<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Stock Market in Downturn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's stock market, the second
largest in Africa, took a knock Tuesday with the key industrial
index shedding 40 points to close at 7,607 in its first fall in
two weeks, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The market had been active for the past two weeks buoyed by
impressive corporate results posted by some of bourse's leading
counters.
</P>
<P>
Last week's release by the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
of the first tranche of a 176-million-U.S.-Dollar balance of
payment credit facility further shored up investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said Tuesday's plunge was precipitated by
doubts, among foreign investors, on the ability of the government
to secure the remaining tranches of the aid.
</P>
<P>
"The market had responded positively to the IMF decision and
the good results achieved by some counters but now there is a
realization in the market that the government might fail to
secure the remaining money because the targets tied to the aid
are too stringent," said one analyst.
</P>
<P>
The targets include reducing the budget deficit, currently
hovering above 10 percent of gross domestic product, to about
five percent and inflation to around 18 percent by the end of the
year from current 26.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
"There is also a realization that the IMF money will not solve
our problems and this has put a dent on investor sentiment," the
analyst said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
