<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Bangladeshi Opposition Soften Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's opposition softened
their stance on a peace accord between the government and tribal
rebels before its planned "long march" toward the country's
southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts which started here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We also favor peace accord... but the one signed (between the
government and the tribals) contains some unconstitutional
provisions which require amendments," Begum Khaleda Zia,
chairperson of the major opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party
and leader of the opposition in the parliament, said at a press
conference here recently.
</P>
<P>
The party would amend the "unconstitutional" provisions in the
accord if it comes to power, she added.
</P>
<P>
Since it was concluded in December last year, the treaty has
been under fierce attack from the BNP-led seven-party opposition
alliance.  The alliance has staged various protests, such as
demonstrations, rallies, public meetings and even fasting, to urge
the government to repeal the treaty, on the ground that the accord
"violated the constitution" and "ignored the interest of the
nation."
</P>
<P>
"The (ruling) Awami League acted in haste and... sacrificed
vital national interests," a senior BNP official said.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the protests by the opposition, the Jatiya Sangsad,
the country's parliament, passed four bills in early May giving
legal effect to the treaty in the absence of the BNP, the major
opposition party.
</P>
<P>
It was against such a background that the opposition called the
"long march," which "would represent a strong and unequivocal
protest against the... accord and the passing of the four acts to
implement the accord" and "help provide an awareness" in people's
mind of their "great harm," according to M.M. Rezaul Karim, member
of the Advisory Council of the BNP.
</P>
<P>
The long march is the climax of the opposition's reaction to
the treaty and its softened stance represents a strategic change
on the part of the opposition, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the treaty has in reality put an end to the
decades-long armed conflict in the hill tracts and hence has been
lauded widely both at home and abroad, although the opposition
accused the government of negotiating the treaty with the Chakma
tribe only and ignoring the Bengali community and other tribes in
the region.
</P>
<P>
And with President Shahabuddin Ahmed signing the bills into law
in late May and the Awami League in power, which has claimed the
treaty as one of its major achievements since coming to power in
June 1996, it seems impractical and impossible for the opposition
to have the treaty scrapped, according to the analysts.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to build a peace-loving image and gain more
support from the public, the opposition would probably resort to
legal actions instead of political ones in regard to the treaty
after the long march, they pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The analysts, however, did not rule out the possibility of
escalating confrontation between the ruling party and the
opposition after the long march, if the procession was blocked and
violent conflicts occurred, which they said might then make the
political situation in the country uncertain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Road Construction Ensures Security: Museveni </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
said Tuesday that poor infrastructure is the key factor leading
to insecurity in northern districts.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the function marking the country's
ninth Heroes' Day at an airstrip here.
</P>
<P>
"In the district of Gulu and Kitgum, the army is not fighting
with the bandits. They are fighting more with the delay, the
bush. The bush is the real enemy,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
Constructing roads would be the only way to ensure security in
those areas, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he had talked with ministers concerned and local
officials about this problem and they promised to repair old
roads and build new ones so that the civilians would be safe from
attacks by rebels.
</P>
<P>
Rebels of Joseph Kony's Lord Resistance Army made frequent
abductions and robberies in these areas recently. The government
ordered a heavy deployment of army to counterattack the rebel
activities.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the rebels, who came from Sudan to get more
supplies, used land mines against civilian vehicles, making the
few roads there nearly impassable.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Ugandans Tuesday marked their ninth Heroes' Day
with various activities in memory of those who sacrificed their
lives or made tremendous contributions to the country's peace and
development.
</P>
<P>
In a short speech, Museveni called on all Ugandans to
contribute to the realization of peace and development of the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
He assured Ugandans that the government will overcome its
weaknesses and do everything possible to achieve its goals.
</P>
<P>
At a recent donors' conference in Arusha of northern Tanzania,
Uganda had reportedly won western donors' trust with a detailed
plan for construction of main and feeder roads as well as its
booming economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
