<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balkan Nations Call for Peaceful Settlement to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the Balkan
countries announced Tuesday that the Kosovo issue, which has
caused serious concern in the region, has to be settled through
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
In an official statement issued at the end of the two-day
Balkan Foreign Ministerial Meeting here, the foreign ministers
strongly emphasized the need for resumption of the dialog between
Belgrade and the representatives of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"Ministers condemned the escalation of the violence, terrorism
and excessive use of force which costs human lives and
suffering," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"They agreed that the consequences of the problem remaining
unresolved could have very negative impact to the process of the
integration of Southeastern Europe and to the peace and stability
of the region," it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it quoted Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin
Jovanovic as saying that the Kosovo issue is an internal issue of
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, which is subject to internal,
direct and unconditional dialog within the country.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a Xinhua question earlier Tuesday, Jovanovic
said that Belgrade is opposed to any form of foreign military
interference in Kosovo because this issue should be solved
through domestic channels.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from Albania, Macedonia, Bulgaria, Romania as
well as Turkey attended the meeting on the situation of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The ministers expressed their deep concern over the rapid
deterioration of the situation in Kosovo and reiterated their
full support to the call of the U.N. Security Council for
immediate cease of excessive use of force against civilian
population.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo issue has been worsening since last February when
bloody clashes erupted between Serbian police and ethnic Albanians
who demand independence from Belgrade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
