<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mass Food Distribution Starts in N.W. Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) said here Tuesday that it has begun an emergency
food distribution for more than 100,000 internally displaced
Rwandans in the northwest of the tiny Great Lakes state.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,200 tons of food will be handed out in the
prefectures of Gisenyi and Ruhengeri in the next two months, said
the WFP in a newsletter available here.
</P>
<P>
In Gisenyi, distribution of 200 tons of food began last week
toward 25,000 people in four communes.
</P>
<P>
The WFP said that heavy insecurity, including frequent rebel
incursions, has plagued much of northwestern Rwanda for nearly
six months, displacing many local people.
</P>
<P>
As a result, WFP and other aid agencies have had only partial
and periodic access to the two prefectures, limiting the amount
of humanitarian assistance that could be sent in, according to
the newsletter.
</P>
<P>
"Up to now, we've only been able to bring in small amounts of
relief food to a few areas," said Gerard Van Dijk, WFP's Country
Director for Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"Now we hope to reach more remote villages where reports
indicate that displaced people are in urgent need of our help,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
With virtually no access to land for cultivation, and little
money, if any, to buy some of the few foods available in local
markets, the nutritional status of many Rwandans is deteriorating
to alarming levels, he warned.
</P>
<P>
"What's absolutely tragic is that this part of Rwanda has
traditionally been self-sufficient, and at times even produced
surpluses which were sent to other parts of the country," said
Dijk.
</P>
<P>
"But with all the fighting, people have lost their ability to
cultivate, turning a once productive population into food aid
recipients," he continued.
</P>
<P>
WFP now is transporting all its supplies to the insecure
region under military escort.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, while Rwanda was still trying to cope with the
aftermath of the genocide and the return of more than 1.2 million
refugees into the country, WFP provided food aid to an average of
750,000 Rwandans each month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
