<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Returns Home After Bonn Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
returned to Moscow Tuesday after a two-day visit to Germany that
covered economic cooperation, nuclear proliferation and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Yastrzhembsky, Yeltsin's press secretary, told reporters
in Bonn that the visit was a complete success.
</P>
<P>
During the trip, Yeltsin won firm support for Russia's economic
reforms from German Chancellor Helmut Kohl in the wake of the
financial crisis that hit Russia late last month.
</P>
<P>
"Chancellor Kohl's personal support, as a major political
figure in the world, is important that our policies are right,"
Yeltsin told a joint press conference in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Kohl praised the steps taken by Moscow to stem
the downturn. "These measures contribute significantly to
increasing the confidence of foreign investors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo was high up on the agenda during their talks on
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, who was among the seven
government ministers in Yeltsin's entourage, stressed that under
no circumstances would Moscow sanction the sending of NATO forces
to Kosovo for the stabilization of the situation in the Yugoslav
region.
</P>
<P>
He said only the United Nations has a right to decide on an
operation of international peacekeeping forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Asia following the nuclear tests by India
and Pakistan, Yeltsin and Kohl urged New Delhi and Islamabad to
immediately join the treaties on nuclear non-proliferation and on
the comprehensive ban on nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
A number of agreements were signed in the framework of the
enlarged Russian-German summit consultations.
</P>
<P>
The two country's interior ministries agreed to work together
to fight the rampant car thefts and organized criminal syndicates.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed Tuesday in Bonn, Russia and Germany
will sign a contract in the autumn for the supply of 1.2 tons of
highly-enriched uranium to Germany for the Munich-2 experimental
reactor.
</P>
<P>
Germany is Russia's largest trading partner. Bilateral trade
last year reached 32 billion German marks (about 17.7 billion U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
