<HEADLINE> U.S. Still Hopeful for Reviving Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States is still hopeful
that the Mideast peace process can be revived despite the
protracted stalemate, a senior Egyptian official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Osama el Baz, political advisor to President Hosni Mubarak,
made the remarks after visiting U.S. Assistant Secretary of State
for Near East Affairs Martin Indyk briefed Mubarak on the
U.S. efforts to break the 15-month-old deadlock in the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Washington peace initiative, which called for a 13 percent
Israeli second stage withdrawal from the West Bank, has been
rejected by the Israeli government led by Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Indyk, a former U.S. Ambassador to Israel, came here as part of
U.S. efforts in keeping the Egyptian leader updated with the
latest developments of the situation, Baz said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the U.S. plan of actions in the
coming two weeks, not only on the Palestinian peace track but the
other tracks as well, he added.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear the U.S. administration is determined to pursue
its peace efforts, and is not losing hope on prospects of
activating the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Washington is convinced that the process has not reached a dead
end, Baz said, adding that "what we hear from them is that they
believe it is their duty to exert greater efforts in the coming
phase."
</P>
<P>
Baz denied that Indyk had asked the Egyptian side to convey a
specific message to the Palestinian side. "Cairo has sought to
propel the Mideast peacemaking and secure its success," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a strong advocate of the Palestinian cause and the first
Arab country that made peace with Israel, has been playing an
important role in mediating the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Indyk, who arrived here early Tuesday, later met with Egyptian
Assistant Foreign Minister Ahmed Abul Gheit. U.S. Ambassador to
Egypt Daniel Kurtzer also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Despite the U.S. efforts in forging an agreement on the second
redeployment, the Israelis and Palestinians are still not on the
verge of a breakthrough. Israeli Cabinet discussed the
redeployment issue on Sunday, but no decision was made.
</P>
<P>
While there are signs that Israel is closer to endorsing the
U.S. plan on a 13 percent pullback in the second redeployment, a
new dispute over the third redeployment seemed to have prevented
the Israelis and Palestinians from finalizing a deal.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is proposing for an additional 2 percent withdrawal
in the third redeployment, which has been rejected by the
Palestinians as too marginal to be accepted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
