<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Repatriate 6,000 Iraqi Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran will repatriate some 6,000
Iraqi refugees under the supervision of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) in the current Iranian year
(started March 21), an Iranian official announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, director
of the expatriates and foreign nationals department of the
northwestern province of West Azerbaijan Mehdi Abtahi said that
the refugees have requested to return home.
</P>
<P>
He said that of the total, some 3,500 refugees would be
repatriated from his province and the remaining from other parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The province now houses 25,000 Iraqi Kurdish refugees, of whom
15,000 are staying at "guest towns" (refugee camps) and the rest
in rural and urban areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Abtahi said that in the current Iranian year 1,200 Iraqi
Kurdish refugees have returned home while a total of 4,300
refugees returned to Iraq last Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
Some 580,000 Iraqi refugees, from the Kurdish in the north and
the Shiite Muslims in the south, took shelter in Iran after the
Gulf war in 1991. With the return of calm to Iraq and easing of
tension, more than 550,000 Iraqi refugees have returned home.
</P>
<P>
Abtahi said that the Iraqi Kurdish refugees have been lodged in
five "guest towns" equipped with health and educational facilities
in the cities of Orumiyeh, Piranshahr, Sardasht and Khoy of the
province, which has a border line of about 2,000 kilometers with
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
With respect to the lengthy settlement of Iraqi refugees in
the province, he said, so far 50,000 children have attended
educational courses at various levels while 15,000 adults
attended literacy movement classes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
