<HEADLINE> Clinton Pledges to Support South Korean Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton Tuesday
affirmed U.S. support for South Korea's economic reforms and
efforts for better relations with the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony to welcome South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung at the South Lawn, Clinton said, "America strongly
supports the economic reforms President Kim is pursuing, opening
markets, making financial institutions, businesses and government
more accountable."
</P>
<P>
Kim, who started his nine-day visit to the United States last
Saturday, is seeking U.S. investment to boost his country's
economy which is troubled with the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
But he has also another major issue in his mind -- to urge
Washington to loosen sanctions against the DPRK, which he sees as
a new approach for security and stability on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
To the appeal, Clinton reacted to say that his administration
supports "South Korea's efforts to find common ground with North
Korea." But he also put stress on the four-party negotiations,
which comprise two Koreas, China and the United States, "to build
a permanent peace" on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Kim, in his reply to Clinton's welcome, stressed engagement
with the DPRK to "promote reconciliation and cooperation while
maintaining a strong security posture and coordinating our North
Korean policy with the United States."
</P>
<P>
"I believe U.S. cooperation is crucial for the success of this
policy," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
Kim also expressed his hope that the United States would give
more help for his country to tide over the present financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Korea faces its worst economic crisis since the Korean War,
and so eyes and ears of the Korean people are focused on our
meeting today," Kim said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
