<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Calls for Netanyahu-Arafat Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Public Security Minister
Avigdor Kahalani on Tuesday urged Israeli and Palestinian leaders
to hold a summit in order to revive the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani issued the call upon his returning home from a meeting
in New York with U.S. special Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He told Israel Radio that it would be easier for all the
parties to find a way of advancing the peace talks by arranging a
meeting between Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani, leader of the centrist coalition party The Third Way,
said Ross also favors an Israeli-Palestinian summit as necessary
to achieve an agreement on the second further redeployment of
Israeli troops in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that although a solution to the second
redeployment is near, there are still gaps to be bridged.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned that the political situation in the region is
sensitive due to the long-running deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks have been stalled since Israeli started the
construction of a controversial settlement in the Arab East
Jerusalem in March last year. The outstanding obstacle blocking
the revival of the process is the dispute over Israeli further
troop pullbacks in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel has so far not formally accepted the American proposal
for a 13 percent handover of West Bank to the Palestinians in the
second redeployment, citing security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who has already endorsed the American compromise
proposal, has ruled out a summit with Netanyahu unless the latter
agrees to accept the U.S. pullback plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
