<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Grant Aid to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and the United States Tuesday
signed three agreements under which the U.S. is to grant the
kingdom 79.2 million U.S. dollars economic and development aid.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were signed by Jordanian Minister of Planning
Rima Khalaf, U.S. Ambassador to Jordan Wesley Egan and Director of
the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) in Jordan
Lewis Lucke.
</P>
<P>
Under the first agreement, the U.S. administration is to
provide 60 million dollars for the Ministry of Water and
Irrigation to upgrade the waste water management systems in the
Jordan Valley, the Red Sea port city Aqaba and the capital Amman
and improve the water supply systems in Amman and some other
selected areas, Jordan's official news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the second agreement, altogether 13.5 million
dollars will be provided to support the USAID to carry out its
initiatives in Jordan to increase "economic opportunities" for the
Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
Under the third agreement, 5.7 million dollars will be
allocated for Jordan's family planning and public health
activities.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has been in serious shortage of water. It currently
needs 4,100 million cubic meters of water per year to meet the
international water-poor country line of 1,000 cubic meters of
water consumption per capita per year.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom is also obsessed with the problem of poverty and
its whole population are in urgent need of economic opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Family planning is also a challenge for the government, for
most of the Jordanian families do not have contraception and
usually have three or more children for each couple. The
kingdom's population increased from 4.1 million in 1995 to 4.3
million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the three agreements brings the U.S. economic
assistance to the kingdom in 1998 to 81.2 million dollars. Total
U.S. aid for Jordan in this fiscal year is expected to reach 140
million dollars, according to Jordan's official news agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
