<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Deeply Concerned at Intense Fighting in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Tuesday
expressed its deep concern at the deteriorating violence in
Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo and urged international monitoring
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union said in a written statement that it
strongly condemned a new wave of ethnic cleansing in the form of
widespread house-burning and indiscriminate artillery attacks on
whole villages.
</P>
<P>
The union insisted on an immediate stop to all violent action
and called for the withdrawal of the Yugoslav special police and
army units from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to condemn," said the EU statement, "any use of
violence for political ends on either side. The European Union is
determined to play its part in stopping the flow of money and
weapons to the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA)."
</P>
<P>
"Neighboring states have a particular responsibility to ensure
that their territory is not used in support of KLA activity," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The European Union stressed that the priorities in Kosovo are
to end violence and to establish a genuine political process which
is the only viable alternative to continuing conflict.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, European Union foreign ministers, meeting in the
general affairs council, decided to ban all new European
investment in Yugoslavia to protest its use of violence in Kosovo
against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
They also decided to freeze Belgrade's state-held funds in the
15 EU member states.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers asked the Western military alliance NATO
to speed up its assessment of options for military actions in the
Balkans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
