<HEADLINE> Kuwait Ready to Cut Oil Output, Oil Minister Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Oil Minister of Kuwait Sheikh
Saud Nasser Al-Sabah said Tuesday that his country is ready to cut
its oil production in an effort to boost oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency quoted Saud as describing the move to cut
output as "a necessity dictated by the conditions of the current
market and low oil prices."
</P>
<P>
"The cut is a duty and a sacrifice the OPEC and non-OPEC oil
producing and exporting countries should make," Sheikh added.
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwait supports the cut as the world market suffers
from a surplus of oil, which has affected prices and the economies
of the oil countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is an issue of common fate between us and other oil
producing and exporting countries," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh made the remarks after a meeting with the visiting
Saudi Oil Minister Ali Al-Naimi.
</P>
<P>
Al-Naimi arrived here Tuesday as part of a Gulf tour designed
to rally support for a tripartite agreement reached last Thursday
in Amsterdam to slash oil output.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait reacted positively Saturday to the agreement involving
Saudi Arabia, Mexico and Venezuela to cut oil production by
450,000 barrels per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
