<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Reactions Greet Nigeria's New Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's new government under
General Abudusalam Abubakar has received mixed reactions at home.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the official News Agency of Nigeria in Lagos
Tuesday, former head of state General Yakubu Gowon has appealed
to Nigerians to support the new head of state.
</P>
<P>
"Let us, as Nigerians, be noble and see what we can do in
making sure that we give our new head of state the support that
he needs so that he can move this country forward and so that we
can achieve that hopeful return to democracy that we call pray
for," Gowon said.
</P>
<P>
Gowon, who led Nigeria through its 30-month civil war in the
1960s, was reportedly on his way to Kano to condole with the
family of late head of state General Sani Abacha, who died of a
heart attack early Monday.
</P>
<P>
He urged Nigerians to give Abubakar a chance, saying that "he
may have problems. He may have his own style. Let us give him a
chance to be able to do it and to do it well."
</P>
<P>
On the former leader Abacha, Gowon said that "he has done his
best. When you are in that position, it is the most uneasy place
as the saying -- the head is like a dustbin -- every sort of
rubbish is piled on him, but he got to do his best to God and
history. So let us mourn the loss of the head of state..."
</P>
<P>
Apparently on the jubilation of some people over Abacha's
death, Gowon said that "we say negative things about anyone who
has died. Let us remember that there is God Almighty who sees
and hears. He is the judge. Let us not be the judge."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, media reports quoted Nigeria's major opposition
group, the United Action for Democracy, as saying that it rejects
the appointment of General Abubakar as the new leader and plans
to go ahead with a demonstration Friday calling for the end of
military rule in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's highest ruling body, the Provisional Ruling Council,
named former Chief of Defense Staff Major-General Abubakar as
Nigeria's new leader early Tuesday morning after an emergency
meeting following the death of Abacha. It also promoted Abubakar
to the rank of a full general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
