<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Ready to Cut Oil Output, Oil Minister Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Oil Minister of Kuwait Sheikh
Saud Nasser Al-Sabah said Tuesday that his country is ready to cut
its oil production in an effort to boost oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait News Agency quoted the minister as describing the move
to cut output as "a necessity dictated by the conditions of the
current market and low oil prices."
</P>
<P>
"The cut is a duty and a sacrifice the OPEC and non-OPEC oil
producing and exporting countries should make," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwait supports the cut as the world market suffers
from a surplus of oil, which has affected prices and the economies
of the oil countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is an issue of common fate between us and other oil
producing and exporting countries," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks after a meeting with his Saudi
counterpart Ali Al-Naimi.
</P>
<P>
Al-Naimi arrived here Tuesday as part of a Gulf tour designed
to rally support for a tripartite agreement reached last Thursday
in Amsterdam to slash oil output.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait reacted positively Saturday to the agreement involving
Saudi Arabia, Mexico and Venezuela to cut oil production by
450,000 barrels per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes EU Decision on Fresh Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- An official at the Iranian Foreign
Ministry on Tuesday voiced Tehran's welcome to the decision made
by foreign ministers of the European Union (EU) to hold fresh
talks with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA quoted the unnamed
official as saying that in light of the EU bid to shift from its
former stand adopted as a result of its unfounded charges against
Iran, Iran would consider the decision and announce its views on
the time and level of the negotiators.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Iran would make its decision on the
agenda of the talks, adding that the subjects of the fresh talks
would be different from the former ones and the EU would be
informed in advance.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers said in Luxembourg on Monday that
they would start fresh talks with Iran this month. But they did
not say what to be discussed with Iran.
</P>
<P>
During the past years, the EU has blamed Iran for the death
sentence on the British writer Salman Rushdie for his
controversial novel "the Satanic Verses," Tehran's stances on
the Middle East peace process, international terrorism and
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
However, the European countries rejected Washington's call for
isolating Iran, pursuing a "critical dialogue" with Tehran in a
bid to milden the Islamic government.
</P>
<P>
Following the election of the moderate President Mohammad
Khatami last year, the EU countries were encouraged to reopen new
talks with Iran to boost cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said that the future discussion between Iran and the EU
would focus on issues consistent with the Organization of the
Islamic Conference currently chaired by Iran, the status of
Muslims in Europe and the approach of the European states toward
the cultural values of the Muslim world and the Iran-EU
cooperation in political, economic and cultural grounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
