<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Mourns Death of Abacha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles Taylor
declared a day of national mourning Tuesday to mark the death of
Nigerian leader General Sani Abacha, a report from Monrovia said.
</P>
<P>
Government offices, business houses, banks and stores shut
their doors in observation of the day, while school authorities
sent pupils home.
</P>
<P>
Taylor declared the day of mourning in a solemn radio
broadcast where he described Abacha, who reportedly died of a
heart attack early Monday, as a "champion of peace" and "a true
son of Africa."
</P>
<P>
Taylor ordered the national flag to be flown at half mast
throughout Liberia from dawn to dusk.
</P>
<P>
"We laments and mourn the untimely home-going of General
Abacha," Taylor said in his broadcast late Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, the general was a true son of Africa, who,
undoubtedly dedicated his life to the enhancement of sub-regional
(west African) peace and cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Taylor extended sympathy to Abacha's widow, Maryam and his
children with whom "my family and I spent many memorable moments,
and came to know very well."
</P>
<P>
He expressed "great sympathy with the people of Nigeria, and
especially those we are with us as relatives, friends and
partners-in-progress."
</P>
<P>
Taylor expressed his gratefulness to late General Abacha, who
as the Chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), has helped tremendously in bringing Liberia's seven
years of civil war to an end in 1997.
</P>
<P>
When the ECOWAS peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG was first
sent to Liberia in 1990 at the breakout of the civil war, it was
the troops of Taylor, a major warlord then, that gave ECOMOG the
strongest resistance.
</P>
<P>
But it is also under ECOMOG's supervision that Taylor emerged
the winner of a free and peaceful presidential election in July
1997.
</P>
<P>
Taylor told the ECOMOG troops now still in Liberia, "you have
lost a very fine commander-in-chief. You have my deepest
sympathy. You must continue to hold your heads up high, your
shoulders square and remain undaunted in the completion of your
noble task of peace-building in our sub-region."
</P>
<P>
"We shall remain indefinitely grateful for the tremendous
sacrifices that General Abacha made in restoring peace and
normalcy to our country," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
