<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Destruction of Churches in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has strongly protested to
the U.N. over the desecration of churches in the island's northern
part controlled by Turkish Cypriots, Cyprus News Agency (CNA)
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The CNA quoted a letter, addressed to U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan by Cyprus' U.N. Permanent Representative Sotos
Zackheos, as saying that two churches in northern Cyprus have
been converted into mosques and a third has been turned into
a cultural center.
</P>
<P>
The letter noted that "the repeated illegal conversions are in
violation of the 1954 Convention for the Protection of Cultural
Property in the Event of Armed Conflict and the Declaration of the
Principles of International Cultural Cooperation adopted by the
UNESCO (United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization) General Conference."
</P>
<P>
It said that "these acts are promoted by Turkey within the
framework of its expansionist plans against Cyprus and are a
further example of Ankara's complete disrespect for other
people's cultural heritage and its religious intolerance."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot diplomat underlined that these acts of destruction
are systematic and "part of a deliberate plan to obliterate the
island's religious, archaeological and historical heritage."
</P>
<P>
"Although the policy of the Government of Cyprus is to protect
and maintain all cultural, historical and religious monuments in
Cyprus, this policy is unfortunately not adhered to in the
illegally occupied areas controlled by the Turkish troops, where
my government has no control," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
aftermath of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
