<HEADLINE> "I Want to Play My Own Game," Japanese Captain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- As the World Cup just one day away,
Japanese team captain Masami Ihara vowed to played his own game in
his first World Cup appearence.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Tuesday, Ihara said:"As it's the first
time we've taken part in the World Cup, I can't imagine what the
atmosphere and the tension will be like until we play our first
matches, but I want to play my own game and not let the atmosphere
influence my Japanese style of play."
</P>
<P>
Japan, co-hosts of the 2002 World Cup finals with South Korea,
are taking part their first ever World Cup finals. They will play
their first group match against twice World Cup winners Argentina.
</P>
<P>
"Argentina are one of the best teams in the world, they are also
one of the favorites. But I'm convinced we have a chance of winning
(the match)." said Ihara.
</P>
<P>
"All our opponents in Group H are successful international teams.
Croatia are one of the best teams in Europe, Jamaica are also a good
team who probably have the same ambitions as Japan. But I will try to
believe that we can't lose against any of them." said Ihara.
</P>
<P>
Croatia and Jamaica are also the new-comers of World Cup finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
