<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot HIV Carrier Jailed for Unprotected Sex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A Cypriot man infected with the
lethal Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) was sentenced Tuesday to
one year imprisonment on charges of having unprotected sex and not
informing his sexual partners about his condition.
</P>
<P>
Andreas Nicolaou, the 28-year-old waiter in southern coastal
town of Larnaca, was found guilty of having sexual intercourse with
two women in a way that could possibly infect them with the HIV,
the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) virus, according to
the verdict of Larnaca District Court.
</P>
<P>
The court heard that Nicolaou's fiance has contracted the HIV
from him, but she has pardoned him. They had a relation before
1993, when he was tested HIV positive, and to their knowledge
they continued having unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
The second woman, a married mother of three, had unprotected
sex with the defendant twice, but she was not aware of his
disease.
</P>
<P>
The court decision stressed the social commitment of an AIDS
patient, noting that Nicolaou expressed repentance too late.
</P>
<P>
He was the third person in Cyprus charged with knowingly
passing the AIDS virus under a 50-year-old law introduced by
the island's then British colonial authorities to combat the
spread of cholera and typhoid.
</P>
<P>
Last July, the Famagusta District Court sentenced a fisherman
to 15 months in jail for negligently passing HIV to his British
lover.
</P>
<P>
In April, a 26-year-old woman, who has full-blown AIDS,
received a seven-month imprisonment after she had pleaded guilty
before the court for having unprotected sex with two young men
without informing them of her disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Action Needed to Reduce Drug Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Global action is needed to
reduce the ability of criminals to hide illegal profits from drug
trafficking, according to a U.N. report released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In its report on Financial Havens, Banking Secrecy and
Money-Laundering, the U.N. Office for Drug Control and Crime
Prevention said most money-laundering schemes involve the use of
financial havens.
</P>
<P>
Finding criminally derived incomes and assets has been made
more difficult because of the dollarization of black markets,
financial deregulation, the progress of the Euro market and the
proliferation of financial havens, the 118-page report said.
</P>
<P>
The annual turnover from drug trafficking is estimated at 400
billion U.S. dollars, but the law enforcement efforts recover only
100 million dollars to 500 million dollars each year, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report introduced anti-money-laundering proposals such as
tighter regulation of offshore banking and casinos, more efficient
exchange of financial information between countries, improved
training for financial investigators, and increased controls over
international business corporations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0056 </DOCNO>
