<HEADLINE> Pakistani PM Concludes Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif wrapped up Tuesday his three-day visit to Saudi Arabia,
during which he clarified his country's stance on nuclear tests
and the Kashmiri problem.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, who arrived in Jeddah Sunday from the United Arab
Emirates, held talks with Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz and
Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz on issues related to the
recent nuclear tests by India and Pakistan, the Kuwait News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
India exploded five nuclear devices on May 11 and 13 and
Pakistan, in response, conducted six tests two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
During his Saudi visit, Sharif also called upon the United
Nations and the international community to address the dispute of
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Kashmir is a 220,000 square-kilometer area in north of the
south Asian subcontinent, over whose sovereignty India and
Pakistan fought two wars.
</P>
<P>
Sharif stressed that once the issue is settled, Pakistan will
have no problem with India.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Sharif also sought financial aid during
his current Gulf tour after the U.S. and other countries imposed
economic sanctions on Pakistan in response to its nuclear tests.
</P>
</TEXT>
