<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandate of S. Africa's Truth Body Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's National
Assembly Tuesday passed a legislation to extend the life of the
Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC), according to Justice
Minister Dullah Omar.
</P>
<P>
The new bill will allow the TRC to submit an interim report on
October 31 this year, and enable its Amnesty Committee to conduct
more than 1,000 outstanding amnesty application hearings, South
African Press Association quoted Justice Omar as saying.
</P>
<P>
Omar introduced the bill.
</P>
<P>
After October 31, the TRC will be suspended while its Amnesty
Committee would continue to work.
</P>
<P>
Once the committee's work is complete, President Nelson
Mandela will reconvene the commission so that it can complete its
final report.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, an amendment to the original act setting up the TRC,
the Promotion of National Unity and Reconciliation Bill, extended
the life of the Amnesty Committee to June 30 this year, and set
July 31 as the date for the final report of the TRC.
</P>
<P>
The National Party, the Freedom Front and the Inkatha Freedom
Party opposed the legislation while the Democratic Party and the
Pan Africanist Congress welcomed it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Officer Sparks Debate by Slamming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Israeli Army
officer in South Lebanon sparked a heated debate in the Knesset
(Parliament) Tuesday by slamming demonstrators supporting
unilateral withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on recent protests held in Tel Aviv calling for a
unilateral pullback from Lebanon, Israeli Army's Liaison Commander
in South Lebanon Erez Gerstein on Monday strongly criticized the
demonstrators for endangering the lives of Israeli soldiers as
well as the pro-Israeli South Lebanese Army.
</P>
<P>
In their reactions, protest organizers, the Four Mothers
Movement and the Movement for a Peaceful Departure from Lebanon
(MPDL), defended their actions, saying they were just exercising
their civil rights. They demanded that the army should stay out of
political matters in a democratic society.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Army Chief of Staff Amnon Lipkin Shahak, in his final
briefing to the Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee, was
forced to reprimand Gerstein for going "out of line" to openly
criticize the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
"Israeli citizens have the legitimate rights to express their
views on all subjects," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he said he believes Gerstein was speaking out of concern
over the security of Israeli and SLA soldiers in South
Lebanon. He added that Gerstein was "an excellent officer" and he
would not be relieved from his post.
</P>
<P>
A political uproar was created in Tuesday's Knesset, where
lawmakers from the ruling and opposition camps traded blames over
Gerstein's remarks.
</P>
<P>
Ran Cohen of the opposition Meretz party said the "horrible"
remarks made by Gerstein could not be accepted by anyone who
believes in democracy. "We are not going to live in Israel while
we send our sons to the army but have no possibility to speak out
our opinions about the ways of fighting in Israel," he said.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that Gerstein should be dismissed because of his
irresponsible statements.
</P>
<P>
Labor's Knesset member and MPDL leader Yossi Beilin, joined by
his party colleagues Benjamin Ben-Eliezer, Yael Dayan and Haggai
Merom, came out in support to Cohen. They all criticized Gerstein
for violating the civilian rights.
</P>
<P>
But Uzi Landau, Chairman of the Foreign Affairs and Defense
Committee and a lawmaker of the ruling Likud party, voiced his
full support to Gerstein, although he conceded that army officers
should stay out of political affairs.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, one Labor lawmaker crossed the party line to
support Gerstein. Ephraim Sneh said that if the citizens have the
right to intervene in the army's affairs such as the security
issue, then an officer also has the right and duty to voice
concern over the security of his soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The continued debate in Israel over a unilateral withdrawal
from South Lebanon pointed to the deep division among Israeli
society over the sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the so-called South Lebanon Security Zone in 1985
after it withdrew the bulk of the 1982 invading forces from
Lebanon. The zone has since become a death trap for Israel, with
an average 35 Israeli soldiers being killed there every year in
fightings with the anti-Israeli Hezbollah (Party of God) guerrilla
forces. Six Israeli soldiers and at least nine SLA militiamen have
been killed since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
Under growing domestic pressure for a pullout, Israel's Cabinet
adopted last April the 20-year-old United Nations Resolution
425 calling for a unilateral Israeli withdrawal from South
Lebanon, but linked the pullout to a security arrangement.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanon and its powerful ally Syria rejected Israel's
conditional offer, saying the U.N. resolution demands an
unconditional withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
