<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Tuesday
that Nigeria's new leader, Gen. Abdusalam Abubakar, was capable of
leading the country on the way to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
"We generally regard him as someone who's capable of taking
this historic decision and we very much want him to do so," State
Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States was considering to revive the idea of
a diplomatic mission to Nigeria, which was called off earlier this
month because the Nigerian government said it would receive the
diplomats only if Washington lifted some visa restrictions.
</P>
<P>
"We were not prepared to meet the conditions the previous
government had set for such a meeting so the fact of a new
leadership opens the opportunity for them to permit such a mission
and that's certainly under consideration," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the White House said the United States was pleased to
see Nigeria is calm following the death of its leader Sani Abacha,
and that it hoped the country would move to civil rule.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased to see that Nigerians have reacted calmly to
the death of Abacha. And we think it's very important that Nigeria
move forward in the transition to civil rule, democratic
elections, as Nigeria has committed itself to do by October,"
White House spokesman Eric Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, 54, died of heart attack Monday and Gen. Abubakar,
chief of the defense staff, was sworn in Tuesday to succeed him.
</P>
