<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Keep Silence on Missile Issue: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- In a move to divert the attention
on its controversial plan to deploy anti-aircraft missiles,
Cypriot government said Tuesday it would no longer make comments
on the issue in the future.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a National Council meeting,
government spokesman Christos Stylianides said "the very nature of
the matter demands that the issue is kept out of the limelight."
</P>
<P>
To demonstrate this, Stylianides declined to comment on recent
reports in the Russian press that the Russian-made S-300
surface-to-air missiles have already been delivered secretly to
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Russian daily "Sevodnya" reported that the S-300s have already
been deployed on the island and more than 200 Russian
specialists were helping install them.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides' statement came following a British newspaper
report that Britain had a "contingency plan" to airlift 250,000
people from Cyprus for fears of a war if the Cypriot government
goes on with its plan to deploy the missiles later this year.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus fears that the reported British plan would adversely
affect the island's tourism and damage its economy.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government decided to purchase the Russian missiles
in January 1997, which are expected to be delivered in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided since
1974 when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern
third in the aftermath of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has kept around 40,000 troops in northern Cyprus, which
was declared unilaterally in 1983 by Turkish Cypriots as a
breakaway "Turkey Republic of Northern Cyprus" which was recognized
only by Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot-Russian missile deal was opposed by the U.S.,
Britain and some other countries. Turkey has threatened to
destroy the missiles if they are deployed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
