<HEADLINE> UNHCR-Africa Coop Successful: UN Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The cooperation between the
United Nations and Africa in trying to find durable solutions to
refugee crises in the continent has continued to be close despite
difficulties in this regard, a senior U.N. official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It is important to realize that a lot of resolutions have been
planned to the refugee problems in Africa, Sadako Ogata, U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), told a press conference
here.
</P>
<P>
Ogata is here for the current 34th summit meeting of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) as an observer.
</P>
<P>
This is the seventh times that she has attended the OAU summit
before the end of her mandate later this year.
</P>
<P>
"We have been able to carry out a very successful repatriation
exercise to Mozambique, now followed by the return of Malian
refugees from Burkina Faso and Mauritania. Togolese refugees
have also been assisted to return home and re-start life," she
said.
</P>
<P>
In sp these, there is still a serious outflow of
refugees in Africa, with the largest in Sierra Leone, where a
military coup in May last year has created social chaos in that
tiny west African country.
</P>
<P>
According to Ogata, some 230,000 new refugees have fled Sierra
Leone to neighboring Guinea and Liberia, bringing the total
number to about 530,000 since the civil war began in 1991.
</P>
<P>
She hoped that the current situation in Sierra Leone would not
be affected by the sudden death of Nigeria's Head of State
General Sani Abacha Monday morning, whose troops have led a
successful peace keeping operation in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The basic cause of Africa's refugee problems has been internal
conflict based on ethnic and tribal divisions, she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she expressed fear that the fragile peace in
countries like Liberia and Rwanda would affect the repatriation
of refugees.
</P>
<P>
On the recent escalating conflict between Ethiopia and
Eritrea, the U.N. official said she did not believe it would
produce refugees in the Horn of Africa at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
