<HEADLINE> Intel Corp to Cut Chip Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corp. is stepping up the use
of pricing as a weapon to protect its biggest business and to
expand into new markets.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday that the giant chip
maker dropped prices by 12 percent to 32 percent on its flagship
Pentium II microprocessors Monday, the third cut this year as
Intel reacts to slowing demand for personal computers and to
rivals at the low end of the market. Microprocessors act like the
heart of PCs, and Intel dominates the field with about 85 percent
of the market.
</P>
<P>
Intel is also attracting attention by slashing prices in its
newest business, chips used to display graphics on PCs.
</P>
<P>
The developments come as the Federal Trade Commission filed a
long-awaited anti-trust suit focusing on the way Intel allegedly
uses its monopoly power to bully customers into sharing their
intellectual property with Intel.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said they were more concerned with the sluggish
personal computer market, price cuts, pressures on profits and
some losses in Intel's dominant market share than with its legal
battle with the FTC, which could drag on for years.
</P>
<P>
Dataquest Inc. said Intel had 93.2 percent of the 20.1 billion
U.S. dollar market for PC microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said that Intel is really facing increased
competition and that competition is not likely to abate in the
next couple of years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
