<HEADLINE> OPIC Plans to Resume Trade Investment to S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Overseas Private
Investment Corporation (OPIC) plans to resume trade investment in
South Korea as a result of improvement of worker rights there,
administration sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was expected to be made after South Korean
President Kim Dae jung's talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton at
the White House, they said.
</P>
<P>
The OPIC, an independent government agency that helps U.S.
companies invest in emerging markets, suspended its program in
South Korea in 1991 because of its concerns over worker rights.
</P>
<P>
The agency, however, has now determined that conditions have
improved for workers in South Korea, thus clearing the way for
resumption of investment.
</P>
<P>
The OPIC provides financing of businesses through loans and
loan guarantees, insures investments against political and other
risks, and supports private investment funds.
</P>
<P>
The agency must still conclude negotiations with Seoul on a
bilateral agreement before its new program gets underway.
</P>
<P>
The White House may also announce the expansion of U.S.
Export-Import Bank support for South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The bank has been in talks with Kim's government on providing
additional financial support for U.S. export sales to South Korea,
a White House spokesman said. 
</P>
