<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Set Forth Package Proposals for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) has urged Africa to frame its economic policies and
integrate itself with globalization for a sustained economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
With market integration proceeding rapidly, Africa must open
up and compete if it is to take advantage of the benefits of the
globalization process while at the same trying to avoid the risk
of marginalization and the risk of capital flows drying up or
reversing, an IMF official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Michel Camdessus, IMF Managing Director, said this to African
leaders who are attending the 34th Summit of Heads of State and
Government of the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief set forth a package of proposals which he
thought would enable Africa to maximize the benefits of
globalization while avoiding its perils.
</P>
<P>
These include consolidating macro-economic stability, ensuring
economic security, strengthening the financial sector, speeding
up trade liberalization, fostering efficient regional economic
cooperation and integration, a good governance and a broad,
frontal attack on structural problems.
</P>
<P>
Africa must now redouble efforts to reduce inflation to
sustained low rates and ensure the viability of the external
position, he said, adding that it must also mobilize savings and
deepen financial intermediation.
</P>
<P>
It must also strengthen everything that encourages private
investment and the entrepreneurial spirit at all levels, he
stated.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, industrial countries should do more to open
their markets to products in which African countries have, or are
likely to develop, a comparative advantage.
</P>
<P>
IMF, meanwhile, will also continue to support the reform
efforts of Africa by providing more loans and moving swiftly to
implement the debt initiative for the heavily indebted poor
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism over the economic progress in Africa.
</P>
<P>
After some two decades of lost opportunities, Africa's
economic performance has improved and the outlook has brightened,
he said. Real GDP for the region as a whole is growing at 4 to 5
percent, and per capita incomes are on the rise. And more and
more African countries are partaking in the economic recovery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. GM Shuts Down 5 Assembly Plants Amidst Workers Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A strike at a General Motors
Corp. parts factory closed five assembly plants and idled about
15,000 workers Tuesday, according to an AP report.
</P>
<P>
Assembly plants in Michigan, Kansas, Ohio and Ontario were
idled because of a parts shortage caused by the strike by nearly
3,400 members of the United Auto Workers (UAW) at GM's Flint Metal
Center, north of Detroit. The plant makes hoods, fenders, doors
and other sheet-metal parts.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators representing GM and the UAW resumed talks Tuesday
on the fifth day of the Flint strike, which largely involves
disputes over work rules and staffing levels. But there was no
progress achieved in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Due to shortages of parts cut-off for a variety of GM's light
trucks and full-size cars, the five of GM's 16 plants shut down in
North America include:
</P>
<P>
-- The Orion Township plant outside Detroit, where about 2,800
hourly workers were sent home. The plant makes five full-size
cars: the Oldsmobile Eighty Eight and Aurora, Buick Riviera and
Park Avenue, and Pontiac Bonneville;
</P>
<P>
-- The Fairfax plant in Kansas City, Kan., which makes the
Pontiac Grand Prix and Oldsmobile Intrigue. The shutdown affected
2,900 workers;
</P>
<P>
-- The Moraine, Ohio, plant, where about 4,300 workers were
idled. The plant makes GM's midsize sport utility vehicles,
including the Chevrolet Blazer;
</P>
<P>
-- The plant that makes the Chevrolet Lumina and Monte Carlo at
GM's big Oshawa, Ontario, Canada, complex, where about 2,800
workers were affected;
</P>
<P>
-- The Buick City car assembly plant in Flint, where about
2,100 workers were sent home. The plant makes Buick LeSabre and
Pontiac Bonneville sedans.
</P>
<P>
The strike's effects were spreading to other parts plants as
well. GM's Delphi Interior &AMP; Lighting plant in Auburn Hills was
closed, affecting 210 workers, Delphi Automotive Systems spokesman
Ray Deibel said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
UAW officials in Flint said they also expected the Flint truck
and bus plant to close Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the UAW threatened to stage a strike at a second
parts plant in Flint Thursday if no settlement is reached. The
Delphi-Delco complex, with about 5,800 hourly workers, makes
instrument panels, spark plugs and other parts used in nearly all
GM cars and trucks.
</P>
<P>
GM's cost-cutting and plant closures over the past two decades
have resulted in the loss of about 50,000 jobs in Flint, and
workers at the Metal Center fear their jobs may be next. The Flint
plant is among the least competitive within GM, according to the
Harbor Report, an independent ranking of the efficiency of North
American auto plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-09 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE President Urges Agreement on Arab Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
Tuesday called for an agreement among Arab countries on holding a
summit with an aim to collectively meet various challenges facing
the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
The UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan made the
call at a meeting here with visiting Saudi Prince Sultan Ibn
Abdul-Aziz, second deputy prime minister and minister of defense.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Zayed voiced the hope that the proposed summit would be
held regularly and yearly with a view to "ensuring the Arab joint
action."
</P>
<P>
He called for rapprochement, solidarity and unity among all the
22 Arab countries instead of divisions and differences.
</P>
<P>
As for the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC), Sheikh Zayed said
the GCC members should exert every possible effort to support the
Arab causes and restore the solidarity of the Arab nation.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out to the necessity of "the principle of
collectiveness," rather than individualism, in dealing with the
GCC-Iran relations.
</P>
<P>
The issue of three disputed islands in the Gulf, namely, Lesser
and Greater Tunb and Abu-Musa, between the UAE and Iran is an
inseparable part of the GCC concerns that should be negotiated
with Iran, he added.
</P>
<P>
Both the UAE and Iran claim sovereignty over the islands near
the strategically important strait of Hormuz.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi prince arrived here Monday on an official visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
