<HEADLINE> UNIP Party Demands Kaunda Acquitted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian President Kenneth
Kunada's party demanded here Tuesday that Kaunda be acquited.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Legal Affairs of the United National
Independence Party (UNIP), Mwangala Zaloumis, told a press
conference that UNIP is disappointed at not acquitting its leader
Kaunda but entering nolle prosequi by the government when Kaunda
was set free on June 1.
</P>
<P>
Zaloumis, who is also Kaunda's lawyer, said the team of
Kaunda's lawyers had wanted the case to be quashed as there was
no evidence which linked their client to the October 28 failed
coup.
</P>
<P>
She said Kaunda is demanding that he should be prosecuted
because he is innocent and the government's decision to enter a
nolle prosequi is not enough.
</P>
<P>
Even if the government has released Kaunda on the spirit of
reconciliation, the nolle prosequi was done in bad faith, she
said.
</P>
<P>
UNIP is unhappy at the statement by Legal Affairs Minister
Vincent Malambo, who said last Thursday that the decision to
enter a nolle prosequi does not mean that the government has no
evidence against Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
Malambo also said that because it is not appropriate to
prosecute Kaunda, he has been freed.
</P>
<P>
Zaloumis accused the government of fabricating lies connecting
Kaunda to the coup.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was arrested on December 25 of 1997 but transferred to
under house arrest six days later following an international cry
for his immediate release or charging him.
</P>
<P>
On January 10, 1998, Kaunda was charged with conspiring with
some army officers to topple the government and one month later
he was formally charged with misprision of treason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
