<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Council Holds First Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The newly-formed governing council of
the European Central Bank (ECB) convened its meeting Tuesday at
the bank's headquarters in Frankfurt to prepare for the launch of
the single European currency, the euro, on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The council comprises the ECB's six board members as well as
the central bank chiefs of the 11 European Union states which will
join the euro in the first wave next year.
</P>
<P>
According to ECB President Wim Duisenberg, among a number of
organizational decisions made Tuesday, the council fixed the
capital participation in the ECB for each member states, with the
German central bank holding the largest stake.
</P>
<P>
Until July 1 this year, the ECB would have four billion euro in
startup capital, Duisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
The ECB meeting also made clear that the 11 national central
banks would be responsible for the supply of the first euro
banknotes. Meanwhile a special panel has already been set up to
fight forgeries.
</P>
<P>
The ECB council also decided to meet on the first Tuesday of
every month in the future. Key issues such as the minimum reserves
of the bank and which monetary instruments would be used would be
discussed in the following months.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference after the meeting, Duisenberg
said that judging from the overall monetary situation of the euro
member states, he saw no major risks for the launch of the euro.
</P>
<P>
A formal founding ceremony for the ECB is scheduled for June 30
in Frankfurt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hospital Death Rates in UK to be Made Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Patients of the state-run health
service are to have access to information about the level of death
rates in individual hospitals before going for operations, the
British government announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of Labor members of parliament, Health Secretary
Frank Dobson said people have a right to compare their local
hospital's performance with the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary clinical indicators for hospitals in England would
be published from next October as a step to boosting public
confidence in the service, he said.
</P>
<P>
The figures will show how many patients die in different
hospitals after operations, heart attacks and broken hips, and how
many suffer complications.
</P>
<P>
"Hospitals and hospital doctors need to know these figures - so
too do patients and their GPs (general practitioners)", Dobson
said.
</P>
<P>
The move followed a public outcry at the deaths of 29 babies
and children after heart operations at a hospital in Bristol, a
far higher death rate than the national average.
</P>
<P>
Dobson said doctors will also be monitored properly to improve
the standard, but patients will not see this information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
