<HEADLINE> S. Africa Unveils Free Trade Proposals to SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's proposals for
a free trade protocol in the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) within the next eight years were unveiled before
Parliament's Trade and Industry Committee Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Director of African Trade Relations in Trade and
Industry Department, Mfundo Nkhulu, told the committee that the
proposed deal would see South Africa abolish almost 80 percent of
its import tariffs within five years, while its SADC trading
partners would phase down their own tariffs more slowly.
</P>
<P>
South Africa would cut most of its tariffs by a minimum of
five percent a year, the South African Press Association quoted
him as saying Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nkhulu said that the trade offer would be placed before SADC
trade ministers at a meeting in Angola next month.
</P>
<P>
Only 10.1 percent of South Africa's total imports came from
other SADC countries, the bulk of which comprised mineral,
precious stones and metals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
