<HEADLINE> Britain to Probe N.Irish Document Leaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The British government was
consulting the Northern Ireland police force on Tuesday about the
latest in a series of leaks from the Northern Ireland office.
</P>
<P>
The leak revealed that Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam
contacted through telephone with a Dublin-based Sinn Fein member
who had been wanted by police for questioning for serious
guerrilla offense. It also revealed divisions between Britain and
Ireland over the composition of an advisory commission on the
province's policing.
</P>
<P>
It was the second such incident in three months, and Mowlam
said "every effort would be made to discover who leaked the
document" to the media.
</P>
<P>
Irish nationalist politicians feared the document, which was
quoted in media reports, was the work of a civil servant opposed
to the peace deal hammered out by rival groups in April.
</P>
<P>
Irish Foreign Minister David Andrews said the peace deal
remained in good shape despite the leak.
</P>
<P>
"It would appear certainly that the leaker or leakers are
opposed to the peace process. They should really examine their
consciences... whoever they are," he was quoted by BBC as saying
in Dublin, the Irish capital.
</P>
<P>
"Sneaky little people in the Northern Ireland Office are not
going to obstruct us in the pursuit of what we all seek to achieve
- a permanent peace on the island of Ireland."
</P>
<P>
Gerry Adams, leader of Sinn Fein, the political arm of the
Irish Republican Army, said the Northern Ireland civil service
needed to be "shaken up".
</P>
<P>
The leak showed that "the people who have run this place for
over 25 years are resisting change," he said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
