<HEADLINE> Africa's Economic Recovery Fragile: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The African Development Bank
(ADB) Tuesday warned that the economic growth in Africa over the
past few years was still not strong enough to reduce poverty in
the continent.
</P>
<P>
The efficiency of investment to Africa must also be improved
in poverty alleviation, ADB President Omar Kabbaj stated at the
current summit meeting of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU).
</P>
<P>
The average growth rate of near five percent achieved by
African countries in recent years is fragile and vulnerable to
the problems in Africa, he noted.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the origin of Africa's economic problems and
a major factor for the fragility of its current recovery can be
traced to the continent's policy weakness, adverse economic
development (both domestic and foreign), and political
uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
"Consequently, if Africa is to restore lasting stability,
reinforce growth and sustain confidence in the continent's
ability to take its rightful place in the world economy, it must
continue to take firm and consistent policy actions to address
the root causes of its problems and spur additional domestic and
foreign investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Because of the multidimensional nature of these problems, no
one and single policy action or measure will be sufficient as a
solution, the ADB president said.
</P>
<P>
He therefore called for an overall framework within which to
address all these problems in tandem and stimulate investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
