<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Contribute to Poverty Reduction in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, june 9 (xinhua) -- The African Development Bank
(ADB) pledged here Tuesday to continue to focus its interventions
on activities that contribute to poverty reduction in Africa in
the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
The bank will continue to direct its financial and technical
assistance to the regional member countries in areas such as
strengthening production capacity and promoting policy reforms,
said ADB President Omar Kabbaj.
</P>
<P>
The areas also cover facilitating economic cooperation and
regional integration and promoting private sector development and
investment, he told the current summit meeting of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
According to him, up to 45 percent of the African population
now live in absolute poverty and seriously lag behind those in
other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Current estimate indicates that Africa needs to achieve a
sustained level of economic growth at about 8-10 percent a year
to arrest and reverse the spread of poverty.
</P>
<P>
For the effort to reduce poverty, Kabbaj said, one important
financial instrument that needs to be developed further is that
of micro-finance for the poor.
</P>
<P>
With a view to contributing to such an effort, ADB is to
launch a pilot program which aims at increasing access to credit
and financial services for micro-entrepreneurs from Africa,
especially women.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, an amount of 20 million U.S.
Dollars of concessional resources has been earmarked to support
the initiative.
</P>
<P>
The bank also gives high priority to the central role of the
private sector in respect of attaining sustainable economic
growth in the continent, he said.
</P>
<P>
To support the development of the private sector, ADB created
a full-fledged department within it last year and adopted a new
strategy which would allow the bank to offer a wide range of
services to its member countries.
</P>
<P>
Since it started its private sector operations in 1991, the
bank has approved 33 private sector projects consisting of loans
and equity participations totaling nearly 130 million U.S.
Dollars, Kabbaj disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
