<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Trade Volume Shows Slower Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade volume
increased from January to May, but the growth momentum was
sluggish.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics from Customs, the total
value of imports and exports in the first five months of this year
reached 123.69 billion U.S. dollars, a rise of 5.4 percent over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of exports reached 71.11 billion U.S. dollars,
increasing by 8.6 percent; while the value of imports reached
52.58 billion U.S. dollars, growing by 1.5 percent. China's trade
surplus was 18.53 billion U.S. dollars, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The volume of exports gradually declined after February. The
value of export and import declined by 1.5 percent and 3.8 percent
respectively in May if being compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to customs analysis, Asia financial crisis has
gradually begun to affect China's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign-oriented enterprises in the country tried to
expand their business in Africa and Latin America. The United
States replaced the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region to
become the second largest trade partner of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
