<HEADLINE> Annan, Hasina Offer to Mediate Between India, Pak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan and Bangladesh Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina Wednesday
offered to play a mediating role in improving the hostile
relationship between Pakistan and India, officials here said.
</P>
<P>
Annan and Hasina made the offer in their separate telephone
talk with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on Wednesday,
according to officials from the Prime Minister's House.
</P>
<P>
Annan told Sharif that he is sending his special envoy shortly
to both India and Pakistan for talks on all the contentious issues
including Kashmir between the two South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
He said his envoy's visit is to pave the way for his own tour
of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
While expressing gratitude to the U.N. Secretary General,
Sharif said the U.N. can play a very positive role in solving the
Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
He requested Annan to increase international pressure on India
and help get the U.N. resolutions on Kashmir implemented.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh prime minister Hasina informed Sharif of her call
that she is willing to undertake a visit to Pakistan and to play a
role in solving the disputes including Kashmir between Pakistan
and India.
</P>
<P>
She said South Asia is very poor and the region cannot afford a
nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
Sharif welcomed her offer and assured his full cooperation in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that India's provocative nuclear tests had
totally altered the strategic balance in the region and Pakistan
had to correct the imbalance by detonating its own nuclear
devices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
