<HEADLINE> Transition Date Remains Valid: Nigerian Senior </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The October 1 date for the military
government to handover to an elected civilian one remains valid,
a member of Nigeria's Provisional Ruling Council (PRC), the
country's highest ruling body, has said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters Tuesday in Abuja after a joint meeting
of the PRC and the Council of States, Air-Vice-Marshal Mohammed
Alfa said the meeting had discussed the transition to civil rule
program announced by late head of state, General Sani Abacha in
October 1995.
</P>
<P>
"One thing we made categorically clear is that the (new)
administration is going to abide by the October 1 handing over
date," he said.
</P>
<P>
Alfa said," We have also resolved to carry on with those
aspects of the policies of the late head of state, particularly
as regards the transition program so that it will succeed."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the August 1 date for presidential and state governor
elections will remain unchanged, he said, "That is still under
discussion. It is something I will not comment on now."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's new leader, General Abdulsalam Abubakar said Tuesday
night that his government will continue to implement the
transition program, but he did not say if the October 1 date
still remains.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's five political parties registered under Abacha's
transition program adopted the late general as their consensus
presidential candidate in April.
</P>
<P>
With less than two months to the election now without any
candidate, there have been wide concern if the transition program
will be adhered to by the new government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
