<HEADLINE> Former Bank Vice-President Sentenced for Taking Bribes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The former vice-president of the
Bank of Communications (BOC), Lu Jiashan, 63, was sentenced to
three years in jail, with three year' reprieve by the Intermediate
People's Court of Shanghai Municipality for taking 90,800 yuan in
bribes.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the Supreme People's Court available
today, Lu took 54,000 yuan in bribes from the manager of a
vegetable oil factory based in Wujiang, a city in east China's
Jiangsu Province, while acting as the vice-president of the BOC
Shanghai branch and president of BOC in May of 1990 through
November of 1992,.
</P>
<P>
Lu then opened an account for the factory at the BOC Shanghai
branch and helped the manager to borrow from BOC's sub-branch in
Wujiang.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, while as the vice-president of BOC in December of
1994, Lu accepted 36,800 yuan worth of gifts from the general
manager of a Shanghai-based investment company and then helped the
company to obtain loans from the BOC Pudong branch based in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Because Lu surrendered to the judicial department and returned
the bribes, the court made a lenient verdict which Lu did not
appeal to a higher court.  
</P>
</TEXT>
