<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reformed State Enterprises Warned of Debt Responsibilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China's highest governing body,
the State Council, has issued a circular prohibiting state-owned
and collective enterprises from shirking their debts as their
operating mechanism is reformed.
</P>
<P>
The circular states that the evasion of debts by some
medium-sized and small state-owned and collective enterprises has
seriously undermined credit relations, resulting in nominal
creditor's rights in financial institutions and the loss of state
assets.
</P>
<P>
Local governments are urged to proceed from overall national
interests and intensify the guidance and supervision on the
shifting of operating mechanisms in such enterprises.
</P>
<P>
As long as there is not a proper overseer of the debts,
relevant government units cannot approve reforms in the
enterprises or give new business licenses to them. The reformed
enterprises which have evaded debts must once again establish a
correct creditor-debtor relationship, according to the circular.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, financial institutions should take an active
part in supervising asset assessments in the enterprises which
undergo reform. And the institutions should regularly report
matters concerning creditor's rights to the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
The reform of the enterprises must go through strict assessment
of their assets, and the outcome of that assessment must be
confirmed by the government departments in charge of the
management of state assets.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China and its local branches should also
work together with local governments to take effective measures to
supervise the situation of the creditor's rights, the circular
says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Killed in Montreal Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Two people were killed and at least
15 others injured in a gas explosion which occurred Tuesday at a
soup kitchen for the homeless in Montreal, reports said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier report said that five people were severely injured and
about 25 others had minor injuries when the blast ripped the front
off the three-story building in Montreal's historic old port.
</P>
<P>
The natural gas leak was caused by a private subcontractor, who
accidentally sawed through a gas line as he was cutting through a
wall at the front of the building to change the gas meter.
</P>
<P>
Fire-fighting officials said the explosion was probably set off
by an electrical spark.
</P>
<P>
By late Tuesday, searchers had accounted for all except one of
the center's workers, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Officials said a worst catastrophe was narrowly averted, since
hundreds of homeless who visit the building for a lunchtime meal
had drifted off before the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Almost all those injured were employees and volunteers of the
soup kitchen, most of them elderly, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
