<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auto Industry Should Consolidate, TRW President Says (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China's automobile industry has
yet to form several large companies to increase its
competitiveness, said Peter Hellman, president and chief operating
officer of TRW, North America's largest automotive supplier.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua during a visit here, Hellman
said that China has too many small automobile manufacturers
that are unable to cut costs and improve efficiency in an
effective way.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 120 automotive manufacturers and more
than 600 refitting factories. The total automobile output of the
country was only 1.5 million in 1997, less than that of a single
car plant in Japan.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, Chinese and foreign investors spent 58
billion yuan on these automobile manufacturers. However, these
enterprises have yet to meet the demands of the domestic market in
terms of product development, technology, performance, quality and
product structure.
</P>
<P>
Hellman said that the automotive industry is undergoing a
global trend toward mergers. Since the world automotive industry
has a redundant capacity of over 18 million automobiles, only the
largest companies can make the most efficient use of resources and
survive intense competition.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Daimler-Benz and Chrysler formed a
130-billion-U.S.-dollar automotive company, the third largest in
the world. Competition has intensified among automotive giants
from the United States, Europe and Japan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hellman said that it has been proved that scale is the key
factor for the efficiency of automotive companies.
</P>
<P>
TRW is the fourth largest automotive supplier in the world,
with annual sales of 12 billion U.S. dollars. It has production
and service companies in 23 countries and regions around the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that, at present, every newly produced car in the world
has 150 U.S. dollars worth of components and parts from TRW. As an
independent supplier, it will schedule production according to the
total demands of the world market. Therefore, the company's
efficiency will not be affected by changes in any single customer
or any specific market, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
