<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auto Industry Should Consolidate, TRW President Says (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, he pointed out that almost all Chinese automotive
manufacturers run their own specific component suppliers. They
could not achieve the economic efficiency that large
companies have, he said.
</P>
<P>
TRW is ready to help China's automotive industry form its own
independent, large component suppliers, a move that Hellman
said will be mutually beneficial.
</P>
<P>
TRW has already set up four joint venture plants in China.
</P>
<P>
Hellman said that if TRW reached its global average sales level
in China, the company would have an annual revenue of 22 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said China's automotive industry should accelerate its pace
of integration.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has already formulated the strategy of
forming five major automotive groups, each of them having an annual
capacity of 200,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Automotive Industry Group, Changchun No.1 Automotive
Group, Dongfeng automotive Company, Shanghai Volkswagen Automotive
Company and Tianjin Automotive Company have become the forerunners
in the process of integration.
</P>
<P>
The top 14 Chinese automotive companies account for more than
90 percent of the country's total output. Each of them has an
annual production capacity larger than 10,000 automobiles.
</P>
<P>
Hellman said that Chinese companies should focus resources on
certain specific products to attain market advantages.
</P>
<P>
He said that TRW is a leading producer of occupant restraint
systems and steering wheels, steering and suspension systems,
engine components, safety, security and convenience electronics,
engineered fasteners and fastening systems in the world. These TRW
products occupy 30 to 40 percent of the world market. TRW accounts
for around 17 percent of the world automotive component market.
</P>
<P>
He said that the global wave of mergers in the automotive
industry will affect China sooner or later. Some of TRW's major
customers such as GM, Chrysler, Volkswagen and Ford have already
entered the China market.
</P>
<P>
Hellman said he hopes that Chinese automotive companies will be
prepared for the pending challenge of international competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
