<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Raises Set-Aside Rate for 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union, decided on Wednesday to
raise the obligatory set-aside rate for the 1999-2000 marketing
year to ensure market balance.
</P>
<P>
The set-aside rate for arable land was raised five percentage
points to 10 percent for the designated period.
</P>
<P>
The commission made the decision unanimously after taking into
account the market outlook in the short term and the conclusion
that there is a serious danger of intervention stocks for
cereals increasing again to unacceptable levels.
</P>
<P>
The rise of the set-aside rate will increase the area set aside
(compulsory and voluntary) by 1.5 million hectares and to reduce
production by 8 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Franz Fischler, European commissioner in charge of agriculture,
said: "Set-aside is a market management instrument whose level
must be adjusted in either direction to ensure market balance and
stability."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner estimated that without raising the set-aside
rate, the European Union could have 30 million tons in
intervention by the end of the 1999-2000 marketing year.
</P>
<P>
Producers of certain crops in the European Union countries can
benefit from a per-hectare compensatory payment provided they
withdraw a certain percentage of land from production for which
they receive a payment of 68.83 ECU per ton of crops.
</P>
<P>
Producers may also set aside land on a voluntary basis. In
fact, 50 percent of the 4 million hectares set aside for the
1997-1998 marketing year was done so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Military Expenditures Decline, Says 1998 Yearbook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- World military expenditures
declined by about one-third over the decade of 1988-1997 and is
estimated to correspond to about 740 billion U.S.dollars in 1997,
according to the Stockholm International Peace Research
Institute's (SIPRI) yearbook 1998.
</P>
<P>
The SIPRI yearbook said the decline in military spending and
armaments slowed down in the past two years to an average rate of
less than 1 percent as against an average of 4.5 percent over the
entire period.
</P>
<P>
The biggest cut over the decade was made by Russia. Its
military expenditure in 1997 was less than one-tenth of that of
the former Soviet Union in 1988. There have also been significant
cuts in Africa, Central America and the United States.
</P>
<P>
In 1988-1997, military expenditures increased in some regions,
in particular in the Middle East and South and East Asia, said the
yearbook. However, the military budgets of several countries in
East Asia are being revised downwards as a result of the financial
crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the military research and development budget, the
1998 SIPRI yearbook said the United States remains the dominant
power in terms of military technology, with a budget of more than
seven times that of France. Russia's military technology is coming
under stricter export controls and continues to fall further
behind.
</P>
<P>
India has spent about 500 million dollars (in 1995 dollars)
annually on military research and development since 1993. This is
about 28 percent of Indian government funding of science and 18
percent of funding for science in the entire country, a figure
exceeded only in the U.S. If funding for nuclear and space
research and development is included, the amount is 910 million
dollars, or 68 percent of the Indian government funding for
science.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the transfers of major conventional weapons, the
yearbook said that international transfers of major conventional
weapons in 1997 were just over 25 billion dollars. The U.S. share
in deliveries of these weapons increased to 43 percent, while that
of Russia had fallen to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
The yearbook said that of the 25 major armed conflicts in 1997,
only one -- between India and Pakistan -- was interstate. All the
others were internal conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
