<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Declares Strike Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) on
Wednesday announced that the crippling strike by its 620-strong
pilots union was over and the airlines has begun to hire new
pilots to replace the striking pilots.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, PAL management said a downsized airlines is
emerging from the five-day illegal walkout of members of the
Airline Pilots Association of the Philippines (ALPAP).
</P>
<P>
The PAL management said the striking pilots reaffirmed the loss
of their employment status with PAL by defying the government's
return-to-work order whose deadline lapsed late Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The airlines is now hiring permanent replacements of these
pilots which the PAL management already declared as having lost
their job Monday, it said.
</P>
<P>
But there was no comment from the pilots union, which launched
the strike last Friday to protest an early retirement policy
contained in a collective bargaining agreement signed earlier by
the PAL and the union.
</P>
<P>
The strike has almost paralyzed all flight operations of the
country's flag carrier, stranding thousands of passengers at
Manila and provincial airports.
</P>
<P>
With a handful of pilots left in its roster, PAL will now have
a limited international network and an expanded domestic service,
the PAL management said.
</P>
<P>
As new pilot recruits come in, PAL's level of operations will
increase accordingly.
</P>
<P>
During the strike, PAL operated only 20 percent of its
scheduled flights due to a shortage of qualified pilots and the
strict regulatory requirements of aviation authorities.
</P>
<P>
To improve its cash-flow position, the PAL management said it
will sell or lease several of its 54 aircraft, including those
newly acquired from Airbus and Boeing.
</P>
<P>
The strike cost the airline about 150 million pesos (3.8
million U.S. dollars) a day in lost revenues or almost 1 billion
pesos (25.6 million dollars) since the work stoppage began last
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
