</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Intel, the world's largest computer chip-maker,
announced Tuesday price cuts for its Pentium II series of personal
computer (PC) processors.
</P>
<P>
The latest price cuts range from 32 percent to 12 percent for
various Pentium II family members of processors, known as central
processing units (CPUs), serving mainly as the brain of PCs.
</P>
<P>
Price for 400 MHz Pentium II, introduced in April, was down 12
percent, from 824 dollars to 722 dollars, while that for the 350
MHz version was off 16 percent from 621 dollars to 519
dollars. (US-Intel-CPU Prices Cut)
</P>
