<HEADLINE> Philippines Hopes for Early Signing of Loan Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is moving
for an early conclusive and signing of its 22nd yen loan package
with the Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund (OECF) of Japan,
Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Siazon, who arrived here Tuesday from Tokyo, expressed
confidence that the loan package involving 900 million U.S.
dollars could be wrapped up shortly.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said there is a need to fast-track the loan signing to
preempt possible problems with the scheduled merger of the OECF
and the Japanese Export-Import Bank on July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines fears that the merger of the OECF, Japan's
official lending arm, with Jexim Bank could complicate the process
of handling the loan.
</P>
<P>
In his earlier report to President Fidel Ramos, Siazon said it
would be highly desirable if the loan package could be wrapped up
before the OECF-Jexim Bank merger since the OECF will wield lesser
power and influence after the merger.
</P>
<P>
Jexim Bank is also a state-owned financial institution and
likewise provides development-oriented loans, but unlike the OECF
which normally does not give concessional terms.
</P>
<P>
Among the 13 projects to be financed from the 22nd yen loan
package are a power distribution infrastructure system and a
quality air project for Metro Manila, Siazon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Considers Lifting Ban on British Beef Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive body of the European Union, proposed on Wednesday to
relax the ban on British beef exports under certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
Franz Fischler, European commissioner in charge of agricultural
affairs, said the commission unanimously agreed to establish the
rules for a partial lifting of the ban on exports under a
date-based export scheme.
</P>
<P>
The scheme will allow the export of deboned fresh meat and
products from eligible cattle born after August 1, 1996, the date
at which time the meat and bone meal ban was in place and properly
enforced.
</P>
<P>
"The cattle must be older than six months but younger than 30
months," said the commissioner. He explained that the six-month
limit provides traceability for parent animals.
</P>
<P>
Other conditions include specially-designated slaughter houses
to process the meat and a computerized data base on cattle being
used to provide export beef.
</P>
<P>
The commission proposal needs an approval with a qualified
majority in the commission's standing veterinary committee, and the
European council of ministers has to be called upon to examine the
proposal if it fails to get the qualified majority approval in the
veterinary committee.
</P>
<P>
The ministers council can approve the proposal with a qualified
majority or reject it on a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
Britain first proposed lifting the ban on beef exports last
October. The ban was enforced in 1996 following Britain's
announcement of a possible link between the bovine spongiform
encephalopathy and the human variant of Creutzfeldt-Jacob Disease.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission has already approved the lifting of
bans on the export of Northern Irish beef and beef products under
the same conditions.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, at the peak of the BSE epidemic, which was first
spotted in 1986 in Britain, a total of 37,280 BSE cases were
confirmed, whereas last year a substantially-reduced number of
3,396 BSE cases were confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Over 3 million cattle have been slaughtered and destroyed under
various disease eradication programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chief of Chinese PLA General Staff Meets Peruvian Military Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Fu Quanyou, chief of the General
Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA), met with
Nicolas Hermoza, president of joint command of the armed forces
and commanding general of the army of Peru, and his party here
today.
</P>
<P>
Fu, also a member of China's Central Military Commission,
appreciated the Peruvian government's "one China" policy and its
support to China on human rights, as well as Hermoza's positive
efforts in the past to develop the friendship and cooperation
between the two armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Fu said he believed that Hermoza's current visit to China will
increase mutual understanding and friendship between the two armed
forces, and the growth of the friendly relations between the two
countries and their armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the Chinese government values its relations with
Peru, Fu said the relations between the two armed forces have
grown rapidly along with the growth of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government and the PLA have adopted a positive
attitude toward the future exchanges and cooperation at different
levels and in various aspects between the two armed forces and are
willing to make active efforts to this end.
</P>
<P>
Fu also briefed the visitors on China's defense policy and
military construction.
</P>
<P>
Hermoza expressed his satisfaction with the growth of relations
between the two armed forces in the past few years, saying that he
will make more effort to further develop relations between the two
armed forces and the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Hermoza arrived here today as guest of Fu, who presided over a
welcoming ceremony for Hermoza this afternoon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
