<HEADLINE> Audi Promoting Luxury Cars in China Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Audi AG will invest
several million U.S. dollars to build its image as a luxury
carmarker in China's market and expects to become the first
manufacturer in China to produce luxury cars, according to Erich
Schmitt, a member of Audi's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to help reach that goal, the company will display
its full range of vehicles -- including the old-style
"Hillclimber," best-selling A4, A6 and A8, as well as the
"Allroad" concept car -- at the 5th Beijing International
Automotive Industry Exposition scheduled for June 23-30 in the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
In the past, few Audi luxury cars were sold in China. As a
result, Audi is only seen in China as a high-quality sedan, but
not as a luxury car. In western countries, Audi has a bigger share
of the luxury car market.
</P>
<P>
To further enhance the company's presence in China, Audi plans
to produce its luxury A6 car early next century.
</P>
<P>
The sale of Audi's series of cars exceeded 6,000 last year in
China and 546,000 worldwide. The company's output value for 1997
was 22 billion marks.
</P>
<P>
China's First Automotive Works (FAW) based in Changchun,
capital of northeast China's Jilin Province, installed assembly
lines of Audi cars in 1990. In 1996 the first batch of Audi 200 V6
cars were produced by the FAW-Volkswagen Automotive Company, a
joint effort of FAW, Volkswagen and Audi. Audi has exported cars
to China since 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
