<HEADLINE> 225 Rebels Killed, 564 Injured in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- At least 225 Tamil rebels were
killed and 564 others injured in fierce fighting between
government troops and Tamil rebels in the past 10 days in Northern
Province of Sri Lanka, according to a senior official Wednesday,
</P>
<P>
Fierce fighting between government troops and Tamil rebels
killed at least 433 persons on both sides and wounded more than
2,100, Sri Lankan Deputy Defense Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte
Wednesday told parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said the troops suffered 208 killed and 1,536 others
injured, 212 of them seriously, in fighting during the 10-day
period ending Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two government officers and 63 soldiers were missing following
the battles, but some of them have returned to their units, said
Ratwatte, who is also Minister of Irrigation and power.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that the official gave details of the
latest military operations in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government imposed censorship on local and
foreign correspondents on the battles in the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
A censorship was necessary because local newspapers had
published details of military plans allowing Tamil rebels advance
information of the military operations, the minister told
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The fierce fighting took place after the troops resumed their
advance on June 3 to recapture the strategic Mankulam town on its
way to clear a 75-km supply route between the South and North.
</P>
</TEXT>
