<HEADLINE> E.U., Asian Countries to Boost Commercial Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The 15-member European Union and
its 18 Asian partners have agreed in an investment plan to promote
economic links among their medium-size and small enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The 50 million U.S. dollar five-year plan unveiled Wednesday by
the European Commission, the executive body of the EU, will help
medium-size and small businesses deepen mutual understanding and
expand cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Asian countries joining in the program are China,
Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, Brunei, Cambodia, India,
Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan, the
Philippines, Singapore, Sri Lanka, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The EU, defying the recent financial crisis raging in Southeast
Asia, called for increased economic exposure among the bloc's
Asian partners in a bid to develop the potentially huge emerging
market.
</P>
<P>
The Europe-based group has been making efforts to bolster ties
with Asian countries. A blueprint for cooperation extending beyond
the current millennium was formulated at the London Asia-Europe
Summit (ASEM) in April. The first summit was held in Bangkok in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Europe Foundation, designed to promote exchanges
between think-tanks, peoples and cultural groups, was set up by
ASEM foreign ministers in Singapore last February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
