<HEADLINE> Pak, French Officials Hold Talks on South Asian Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of senior officials
from the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs held consultations
here today with their Pakistani counterparts on the current
situation in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Siddique Khan Kanju, Pakistani Minister of State for Foreign
Affairs, told the guests that Pakistan's nuclear tests were
conducted for self-defense and aimed at restoring the strategic
balance in South Asia following India's decision to weaponize and
to induct nuclear weapons, according to a press release issued by
the Foreign Office.
</P>
<P>
While stressing that Pakistan shared the international
community's concern for nuclear non-proliferation, the minister
contended that Pakistan's legitimate security concerns must be
recognized.
</P>
<P>
He urged the permanent members of the U.N. Security Council to
take concerted action for resolution of the core issue of Kashmir
in accordance with the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
The minister made it clear to the French guests that given
India's tendency to renege on its commitments as shown during the
past 50 years, bilateral dialogue between Pakistan and India will
not serve any useful purpose.
</P>
<P>
He said that the success of the India-Pakistan dialogue can
only be assured by participation of the international community or
a third party mediation.
</P>
<P>
The French delegation, who arrived here from New Delhi Tuesday,
emphasized the need for non-proliferation and de-escalation of
tension in the South Asia region. The delegation also delivered a
letter to the Pakistani Prime Minster from the French President.
</P>
