<HEADLINE> Philippine Public Deplores Pilots' Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Various sectors in the Philippines
are deploring the defiance by Philippine Airlines (PAL) pilots of
a government return-to-work order.
</P>
<P>
The pilots belonging to the 620-strong Airline Pilots
Association of the Philippines (ALPAP) staged an allegedly illegal
strike last Friday, which had crippled flight operations of the
country's flag carrier, stranding thousands of passengers at the
Manila and provincial airports.
</P>
<P>
The striking ALPAP members, who were declared by PAL management
as having lost their employment status with PAL, were asked
Saturday by the Department of Labor and Employment to return to
work.
</P>
<P>
But the pilots, who said they were protesting a new retirement
policy, defied the order which lapsed late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This has prompted PAL management to ask the Labor Department to
allow them to hire new pilots to be able to resume operations,
saying that the striking pilots have reaffirmed the loss of their
employment status with PAL.
</P>
<P>
Because of the work stoppage, mobility of people and goods from
various points of the archipelago country was affected, resulting
in huge losses in business and opportunity, the Philippine News
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
With the strike on its fifth day now, businessmen complained of
substantial losses amounting to several millions of pesos.
</P>
<P>
In central Cebu city, business and civic groups said the strike
is seriously affecting the local economy.
</P>
<P>
Val Satira, a Cebu businessman, said that the country, due to
the volatility of the economic situation, cannot afford a costly
strike that can only lead to the "closure of a pioneer airline
company, Philippine Airlines, the nation's flag carrier."
</P>
<P>
Another businessman, Rene Jose, warned that all the investments
for the celebration of the centennial of the Philippines'
independence will be lost if people who want to come and
participate are prevented by the PAL pilots' strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
