<HEADLINE> Philippine Soldiers Raid Marijuana Farm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine soldiers uprooted
Wednesday about 1,000 fully grown marijuana plants in a secluded
farm in a remote village in the southern Philippine province of
Davao del Sur.
</P>
<P>
A police report said government soldiers were engaged in a
gunbattle against a group of bandits near the farm for about an
hour before they reached the farm in Kimlawis village.
</P>
<P>
Upon reaching the farm, soldiers uprooted hundreds of marijuana
plants scattered in about two hectares of land in the remote area,
which has seen as the center of marijuana farms in southern
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Part of the illegal plants was burned on the site while the
rest was stored to be used as evidence during court trial.
</P>
<P>
Marijuana is one of the several kinds of drugs widely used by
an estimated 1.7 million drug addicts in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
