<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Flat Steel Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- To adjust the product structure of
its iron and steel industry, China is now working to increase its
steel plate production.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Wang Xiaoqi, deputy director of the
development planning department of China's State Administration of
Metallurgical Industry, while speaking at the ongoing
China Iron and Steel Conference 1998 here today.
</P>
<P>
Wang said China will start steel projects that are aimed at
creating production capacity of key plate products in such steel
makers as the Baoshan, Anshan and Capital iron and steel groups.
</P>
<P>
He said these projects include hot and cold continuous casting
mills as well as zinc-plating production lines.
</P>
<P>
The construction of cold roll mills is expected to begin early
next century in the Wuhan, Capital and Taiyuan iron and steel
plants.
</P>
<P>
China is also accelerating the upgrading of existing plate
lines, including the hot continuous casting lines in Anshan,
Benxi, Taiyuan, Panzhihua and Meishan, and the cold continuous
casting line in Wuhan Iron and Steel Company.
</P>
<P>
China's industrialization will result in changes in steel
consumption restructure, which is evident in the increasing share
of steel plates and pipes in the total consumption.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Chinese steel consumers are calling for
cost-efficient plate products to substitute for imports.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show two-thirds of China's steel imports are
plates, of which many cannot be produced in China.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, the state administration will give full
support to high value-added and technology-intensive plates such
as auto sheet, appliance and package sheet, cold rolled silicon
plates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Continues Tight Monetary Policies to Curb Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
will continue its tight monetary policies to curb inflationary
pressure, a central bank official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Diwa Gunigundo, director for research of the bank, said that
monetary aggregates are still well in check and the bank will try
its best to meet reserve money ceilings.
</P>
<P>
He said that the total amount of reserve money, which is
defined as cash in circulation plus reserve deposits of banks with
the central bank, is about 20 million pesos (0.5 million U.S.
dollars) below the ceiling set by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
"Our monetary policies are appropriately tight and would remain
so to make sure that inflation won't increase too much," Gunigundo
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the central bank is ready to respond with whatever
measures necessary if the monetary situation calls for it.
</P>
<P>
With a 9.2 percent inflation rate in May, market analysts
believe that monetary authorities in the country would have to
reverse its move to bring down interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The central bank, upon appeals of the business sector, has been
trying to bring down lending rates to the 11 percent level before
the Asian financial crisis broke out last July.
</P>
<P>
The central bank appeared to be making headway with rates based
on the 91-day Treasury bill which is falling below 15 percent now.
</P>
<P>
But analysts said that the central bank may have to tighten up
its monetary level with the increase of inflation rate in May and
the weakening of the peso against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the Philippine Dealing System Wednesday, the peso fell
further to 40.27 against the dollar following the latest round of
currency fluctuation in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
