<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Para-military Forces to Combat Armed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania plans to deploy
para-military forces to Biharamulo district in the northwest
Kagera Region to deal with armed Burundian refugees who are
allegedly harassing local Tanzanians.
</P>
<P>
Ali Ameir Mohammed, the Minister of Home Affairs, has said
that his ministry is contacting the regional commissioner's
office to know the extent of the problem, The Guardian newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will dispatch the para-military force to conduct special
operations to comb the armed Burundian refugees who are
terrorizing our people in the Biharamulo district," he said
Tuesday in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two months, more than 450 Tanzanians living in
the district have fled their home after being harassed by armed
Burundian refugees.
</P>
<P>
According to Anatoli Choya, the Member of Parliament for
Biharamulo, the refugees have been terrorizing local residents,
especially by robbing their property.
</P>
<P>
The MP said last week many residents lost their property
and fled their houses for fear of being killed by armed Burundian
refugees who most of the time plunder whatever valuable
belongings they find.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities have been unable to control the bandits who
come from the Msuhura refugee camp in the Ngara District on the
border with Burundi, said Choya, adding that the bandits, who
hide themselves well, are difficult to be spotted.
</P>
<P>
It is ridiculous that Tanzanians have fled their houses and
become refugees in their own country, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The MP said the district will most probably face an acute
shortage of food this year as some 50 Tanzanian households have
abandoned their farms.
</P>
<P>
Those who fled their houses are currently accomodated at a
police station nearby and a house belonging to a Norwegian-aided
project, Choya said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania plays host to around 225,000 refugees, mainly Hutus
who fled Burundi's civil war, the United Nations High
Commissioner of Refugees (UNHCR) said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
