<HEADLINE> Eritrea Asks for Egypt's Help to End Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Eritrea Wednesday urged Egypt to
help it and its neighbor Ethiopia to reach a peaceful solution to
the border conflicts, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made in a message sent to Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak from his Eritrean counterpart Issayas Aferwerki in
the day by Eritrean Minister of Local Government Mohamud Sherifo,
the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Sherifo arrived in Cairo Tuesday night to brief Egyptian
officials on the latest developments of the armed clashes along
the border of the two Horn of Africa states.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993. Ever since
then, the two countries have been at odds over at least six border
areas. On May 6, fightings broke out between the two sides for a
400-square-kilometer rocky land.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president has sent messages to the leaders of the
two countries, calling for an immediate end to the armed conflicts
and holding peace talks to resolve the border row.
</P>
<P>
"Fighting solves no problems. Negotiations and nothing else
hold the key to the problems," Mubarak has said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, an Egyptian aircraft chartered by the
United States landed at Cairo airport early Wednesday, carrying
230 passengers of Egypt, the U.S., Eritrea and other countries
from Eritrean capital Asmara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
