<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Celebrates Traditional Sagadawa Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Lhasa, capital of the Tibet Autonomous
Region, today turned into a sea of Buddhists, who came to streets
and temples to celebrate the traditional Sagadawa Festival.
</P>
<P>
Sagadawa, which falls on April 15 on the Tibetan calendar, is
the birth and nirvana day of the Buddha. Buddhists pray to
celebrate the event.
</P>
<P>
Ce Zholma, a woman living in Lhasa, got up at four in the
morning and spent nearly four hours in praying, migrating
through the city's several major religious places including the
Potala Palace and the Johkang Temple.
</P>
<P>
"Elder generations say it will disperse calamities by praying
on such a religiously auspicious day like today," she said. "I
pray for the longevity of my old father, as well as for a peaceful
life and health for my family."
</P>
<P>
Bargor Street was crowded with people offering prayers, monks
and peddlers.
</P>
<P>
The festival for Baima Yangtsong, manager of a sweet tea house,
means a golden business opportunity. She said today was the
busiest day since she opened the tea house two weeks ago. She
said she could earn several hundred yuan today.
</P>
<P>
Each temple in Lhasa also attracted a large number of
pilgrims. The Johkang Temple in the downtown area opened two hours
in advance to meet the demand of people who wanted to worship the
Statue of Sakyamuni, founder of Buddhism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
