<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Wharton School of the
University of Pennsylvania in the United States plans to start a
management training program for high-ranking Chinese officials and
public servants in Beijing in September.
</P>
<P>
The training program is part of an agreement announced when
Chinese President Jiang Zemin visited the Wharton campus last fall.
</P>
<P>
The senior management training program is conducted at the
National School of Administration in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Scott Koerwer, director of Custom Programs for Wharton
Executive Education at the school, told local news media here
today that work on the other two training programs under the
agreement are also proceeding smoothly.
</P>
<P>
One of the programs is the Jiangsu Management Development
Program in east China's Jiangsu Province. The other is the
Shanghai Executive Development Program.
</P>
<P>
Koerwer said that the Wharton School is ready to forge a
long-term relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
As President Bill Clinton prepares for his visit to China later
this month, faculty and administrators from the Wharton School
visited Beijing to develop specific plans for conducting these
programs.
</P>
<P>
Wharton is considered one of the leading business schools in
the world. It began educational exchanges with China in the
1940s. Since 1979, it has been increasing cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
The training programs that it now conducts in China are aimed
at enhancing the management skills of government officials and
executives of state-owned enterprises who are working at the
national, regional and local levels. 
</P>
