<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solid Fundamentals to Lead HK to Recovery: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Hong Kong
official said here Wednesday that the sound economic fundamentals,
which may not provide an instant solution to the current economic
woes, would eventually help the Special Administrative Region
(SAR) ride out of the Asian financial storm.
</P>
<P>
Rafael Hui, SAR secretary for financial services, made the
remarks in a keynote speech at the Far Eastern Economic Review's
annual conference, with "Weathering the storm: Hong Kong and the
Asian financial crisis" as its theme.
</P>
<P>
"They (economic fundamentals) may not bring us immediate relief
and reversal of fortune, but I do believe that it's largely the
fundamentals that will eventually see us through our present
difficulties and lead us, once again, to recovery," Hui told the
economic conference.
</P>
<P>
He listed a string of Hong Kong's economic fundamentals, which
are the same before and after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong still holds its status as an international financial
center, keeps its currency stable, sticks to prudent fiscal
policy, has a sound and robust banking system, and serves as a
gateway to the mainland, according to the official, who stressed
that economic confidence was basically built upon sound and solid
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter, Hong Kong economy recorded negative
growth, with GDP falling two percent from the same period of
1997. Unemployment rate hit a 14-year high, interest rates soared
to trigger credit crunch, while property and stock prices plunged.
</P>
<P>
"In times of turmoil, frustration and uncertainty, we have no
better alternative than to hold fast to those basic fundamentals
and policies that have withstood endless tests and strains in the
past," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Hui warned: "The real danger, as always, lies in letting go of
those fundamentals in exchange for immediate, but ultimately
futile and illusory relief." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
