<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Increases 98/99 Budget to $91.6 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar Revolutionary
Government has announced to spend 60.375 billion Shillings (about
91.6 million U.S. Dollars) in the 1998/99 fiscal year, an
increase of 8.9 percent over the past year.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the government budget proposals for the 1998/99
fiscal year to the House of Representatives Tuesday, Minister of
Finance Amina Saalum Ali said that about 42 billion Shillings (63.8
million U.S. Dollars) will be for recurrent expenditure while
some 17 billion Shillings (about 25.8 million Dollars) for
development.
</P>
<P>
Ali said the government will concentrate on achieving a 5.2
percent economic growth in the 1998/99 year compared to
4.8 percent last year as well as on enticing the donor
community's support.
</P>
<P>
She said the Zanzibar national debt now stands at 145 billion
Shillings (220 million Dollars) with 71 billion Shillings (108
million Dollars) foreign debt and 74 billion Shillings (112
million Dollars) internal debt, surpassing the national budget by
nearly 150 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The national debt is becoming too big and the government can
hardly service the debts, both local and foreign," she said.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar Minister for Planning and Investment, Ali Juma
Shamhuna, presented the development plan which will execute 42
projects at a cost of 17.72 billion Shillings (17.79 million
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said the government will put more emphasis on the
consolidation of free economic zones, free ports and especially
the tourism sector which collected 1.3 billion Shillings (1.98
million Dollars) from hotel levy during the ending fiscal year.
</P>
</TEXT>
