<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Stick to Fiscal Prudence: Chief Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa warned here
Wednesday that any deviation from the long-held philosophy of
fiscal prudence may give rise to speculative attacks again on the
Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
Tung made the remarks in response to calls for further tax cuts
in order to pull Hong Kong out of the current economic woes. He
told an economic conference Wednesday that the result of the
deviation may well be another increase in the already high
interest rate.
</P>
<P>
When the financial storm lashed Asia in the latter half of
1997, international speculators attempted to break the peg, which
linked the Hong Kong currency to the greenback at 7.8 HK dollars
to one U.S. dollar. Despite a few speculative attacks, the peg
stood firm and the currency remained stable, but interest rates in
Hong Kong soared.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, with the weakening of the yen this week, Hong Kong
currency is already under pressure in the form demonstrated in the
higher interbank interest rate in the last few days," said the
Hong Kong leader.
</P>
<P>
Tung delivered a luncheon speech at the Far Eastern Economic
Review's annual conference, which focuses on the impact of the
Asian financial crisis on Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the 1998-99 financial budget presented on
February 18, the SAR government made the largest provision of
stimulus in history to boost the battered economy. Tax cuts plus
expenditure increases totaled 53 billion HK dollars (6.8 billion
U.S. dollars) in money terms, equal to four percent of Hong Kong's
GDP.
</P>
<P>
"We know the pain of the adjustment process but the budget
measures must be given time to work," said the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial turmoil has resulted in a high interest
rate and serious credit crunch in Hong Kong. Tung pledged that the
SAR government would take initiatives to improve liquidity in the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
As to the property prices that have fallen substantially over
the past few months, the chief executive said: "The government
does not wish to see a collapse of the property prices as this
will have serious impact on our banking system and will further
erode the already very weak consumer confidence."
</P>
<P>
He admitted that Hong Kong was now in the depth of a major
economic adjustment, the result of which may be prolonged and
painful to everyone.
</P>
<P>
But he is confident that Hong Kong, with sound economic
fundamentals, would be able to go through the difficult period and
embark on the path of economic growth in the not-too-distant
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
