<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke061065 - Pak Achieves Macro-economic Stability, Growth: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has achieved the twin
objectives of macro economic stability and growth as inflation
sharply declined during the 1997-98 fiscal year, said a
governmental economic survey Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Survey 1997-98 (July 1 1997- June 30 1998) was
released by Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz at a press conference
here.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the government was able to pull the
crumbling economy out of oblivion as the real growth of the gross
domestic product (GDP) is estimated to be at 5.4 percent during
the current fiscal year as against 1.3 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
This growth was supported by the strong performance of the
agriculture sector which recorded a 5.9 percent growth followed by
a 7 percent increase in the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
Another notable development in the fiscal year has been the
sharp decline in the rate of inflation which declined to 8.2
percent during the first ten months against 11.6 percent of the
comparable period of last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
However, the survey has nevertheless, noted a relative weak
performance in the tax collection, which forced government to
further revise the revenue target to 297.6 billion rupees (about
6.75 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the current fiscal year, the budget deficit is 5 percent of
the GDP while Last year's budget deficit was 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Trade balance during July-April 1997-98 registered a 54.2
percent improvement and stood at 1,325.2 million dollars as
against 2,895.9 million dollars in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The current account balance during the first nine months of the
current fiscal year stood at 1,127 million dollars as against
3,288 million dollars in the corresponding period of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
