<HEADLINE> UNESCO Assists China to Combat Crimes of Cultural Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Experts from international
organizations and Chinese departments related gathered here today to
discuss ways of fighting the illicit trafficking and smuggling of
cultural property.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization (UNESCO), the Seminar on Fighting
Illicit Trafficking and Smuggling of Cultural Property, that opened
here today, will mainly focus on introducing international regulations
in the fight against the illicit trafficking of cultural property and
discuss measures China needs to adopt.
</P>
<P>
Lyndel Prott, a UNESCO official in charge of cultural property,
said the seminar aims to "facilitate cooperation with the
international communities in fighting against illegal activities
and to protect the cultural heritage of the mankind."
</P>
<P>
The seminar, which will last one week, is being attended by
experts from relevant international and Chinese organizations and
departments including UNESCO and the National Administration for
Cultural Heritage of China.
</P>
<P>
China is now faced with a tough situation of crimes involving
cultural property. In 1997, Chinese customs uncovered more than
600 cases of cultural property smuggling, and seized more than
11,200 items of cultural property.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Chinese public security departments cracked
5,000 cases of theft, smuggling and illicit sales of cultural
property, and seized more than 50,000 items.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Urges Eritrea, Ethiopia to Settle Conflict Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
Wednesday called on the two warring north African countries,
Eritrea and Ethiopia, to cease and refrain from all actions that
may lead to a further escalation of their border conflict.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at his weekly press conference, Ramos
also said the Philippines supports the peace initiatives being
brokered by third parties, particularly those of the United States
and Rwanda, in seeking a peaceful solution to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the Philippines believes that the United Nations
should also play a crucial role in bringing the warring states to
the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
He also assured Filipinos with relatives working in Eritrea,
that the government is exerting all efforts at evacuating overseas
Filipino workers based in Eritrea, most of whom are teachers and
engineers.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing armed conflict between Eritrea and Ethiopia flared
up last week because of a long-time territorial dispute, killing
dozens of civilians and displacing tens of thousands of others in
the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
