<HEADLINE> World Cup 010hke-- Cameroon Captain Said Team "Thirsty to Win" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Cameroon team captain Francois Omam
Biyick said that his team, a fine blend of old and new talents, was
craving for victories at the soccer World Cup finals to start on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are part of a rejuvenated team, and are thirsty to win," said
Italian-based Biyick who play for Sampdoria Genoa.
</P>
<P>
"A mix of old and new players is working well. The less experienced
players know that we're there to help them out," he added.
</P>
<P>
Biyick said the chance of entered the second round would be greatly
boosted if the Indomitable Lions win their first match against Austria
on June 11.
</P>
<P>
His teammate Rigobert Song, who played in the French club Metz,
said the team would received more vocal support from the French crowd
than most people thought.
</P>
<P>
"I've been enough to have played everywhere in France this year, so
it's rather like playing at home in front of a public that I already
know. That is an extra advantage going into the first match," he said.
</P>
<P>
Song, who took part in last World Cup in the United States, added
he had gained in experience and maturity and the crowd factor also
made him more confident than ever.
</P>
<P>
"At least twenty-five percent of the French people are behind us,"
said Song.
</P>
<P>
Besides Song, five other players also played in French clubs,
including those in the host cities of Nantes, Lyon and Saint Etienne.
</P>
<P>
Cameroon will face Group B opponents Italy, Austria and Chile in
the first stage of the tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
