<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Apartheid Regime Stockpiles Lethal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The former South African
military authorities manufactured poisons and biological agents
during the 1980s in amounts which could, theoretically, wipe out
entire populations, top scientists, who were involved in the
project, has revealed.
</P>
<P>
Some of the poisons were used against internal "enemies of the
state," and deadly bacterial agents were also released in foreign
countries, Schalk van Rensburg, head of research at Roodeplaat
Research Laboratories (RRL), Tuesday told the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission, a special court authorized by the
current government.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Van Rensburg, bacteriologist Mike Odendaal, in
charge of manufacturing bacterial agents at RRL, and Johan
Koekemoer, senior research chemicist at Delta G Scientific, also
made evidence at the TRC hearing.
</P>
<P>
RRL and Delta G Scientific were military front companies
operating under Project Coast, the former South African
military's chemical and biological warfare project.
</P>
<P>
The scientists' evidence directly contradicts claims by the
previous government that the project was aimed purely at
developing a defensive capability.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the TRC heard, RRL was involved almost exclusively in
the manufacture of devastating bacteria and lethal poisons. These
include cultures of cholera, anthrax, salmonella, botulism and B.
melitensis, the bacterium which causes malta fever.
</P>
<P>
The deadly bacteria were freeze-dried and kept in cold storage
at RRL, from where they were dispensed on demand to military
operatives.
</P>
<P>
A plan was hatched to poison President Nelson Mandela after
his release from prison with a substance which would cause steady
deterioration of brain function, Van Rensburg said. But the plan was
not carried out.
</P>
<P>
Delta G Scientific manufactured almost one ton of the designer
drug ecstasy and a quarter ton of Mandrax as "incapacitating
agents" for possible use against the local population, the TRC
heard.
</P>
<P>
Sufficient quantities of cholera bacteria to affect the entire
population of Namibia were delivered to the military as late as
September 1989, shortly before the Namibian election.
</P>
<P>
Then-president F W de Klerk was briefed about RRL's activities
in 1990 and put a stop to offensive projects.
</P>
<P>
Among the victims of RRL's poisons was Frank Chikane, former
secretary-general of South African Council of Churches, now
Director-General in Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's office. He
survived only because the attack was botched.
</P>
<P>
In another attack, a Russian adviser to the African National
Congress in Zambia was killed by anthrax spores secreted into his
food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
