here Wednesday that the setting up of the Hong Kong Port and
Maritime Board would help further promote the development of Hong
Kong's shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
The main function of the board is to co-ordinate and bring
together the resources of the government and the maritime sector
to promote Hong Kong as an international shipping center, support
Hong Kong's economic development and create new job opportunities,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Ip said that an important
initiative in the SAR government's effort to promote the Hong Kong
shipping industry is the expansion of the role of the Hong Kong
Port Development Board (PDB) to strengthen the link between the
government and the shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
The new Hong Kong Port and Maritime Board was officially
established on June 1, 1998. All members are appointed by the
Chief Executive for a period of two years. The chairman is Peter
Thompson, an experienced maritime lawyer and former Port
Development Board chairman.
</P>
<P>
"The main strength of Hong Kong as an international shipping
center is that we are not only a shipowning center but we are also
a very important ship management center. Over 1,200 vessels plying
round the world are managed by Hong Kong companies," Ip noted.
</P>
<P>
At present around 500 ships are registered in Hong Kong with a
total tonnage of some six million tons and the shipping and
maritime industry directly contributes 1.7 per cent of Hong Kong's
GDP, according to Ip.
</P>
<P>
Ip said the Economic Services Bureau and the Marine Department
have been undertaking a series of initiatives to support and
encourage the development of Hong Kong's maritime industry, which
include:
</P>
</TEXT>
