<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Scientists Move Towards El Nino Predictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Australian scientists believe
they will be able to improve drought forecasting by using advanced
technology to test water samples from the Indian and Pacific
Oceans.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization
(CSIRO) and the Bureau of Meteorology scientists will combine for
the first time to analyze ocean currents and make forecasts about
the drought-causing El Nino phenomenon, believed to be explained
by the movement of warm and cold ocean currents.
</P>
<P>
The two organizations are looking to boost the effectiveness of
long-range predictions.
</P>
<P>
Nan Bray, CSIRO's marine research chief, told reporters that
while three months is the maximum time that scientists currently
require to predict the El Nino effect, they are working on
extending the forecasting range to a year.
</P>
<P>
Testing will be done from the research vessel the Franklin, at
present docked at Melbourne's Station Pier.
</P>
<P>
Equipment on the vessel can be dropped as deep as six
kilometers into the Indian or Pacific Ocean to take samples.
</P>
<P>
Bray said more accurate predictions on the El Nino can be made
by measuring salinity content, nutrient levels and examining where
the water is going and where it has been.
</P>
<P>
He said the next step would be to provide advice for the
individual needs of farmers in different parts of the country,
taking into consideration the moisture content of soil and other
factors.
</P>
<P>
But the extent to which scientists can be sure of an El Nino
forecast remains limited.
</P>
<P>
"That's part of our risk assessment .. how much we're willing
to put on the line," said Bray. "(But) once the water is in the
direction of El Nino, it doesn't seem to go back."
</P>
<P>
Scientists still do not fully understand what sets off the El
Nino effect and CSIRO climatologist Gary Elder said Australia was
working in collaboration with America, Japan and France to
investigate causes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Slides Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso depreciated
further Wednesday to 40.27 to the U.S. dollar in the afternoon
trading from Tuesday's 39.40 due to high corporate demand and the
sliding trend of the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The peso opened at 39.21 against the dollar at the Philippine
Dealing System, stronger than Tuesday's close of 39.40, but it
subsequently weakened in the morning trade.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, the peso weakened further, like other
currencies in the region. It closed at 40.06 to the greenback,
recovering from the day's high of 40.47, the lowest in about a
month.
</P>
<P>
The average for the day was 39.77 pesos to the dollar compared
with Tuesday's average of 39.47.
</P>
<P>
At 164.5 million dollars, Wednesday's transaction volume was
two times higher than the 77.75 million dollars traded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the continued fall of the Japanese yen, which
was traded around 140.70 against the dollar, put pressure on all
regional currencies, including the Philippine peso.
</P>
<P>
However, they said, the peso can still be considered "delinked"
from the regional currency movement, as its fall was much lower
than other currencies in the region.
</P>
<P>
High corporate demand also added to the pressure for the peso's
depreciation, the dealers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
