<HEADLINE> Zambian Central Bank Optimistic about Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Central Bank has said that
attainment of a nine percent inflation rate and 4.5 percent
growth in the gross domestic product (GDP) still remains the
country's realistic goals this year.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Wednesday quoted Felix Kani, Director of
Economics of the Bank of Zambia (BOZ), as saying Tuesday "We
remain optimistic that we shall achieve the stipulated goals but
of course we should leave room for any unforeseen circumstances
which could lead to some changes, but for the time being we are
on course."
</P>
<P>
According the bank, the exchange rate of the country's
currency, Kwacha, has been stable in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the stability to the recent consultative
group meeting held in Paris and intervening measures the bank
undertook.
</P>
<P>
Kani said that the Kwacha is largely expected to remain stable
if the current economic trends continue.
</P>
<P>
He said the economy has been on course in the past six months
and the targets in the budget still remain realistic.
</P>
<P>
At the Paris meeting held last month, donors pledged Zambia
530 million U.S. Dollars in aid.
</P>
<P>
Several months earlier, an increased demand for foreign
currencies and shortage of them pushed the exchange rate of
Kwacha down considerably. 
</P>
</TEXT>
