<HEADLINE> Intel Cuts Prices on Pentium II Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Intel, the world's largest
computer chip-maker, announced Tuesday price cuts for its Pentium
II series of personal computer (PC) processors.
</P>
<P>
The latest price cuts range from 32 percent to 12 percent for
various Pentium II family members of processors, known as central
processing units (CPUs), serving mainly as the brain of PCs.
</P>
<P>
Price for 400 MHz Pentium II, introduced in April, was down 12
percent, from 824 dollars to 722 dollars, while that for the 350
MHz version was off 16 percent from 621 dollars to 519 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, price for Intel's 266 MHz Celeron processor, also
introduced in April for the lower-end of PC market, was cut by 32
percent, from 155 dollars to 106 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Intel, based in Santa Clara, California, usually cuts the
prices of its CPU chips every three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
