<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Set Up Fund for Chemical Agent Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is to set up a fund for
victims of agent orange, a chemical weapon used by American
soldiers in the Vietnam War, reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As decided by Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai, the fund
will be handled by the Vietnam's Red Cross to help mobilize
humanitarian donations both at home and abroad for the victims.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Vietnam's Foreign Ministry said Tuesday the war
has left enormous consequences, including the long-term and heavy
effects of toxic chemicals, onto the Vietnamese people.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics showed that more than two million
Vietnamese people are affected by various kinds of toxic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
More than one million hectares of affected forests cannot be
naturally recovered, causing soil erosions, flooding during rainy
seasons and droughts during dry seasons, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government is calling for external cooperation
for its project to assess the existence of toxic chemicals in the
country and to evaluate their impacts on people and environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Dips Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar Wednesday
continued a relentless slide toward 58 U.S. cents, even below the
lowest level of 59.60 12 years ago, despite boosted efforts by the
federal government to shore up confidence in the ailing currency.
</P>
<P>
Federal Treasurer Peter Costello and Prime Minister John Howard
hit the airwaves Wednesday to talk up the economy and its ability
to withstand currency troubles without an interest rate hike.
</P>
<P>
Costello said the fall in the Australian dollar was linked to
the slump in Asian currencies, and stressed the need for dealers
to take into account the economy's strong fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
He said there was no case for banks to boost home loan rates,
as the Reserve Bank had not increased official cash rates.
</P>
<P>
Costello told radio 3AW, "The important thing for those that
are looking for long-term values is to look at the fundamentals -
and the fundamentals of the Australian economy are strong."
</P>
<P>
The treasurer ruled out the possibility of a recession for
Australia, saying the economy's growth was probably the fastest in
the world, but conceded that it was expected to slow.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's export performance to ASEAN countries was
expected to pick up in 1998/99.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Prime Minister John Howard spoke on Sydney
radio of the economy's low inflation, strong business investment
and projected budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
"When you look around our region, the things that really count
in the medium to longer term are very strong in Australia," Howard
told Radio 2BL.
</P>
<P>
However, the efforts made by the political leaders seemed to
have little effect with the Australian dollar closing at 58.29
U.S. cents from Tuesday's local close of 59.78.
</P>
<P>
The previous lowest closing rate for the local currency was
59.60 U.S. cents on July 31, 1986.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank (NAB) business survey said
Australia's economic growth would be just 1.75 percent in 1998/99
- compared with the government's 3.0 percent prediction - and that
official cash rates would rise in the next month or so.
</P>
<P>
NAB chief economist Alan Oster warned the Australian dollar
could fall to 57 U.S. cents without a rate hike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
