<HEADLINE> Italian Police Smash Arms-Drugs Gang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Police in the Italian city of Milan
Tuesday arrested 125 people on alleged using drug-related profits
to help fund fighting in the Serbian province of Kosovo and
terrorist operations in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Police also caught 100 kilograms of cocaine and heroin from the
criminal organization, whose members include 30 ethnic Albanians
noted by the police as of "particular importance."
</P>
<P>
These ethnic Albanians were progressively merging with Mafia
clans to help move enormous quatities of narcotics from locations
in eastern Europe to thriving markets in the West, police said.
</P>
<P>
The gang members then used the money to buy weapons in Italy
and smuggle them into to Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians are in a
bloody struggle for independence.
</P>
<P>
Some other members of the group were involved in the money
laundry wing of the criminal operations, depositing millions of
U.S. dollars in Swiss banks and using the profits for terrorist
operations in Egypt, said the police.
</P>
<P>
All the arrested have been charged with conspiracy to traffic
in arms and narcotics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
