<HEADLINE> Pak PM to Announce National Agenda Against Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif will announce a national agenda in his address to the
nation Thursday to combat economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's speech will be broadcast live by Radio
Pakistan and Pakistan Television at 2000 hours Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agenda will envisage austerity measures to be adopted both
at official and public levels to minimize the impact of the
economic sanctions on the country's economy, government officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to announce drastic cut in the
administrative expenditure to override the situation, they said.
</P>
<P>
The national budget for the year 1998-99 (from July 1, 1998 to
June 30 1999) will also be finalized in the light of the national
agenda, they said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistani parliament Wednesday adopted a resolution
to impose a six-month emergency in the country to enable the
government to deal with the post-nuclear test situation.
</P>
<P>
Following Pakistan's nuclear tests in late May in response to
the Indian provocation, some Western countries including the
United States and Japan announced economic sanctions against
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say Pakistan will be hit harder than India by the
Western sanctions as the country's economy is very dependent on
foreign aid and loans. 
