<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Down on Currency, Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
Wednesday closed weaker on concerns over the downward pressure on
the Australian dollar and fears that interest rates could rise.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed down 31 points, or 1.18
percent, at 2,592.9, but off its low of 2,582.9.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 7.1 points weaker at 1,061.2 and
the all industrials index was 59.7 points lower at 4,501.0.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar at the end of local trading was worth
58.32 U.S. cents, down from 59.81 U.S. cents at the previous
session close, and off an intraday low of 58.09 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Ausbil Xiradis, a funds manager, said the Australian dollar was
"probably getting close to its bottom" and "it appears that there
is not going to be any change to interest rates" by the Reserve
Bank of Australia, the central bank.
</P>
<P>
He said this had helped the market pick up off its low in the
afternoon session with News Corp. leading the way.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweight News Corp. gained 14 cents, or 1.40 percent,
to 10.14 Australian dollars and its preferred scrip gained 9
cents, or 1.03 percent, to 8.82 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said that because News Corp. earned a significant
amount in the United States it was relatively insulated by the
downward pressure on the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank shares dropped 45.1 cents, or 2.07
percent, to 21.303 Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of
Australia fell 27 cents, or 1.50 percent, to 17.73 Australian
dollars, and ANZ Banking Corp. slipped 18 cents, or 1.66 percent,
to 10.67 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
But Westpac Banking Corp. rose 5 cents, or 0.52 percent, to
9.60 Australian dollars, with brokers saying the bank had bucked
the trend because it had recently gone ex-dividend and been
oversold.
</P>
<P>
"The stock has come back fairly savagely since it went
ex-dividend," said Xiradis, adding that Westpac's share buyback
scheme could have contributed.
</P>
<P>
Major resource stocks finished mixed, with Australia's leading
company BHP closing down 10 cents at 13.44 Australian dollars, and
global miner Rio Tinto falling two cents to 19.65 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index gained 1.9 points to 1,126.1.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion closed 4.75 U.S. dollars lower at 290.75 U.S.
dollars in Sydney trading. It was trading at 291.55 U.S. dollars
at midday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 338.78 million shares valued at 629.8
million U.S. dollars, with falls easily outnumbering rises by 874
to 376, and 419 stocks were steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
