<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Falls by Nearly 1.5 U.S. Cents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The battered Australian dollar
lost nearly one and a half U.S. cents Wednesday to dive through
the key 59 U.S. cent barrier to a record post-float closing low.
</P>
<P>
The currency touched 58.09 U.S. cents Wednesday before
recovering slightly to end at 58.32 U.S. cents, its lowest close
since 1986, down from 59.81 U.S. cents at Tuesday's session in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The battered local dollar continues to nudge at all time
post-float record lows reached on July 28, 1986 after then
treasurer Paul Keating warned Australia of becoming a banana
republic when commenting on the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Mike Hollows, a foreign exchange manager, said with sentiment
towards the Asian currencies and especially the Japanese yen being
particularly bearish Wednesday "the Australian dollar is looking
quite vulnerable".
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar is comfortably trading below 60.00 U.S.
cents and not even looking like rallying," he said. "I guess the
all-time low is beckoning."
</P>
<P>
Traders warned the Australian dollar, which reached its
previous lowest close of 59.60 U.S. cents on July 31, 1986, could
now head towards its all time post-float intraday low of 57.10,
seen on July 28 that year.
</P>
<P>
At the close locally, the Australian dollar was sharply lower
against the Japanese yen at 82.35 from 84.06 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The currency was also buying 1.0385 German marks from 1.0626
marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
