<HEADLINE> S. Korean Airline Orders 27 Boeing jetliners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Korean Air, of South Korea,
ordered 27 Boeing 737 jets worth about two billion U.S. dollars, a
release from the Seattle-based Boeing said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The package, the second-largest aircraft order in Korean Air's
history, includes firm orders for 11 Boeing 737-800s, 11 Boeing
737-900s and five options for a mix of the same models.
</P>
<P>
Deliveries are to begin in August 2000 and continue through
July 2005, the world's largest aircraft maker said.
</P>
<P>
The orders are timed to expand air routes in northeast Asia as
South Korea's new Inchon International Airport opens in 2001, said
Y.H. Cho, Korean Air's president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
The deal has drawn attention as South Korea, once a dynamic
economic powerhouse in the world, has been hard hit by a financial
crisis since late last year.
</P>
<P>
Korean Air's largest order was for 28 Boeing 747-400 jumbo jets
in 1986. 
