<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Oil Companies to Join on Gas Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 9 (Xinhua) -- China National Offshore Oil
Corp. (CNOOC) and Atlantic Richfield Company (ARCO) of the United
States have agreed to conduct joint study for possible development
of the Ledong natural gas fields in the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
An agreement, signed Tuesday in ARCO's headquarters of Los
Angeles by the two partners, will increase the chances of jointly
developing the Ledong natural gas fields and the nearby Wenchang
area where natural gas was previously discovered.
</P>
<P>
The three Ledong fields, of about 925 square kilometers, were
discovered in 1996 by China National Offshore Nanhai Corporation,
a CNOOC subsidiary, some 100 kilometers southwest of Hainan Island.
</P>
<P>
In the 463-square-kilometer Wenchang area, two of the three
geological structures have been drilled and found to contain gas.
</P>
<P>
Both Ledong and Wenchang are near the 770-kilometer pipeline
that currently carries natural gas to Hong Kong and Hainan Island
from Yacheng 13-1 gas field.
</P>
<P>
"Adding Wenchang to our study of Ledong fields brings a whole
new dimension to this project," said ARCO's president William Wade.
</P>
<P>
"If development proceeds, the project will enable both
companies to build additional value in the South China Sea and
supply cleaner-burning natural gas for the energy growth needs of
southern China," Wade said.
</P>
<P>
Feasibility studies currently underway include an engineering
and geological evaluation of the fields, an assessment of
recoverable reserves, and identification of possible markets for
the gas.
</P>
<P>
If the area is concluded worthy of joint development, said
CNOOC President Wang Yan, "I will come back as early as September
to sign an official agreement to start the joint development of
Ledong/Wenchang natural gas fields."
</P>
<P>
Wang predicted that given the rising energy need in southern
China, the joint investment would hit over one billion U.S. dollar
with a greater profit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's Financial Market Opens Up Wider (1) by Xinhua Writer Chen Xin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A group of overseas banks have
been approved to have limited access to China's bond market as the
central authorities continue to carry out the policy of prudently
globalizing the country's financial market.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the People's Bank of China, the central bank, told
Xinhua today that eight overseas bank will start inter-bank bond
transactions via their branches in Pudong, Shanghai, as early as
next week.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time that foreign banks join in China's
bond trading through the market.
</P>
<P>
Such business will be conducted on the National Inter-Bank
Market through computerized quoting system. The branches of the
eight banks in Pudong are expected to be hooked up with the system
by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
The eight banks are Industrial Bank of Japan, Dai Ichi Kangyo
Bank, Citibank, Standard Chartered Bank, Hong Kong and Shanghai
Banking Co., Bankque Indosuez, Sanwa Bank and Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
They were approved to begin Renminbi-based business in Pudong
over a year ago and became members of the National Inter-Bank
Market last April.
</P>
<P>
Central bank officials say that the move illustrates China's
determination of a gradual opening-up of its financial sector in
spite of the financial crisis in southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
To date, nine overseas banks have been allowed limited access
to the local currency business. By the end of last March, their
Renminbi assets totaled 916 million yuan, with outstanding loans
totaling 591 million yuan and deposits 566 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts believe that this latest development will not
have much impact on China's bond market in the short term because
the banks' Renminbi assets are still small.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's Financial Market Opens Up Wider (2) by Xinhua Writer Chen Xin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the meantime, bond trading of the overseas banks are limited
within the inter-bank market, which is currently separated from
those of the two stock exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, analysts regard the overseas banks' joining in
China's inter-bank bond trading as having a long-term positive
impact on country's financial market.
</P>
<P>
The changes of interest rates on the inter-bank market will
become more rational to reflect the actual balance between capital
demand and supply, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
"Though the foreign banks do not necessarily make large
transactions, their long-established reputation in capital
management will definitely have some influence on other dealers in
rate offering," an economist with the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the overseas banks' entry will push their Chinese
counterparts to further improve their internal management and help
increase market efficiency.
</P>
<P>
China has kept to open its financial market to foreign banks
for the past decade. Central bank figures show that there are now
more than 700 branches and representative offices of overseas
financial institutions in China at present.
</P>
<P>
A few foreign insurance companies have also started business in
China.
</P>
<P>
Dai Xianglong, central bank governor, told a symposium here
Tuesday that China is considering to allow more foreign banks to
start Renminbi-based business and approve more foreign insurance
companies to enter the Chinese insurance market in the
future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Learning for Children in Impoverished Parts of China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- As computers become more common
for people in eastern China's large cities, children in some
impoverished areas also want a chance to learn more about them.
</P>
<P>
Zholma, a fourteen-year-old Tibetan girl from China's Qinghai
Province, says, "I want to learn about computers. If I have the
chance to learn about computers, I will help our town get rid of
poverty."
</P>
<P>
The China Association for Science and Technology (CAST) started
a project today to do something about this and to get people to
donate computers and educational materials to children in China's
impoverished areas. Its magazine "Popsoft" donated 50 computers
today to the project and plans to set up two classrooms for
computer education in Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
A recent study showed that none of the 389 primary schools in
Xining, Qinghai's capital, has a computer, and only 16 percent of
the 97 middle schools in the city have computers. And, the only
computer classroom, in the city's children's center, has 26
outmoded computers. More than a hundred children can be seen
elbowing each other there, and four or five share one computer, a
teacher says.
</P>
<P>
Science and education are backward in many parts of central and
western China, and their economy is underdeveloped, according to
He Yucheng, a Qinghai official, and developing them is the only
way to get rid of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Guangzhao, CAST's president, has asked local governments
to spend more on education, and he has asked the rest of society
to pay more attention to improving the quality of life in
impoverished areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Parliament Approves Emergency Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The federal Parliament of
Pakistan Wednesday approved the emergency proclaimed by President
Rafiq Tarar on May 28 in the wake of Pakistan's five nuclear tests
the same day.
</P>
<P>
After a four-day hectic debate, the joint session of the
Parliament approved the resolution on imposing a six-month
emergency in the country by a vote of 166 in favor against 50.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan exploded five nuclear devices on May 28, 17 days after
India's nuclear tests. President Tarar promulgated the emergency
late in the night of May 28 which included certain temporary
restrictions on foreign exchange and suspending of fundamental
rights of the citizens.
</P>
<P>
Although the emergency was approved by a comfortable margin,
all government allied groups stayed away from Wednesday's session
which was specially summoned to approve the imposition of
emergency.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Muslim League (N) achieved the support of the
deputies from the Federal Administered Tribal Areas and minorities
while the main opposition People's Party, Awami National Party and
Jamiat Ulema-e-Islam opposed the emergency.
</P>
<P>
The government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif imposed emergency
to deal with "foreign threats and the country's economic
condition". All foreign accounts were frozen after the state of
emergency was imposed.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition vehemently opposed the proclamation of
emergency and accused the government of usurping the fundamental
rights of the nation.
</P>
<P>
The opposition contended that the emergency had nothing to do
with either the threat perception or the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"It has been imposed only to avoid the imminent economic
collapse. Had there been any external threat, the emergency would
have been imposed soon after India had carried out five nuclear
explosions," the opposition claimed.
</P>
<P>
However, the government believed that it had become inevitable
to take such measures at a time when Pakistan was confronted with
an extraordinary situation.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan was facing dire challenges to its security and
economy in the wake of nuclear tests carried out in response to
the Indian provocations," the Treasury benches said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
