<HEADLINE> China's Shanghai Opens Hotline to Boost Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- This economic and financial
center of China just opened a telephone hotline in an effort to
improve foreign trade and draw more investment from overseas.
</P>
<P>
The hotline, (021) 6275-1815, is primarily meant to serve the
17,900 overseas-funded enterprises, 4,000-strong representative
offices of overseas companies, 200-odd multinational corporations,
consulates of 32 nations, and 700-plus foreign trade companies in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
From now on, anyone who come to trouble or have problems
pertinent to foreign trade and economic cooperation in Shanghai
can dial the hotline for help.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Xiaoming, director of Shanghai Municipal Foreign Trade
Commission, said that overseas investment in Shanghai has entered
a period of slow growth at the high level and the foreign trade
enterprises have met with unprecedented difficulties because of
the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the government must do better in smoothing
information flow and providing policy services to make Shanghai
more competitive in terms of foreign trade and the use of overseas
investment," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that starting this year Shanghai will publish
details of its foreign trade and use of overseas investment twice
a year and will open on the Internet a page about Shanghai's
foreign trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Related policies, rules and regulations, and other information
will be published regularly in the mass media.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, Shanghai will take advantage of its agencies
stationed overseas to help potential investors obtain more
knowledge of the city.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will soon publish a detailed set of rules on the
approval of overseas investment, further expanding the power of
the Pudong New Area and the Waigaoqiao Bonded Zone in approving
investment in their respective areas, Zhu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
