<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plummet in Tokyo Due to Falling Bank Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled 190.91 points
in Tokyo Wednesday as bank shares fell sharply due to the
unraveling of cross-shareholdings.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange finished at 15,339.26, down
1.23 percent from Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX) covering all First Section
issues dropped 10.08 points, or 0.83 percent, to 1,198.60.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the First Section grew to an estimated 350 million
shares from Tuesday's 315 million shares. And long-Term Credit
Bank of Japan was Wednesday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Falling prices on the Hong Kong stock market also contributed
to the Tokyo stock market's decrease, but the downslide was slowed
by bargain-hunting Japanese pension funds, traders said.
</P>
<P>
While profit-taking during the morning trading session pushed
share prices down, concerns over the sagging Hong Kong stock index
and Japanese banks' poor health were behind the overall decline.
</P>
<P>
Japanese banks also helped push Tokyo stock prices downward,
with declines seen across the board, said analysts.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,336 issues listed on the First Section, losers
surpassed gainers 746 to 352, with 145 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
