<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Scientists Make Breakthrough in Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- South African researchers
have developed a new series of compounds which it is hoped could
have an impact in the fight against cancer.
</P>
<P>
The eight new molecules developed by researchers at the
University of Pretoria could reduce the cost of treating cancer,
tuberculosis (TB) and malaria by allowing doctors to treat
patients with older drugs which have become ineffective as these
diseases are resistant to them, The Star daily reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new molecules, called Riminophenazines, have slowed the
growth of cancer in laboratory tests. Although the research into
TB is not as far advanced as the cancer research, it is hoped the
Riminophenazines could help save the country millions of Rand.
</P>
<P>
Professors Connie Medlen and Ronnie Anderson, along with team
spokesman Johan Spence, have been working on the specific project
for the past six years and achieved the milestone of having the
molecules patented in the United States Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But it will take at least five years before the drug becomes
available to the public. Researchers still have to conduct
clinical trials -- testing the drug first on animals, then on
healthy human volunteers before it is tested on cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking for a partner now, South African or
international, to develop it further. Clearly, the
ground-breaking work was done here and there needs to be some
benefit to South Africa," Spence said.
</P>
<P>
Riminophenazines work like no other cancer drugs currently on
the market. Instead of attacking the brain of the cell, the
nucleus, or other vital parts of the cell, the new molecules act
on the outer wall of the cell.
</P>
<P>
This is said to slow down the rate at which the cells can
absorb Potassium, a vital element needed for the cell to grow and
multiply, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
Cancer cells grow faster and absorb about three times as much
Potassium as normal cells, but Riminophenazines reportedly reduce
the Potassium uptake significantly.
</P>
<P>
The other significant effect of these molecules has wider
significance than just cancer treatment. One of the major
problems faced by doctors and drug companies is that viruses and
bacteria develop a resistance to specific drugs and they become
almost useless, necessitating the development of new drugs.
</P>
<P>
The disease cells recognize the drug and pump it out of the
cell as soon as it enters and the drug has no effect.
</P>
<P>
Riminophenazines make the drug stay inside the cell and can
therefore act to kill the disease cell. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 08:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Likely to Be Dissolved: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti National Assembly
(Parliament) is likely to be dissolved at weekend due to its
stand-off with the Cabinet over the probing of the interior
minister, local newspapers reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources were quoted by the reports as saying that
government leaders met on Tuesday to review the stand-off and came
to a conclusion that dissolution of the National Assembly is the
best way to solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the government leaders have decided to send a
letter to Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, saying
cooperation is no longer possible between the Cabinet and the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The assembly has demanded that Interior Minister Sheikh
Mahammad Khaled Al-Hamad Al-Sabah be investigated for alleged
responsibility for "the spread of crimes and corruption in various
bodies of his ministry."
</P>
<P>
But the Cabinet has vehemently opposed the move.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet also has discovered that the assembly is planning
to investigate the ministers of health, defense, and justice and
Islamic affairs.
</P>
<P>
Observers here pointed out the current political crisis has
been aggravated by other controversial issues, including a
government proposal to raise fuel prices and public service
charges.
</P>
<P>
The Parliament was against the price hikes, a move it says will
exert negative impact on low-income citizens.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that at least 12 parliament members have
submitted resignation due to the inevitability of the parliament
dissolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
