<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environment Protection Cooperation In Northeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China's Liaoning Province plans
to get 1.1 billion U.S. dollars worth of foreign loans for
pollution control on the Liaohe River, urban infrastructure, and
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is China's largest and oldest heavy industrial base
and has serious pollution problems. It has a tenth of the country's
state-owned large and medium-sized enterprises, and is known for
its iron and steel, machinery, power, and building materials
industries.
</P>
<P>
The province emits 900 billion cubic meters of waste gas
annually, and 2.2 billion tons of industrial and human waste. The
Liaohe, which is used by eight cities and over half the province's
people, is one of the country's most seriously polluted rivers.
</P>
<P>
Du Qiugen, the head of the provincial environment protection
bureau, says that the need for environment's protection is urgent.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the province has used 140 million U.S.
dollars worth of foreign loans for environmental protection
projects like sewage treatment, energy research, and saving water,
and has spent 2.8 billion yuan stopping industrial pollution over
the past five years, Du says.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning's problems are mainly with the water, so the
environment protection emphasis will be on stopping water
pollution, he says. It will set up over twenty sewage treatment
plants in cities and 140 projects to stop industrial pollution at
the source. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Stock Index Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Component Stock Index on the
Shenzhen Stock Exchange finished at 4,034.13 today, down 5.36
points from the previous session, according to the Guangfa
Securities Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
