<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air France Pilots, Management Reach Deal to End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The striking pilots of Air France
and the company's management have signed an agreement to end the
10-day long strike, said the biggest pilots union SNPL and the
management in a joint communique Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached hours before the football World Cup
will be officially opened in the Stadium of France and as
criticism against the strikers is rising from both the government
and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The SNPL, which represents most of the 3,200 pilots of Air
France, asked the pilots to resume flights as soon as possible as
the 10-day long strike is still paralyzing three fourths of the
flights and has already cost the company one billion francs (167
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the pilots will participate in
improving the competitiveness of Air France by becoming the
stock-holders of the company in exchange for a reduction of their
salaries.
</P>
<P>
Air France is trying to partially privatize its stocks and to
reduce the payroll of its employees by 500 million francs (83
million U.S. dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
The management agreed to scrap the double standard in pays for
the company's older and younger pilots, and instead establish a
specific pay system for the young pilots whose training costs are
paid by the company.
</P>
<P>
The pilots and management also agree to negotiate in the
following years an agreement on establishing stable relations
between them, which are based around policy-making, employment
and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
"Following the agreement passed, the SNPL calls on pilots to
resume flights ... the most rapidly possible," said the SNPL.
</P>
<P>
The management has already signed an agreement to end the
conflict with a minority pilot's union Tuesday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
