<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Oilfield Found in South China Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The China National Offshore Oil
Corp (CNOOC) and the Santa Fee Energy Co.Ltd of the US have found
a new oilfield in the basin of Zhujiang River Mouth in South China
Sea, through joint exploration.
</P>
<P>
The new offshore oilfield, Panyu 4-2, is located some 160
kilometers southeast of Hong Kong in 15/34 block of South China
Sea contracted by the Santa Fee company, which is expected to have
geological oil reserves topping 20 million tons.
</P>
<P>
According to the CNOOC source, the 15/34 block was contracted
to Santa Fee in January 1997. So far, a group of oil and gas
bearing structures including Panyu 2-1, Panyu 4-2, Panyu 9-2 have
been found in the block.
</P>
<P>
Experts held that the newly-discovered Panyu 4-2 oilfield is
rich in oil and gas reserves, with oil layer extending 169.2
meters in thickness.
</P>
<P>
A CNOOC official noted that the discovery of Panyu 4-2 oilfield
proves to be another major breakthrough following Xijiang 34-3
oil-bearing structure in the basin of Zhujiang River Mouth of
South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
Experts expect the offshore Panyu area to be the fifth group of
oilfields in the eastern part of the Zhujiang River Mouth Basin
after the successful exploration of oilfield groups of Huizhou,
Xijiang, Lufeng and Liuhua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
