<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Region Fighting Last Campaign to End Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region in northwest China has launched a decisive battle to fight
poverty in an attempt to bring its remaining 740,000 poor farmers
out of difficulties by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The region began poverty relief work in 1986, and has
intensified its efforts in this regard over the past few years. As
a result, it reduced the poor population from 1.43 million to
740,000.
</P>
<P>
During the past few years, more than 200,000 people, one-third
of whom were officials from governments, enterprises and
institutions, participated in pair-cooperation on poverty relief
activities, involving some 250,000 rural households to cover more
than 80 percent of the total impoverished population.
</P>
<P>
Hotan Prefecture in southern Xinjiang, for example, has
received several hundred million yuan in aid over the past few
years to cultivate 20,000 hectares of wasteland, and cut local
poor population by more than half.
</P>
<P>
Resettlement projects have also contributed to the effort, and
many poor farmers have considerably improved their living
conditions moving elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The region focuses its poverty eradication on agriculture-based
industries, supported by scientific achievements such as maize
planting using plastic sheeting techniques, high-yield cotton
developments, fast fattening techniques for sheep and cattle, and
other farm produce and livestock processing techniques.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, maize output increased by more than 30 percent in
poor areas last year, and farmers' per capita income in 30 poor
counties was raised from 759 yuan three years ago to 906 yuan last
year.
</P>
<P>
Local goverment will give priority to rural infrastructure,
scientific training, and application of practical agro-techniques
in the process to aid the poor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
