<HEADLINE> More Bank Mergers Expected in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
 Wednesday foresaw the possibility of more mergers of small banks
with big ones before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said those cash-strapped
small banks will have to merge with large banks in order to avoid
cash flow problems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, the requirement of the central bank to
raise banks' operating capital to a new height is expected to
result in more bank mergers.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the central bank has decided to gradually raise
banks' operating capital until it reaches the limit set by the
government up to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to him, small banks such as the Unisave Bank and
Capitol Bank are now seeking merger with two big banks.
</P>
<P>
Singson did not explain how much the new banks' operating
capital should be. But he admitted that the capital hike will be
done in stages, possibly every six months from the effectivity of
the central bank's ruling.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Singson clarified that the central
bank management meet with the Orient Bank depositors every week to
assure them that the cash-strapped Orient Bank will not be totally
closed as others fear.
</P>
<P>
According to him, if the central bank will permanently close
Orient Bank, it is likely that many of the depositors with more
than 100,000 pesos (2,500 U.S. dollars) in deposit accounts will
not be paid.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Philippine Deposit Insurance Corporation
is only responsible for a maximum of 100,000 pesos as mandated by
the insurance law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
