<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austerity Budget Expected to Kick-Start Kenyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Simeon
Nyachae is expected to present Thursday to parliament an
austerity budget aimed at reviving the battled economy.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth in the east African country fell from 4.6
percent in 1996 to 2.3 percent last year. Analysts said the
mounting budget deficit now is perhaps the key issue facing
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Measures included in the budget can only work if the
government reduces expenditure and collects more taxes, they
said.
</P>
<P>
However, Kenya's tax collections have been on the increase
over the past few years. But that the government now is being
questioned about the use of public revenue, makes such a move
difficult.
</P>
<P>
"Given that revenue collection increases are not going to be
easy, government expenditure has to be tackled head on. This seems
to be the only way to reduce the budget deficit," Nikhil Hira, a
local economic analyst, claims.
</P>
<P>
It is likely that the government will increase the tax
brackets in an effort to increase consumers' disposable (after
tax) incomes and stimulate consumer spending for the sake of
faster economic recovery, according to the experts.
</P>
<P>
They urged the government to speed up privatization and civil
service reform plans as inefficient parastatals have been a drain
on the exchequer for too long and the current wage bills in the
public sector is too high and unsustainable in the long run.
</P>
<P>
"The current high level of interest rates is indicative of the
harmful effect of the budget deficit," they add.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of Thursday's reading, the Kenya Shilling has, however,
remained stable as traders wait to see the effect of the budget
on the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
A daily market bulletin from the Standard Chartered Bank said
Tuesday that, despite heavy inflows of hard currency from
exporters, large buy orders from corporate clients contained the
Shilling at just below the 61-Shilling mark to the U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin said that the budget could drive the market
either way, which has made both the buy and sell counters to
remain active.
</P>
<P>
Since last year's budget, Kenyans have seen a hike in the
standard and lower rate of value added tax (VAT) of two percent,
which has had its greatest impact on the poor, in a declining
economy.
</P>
<P>
Promises of realizing higher growth and alleviating poverty in
the 1997/98 budget also came to naught as the economy is
currently in a recession. It is estimated that nearly 46 percent
of the population is living in conditions of absolute poverty.
</P>
<P>
The other trend in past budgets is the tendency to increase
indirect taxes. This usually involves raising the rates of value
added tax (VAT) on various commodities.
</P>
<P>
However, the Central Bank of Kenya predicts that the slowdown
in Kenya's economic growth since 1997 can be reversed by the
second half this year.
</P>
<P>
Investor confidence will also be restored particularly with
the expected resumption of 205-million-U.S.-Dollar aid package by
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) later this year, the bank
announced earlier.
</P>
<P>
The IMF cut the loans to Kenya under the Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility at the end of last July, citing rampant
corruption and poor governance in the east African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Real U.S. Moves to Abandon Hostility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran has urged the United States to
take real actions to abandon its hostility toward Tehran so as to
pave the way for improving bilateral relations, Iran's official
news agency IRNA reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Foreign Minister for Euro-American Affairs Morteza
Sarmadi was quoted as saying that Washington's good words and kind
gestures could not be a substitute for good deeds.
</P>
<P>
Sarmadi focused blame on Israel, who he said instigated
Washington to paint an erroneous picture of Iran. But this effort
"had failed by the presence on all scenes of the Iranian people
and especially by their massive participation in the presidential
elections" in May last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The absence of support to the U.S. by other countries in its
continuing schemes against Iran is a proof of Tehran's plausible
diplomacy worldwide, the official added.
</P>
<P>
He attacked Israel and pro-Israeli pressure groups in the
U.S. for trying to distort Iran's image in a bid to prevent the
closeness of human societies.
</P>
<P>
Sarmadi made the remarks after Iran's Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi granted an interview to the Cable News Network in New
York, in which Kharrazi blamed the U.S. government for continuing
its hostile policies toward Iran.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the U.S. General Assembly on Drugs,
Kharrazi said the U.S. is not yet qualified for rapprochement with
Iran on the basis of mutual respect and equal rights.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., which repeatedly accuses Iran of sponsoring
terrorism, undermining the Middle East peace process and seeking
weapons of mass destruction, has been exerting desperate efforts
to isolate Tehran in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
Tehran, on the other hand, attacked Washington for supporting
Israel and adopting arrogant policies towards other countries.
</P>
<P>
But since the ascendance to power of Iran's moderate President
Mohammad Khatami last August, both Tehran and Washington have
softened their harsh tones and signs were emerging indicating that
the two arch enemies were moving toward opening a "crack in the
war of mistrust."
</P>
<P>
Senior Iranian officials have hinted that Iran-U.S. relations
could be improved if Washington drops accusations against Tehran
and takes concrete steps to solve the financial disputes with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Hague International Court granted Iran an
extension of three months to reply to the U.S. counter-claim over
the destruction of three Iranian oil platforms in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Iran has demanded compensation for the platforms destroyed by
U.S. war ships during the Iran-Iraq war between 1980 and 1988. But
the U.S. argued that the platforms were used in military actions
that were detrimental and dangerous to maritime commerce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Mourns Death of Young Editors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
expressed sorrow and sadness over the death of two Monitor
editors who were killed in a car rally Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a message of condolences sent to The Monitor newspapaer's
Editor-in-Chief Wafula Oguttu and the staff Tuesday, Museveni
said he was sad to learn the tragic death of two such young
people who had perished at an age when they still had their full
lives ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
The message was sent by the president's Press Secretary Hope
Kivengere.
</P>
<P>
Sunday Monitor editor Richard Tebere, aged 33, and sports
editor Rashid Mudin were killed when their car crashed into a
bridge at about 2:30 p.m. Monday in Kotido district during the
Cannonball Rally.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said they were driving back to Kampala in the
second leg of the 1,500 km rally expected to end Tuesday, when
Tebere lost control of their Toyota car on the slippery road
after heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
Their bodies were flown back to Kampala Tuesday. The body of
Rashid Mudin was buried later in the day at a cemetery in Kampala
while that of Richard Tebere would be laid to rest at his
home town in Gulu district Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
