<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspaper on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is considering
holding a referendum on a United States proposal calling on the
Jewish state to withdraw from 15 percent of the West Bank, an
advisor to Netanyahu said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan said that a final decision on the referendum
would be made in a few days.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The Jerusalem Regional Planning and Building Board Tuesday
approved an expansion plan for the Beit Orot yeshiva (religious
school) in the traditionally Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, 48 housing units will be built for students on
the yeshiva grounds.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority has responded to the plan by
calling for a "full-scale mobilization" against Israel's
settlement policy.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Ahanorot:
</P>
<P>
-- Incumbent Histadrut Chairman Amir Peretz of the Labor party
scored a landslide victory Tuesday over Knesset (Parliament)
member Maxim Levy of the Gesher party in the election of the union
leader.
</P>
<P>
Some 42 percent of the Histadrut members cast the votes, the
lowest turnout in the union's elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
