<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Meets With Vietnamese Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Chi Haotian, the Defense Minister
and Vice-chairman of China's Central Military Commission, in a
meeting here today with Vietnam's National Defense Minister
General Pham Van Tra, said that China and Vietnam had fast
recovery and development in bilateral friendly cooperative ties in
politics, the economy, science and technology and cultural affairs
after they resumed normal diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that the two countries have common
interests and a common wish to further the mutual friendship, and
that jointly safeguarding and developing this relationship will
have far-reaching significance.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese Communist Party, the Chinese government and the
People's Liberation Army place great importance on Sino-Vietnamese
relations. We are willing to make a joint effort with Vietnam in
furthering friendly ties between the two countries and the two
armies," Chi said.
</P>
<P>
Military relations have greatly improved in recent years, he
said, and they have agreed to have frequent contacts between the
leaders and the two armies to improve exchanges and
communications, he said. He hopes neighboring military commands
and border troops will increase their trust and friendship,
contacts, and cooperation so that border affairs can be properly
handled and the border can be built into a peaceful, quiet and
friendly area.
</P>
<P>
Chi said that the tense situation in South Asia was caused by
the nuclear arms race and that the "China threat" was merely made
up by some nations and is a rumor based on ulterior motives.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government was anxious and worried about the arms
race and urged the countries involved to show restraint and
immediately abandon the nuclear weapons development programs to
prevent further deterioration in the regional situation and to
keep peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Pham Van Tra said that Vietnam and China are both socialist
countries and that Vietnam places importance on its China ties and
that he is pleased to see the continued development of friendly
relations between the two countries. "Viet Nam will never forget
the sincere friendship and gigantic assistance given by the
Communist Party of China, the Chinese people, and the Chinese army
in our past struggle and economic construction," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed satisfaction with the two countries' military ties
and said he hopes that exchanges between the headquarters of the
general staff, the general political departments, and other military
units will increase.
</P>
<P>
Xiong Guangkai, the PLA's deputy chief of general staff, Yuan
Shoufang, the deputy director of the PLA General Political
Department, and Li Junlian, deputy political commissar of PLA
naval forces attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
