<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiations to Sell Zambia's Copper Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations to sell Zambia
Consolidated Copper Mines' Nchanga and Nkana mines between the
Zambian government and the Kafue Consortium finally collapsed.
</P>
<P>
The development follows the decision by the sole bidder's two
remaining members to abandon the project after "unfruitful
negotiations" with representatives of the Zambian government, The
Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nchanga and Nkana are two biggest copper mines in Zambia which
account for 65 percent of the country's total copper production.
</P>
<P>
Both Commonwealth Development Corporation (CDC), the initiator
of the consortium, and South Africa's Anglo Vall (AVMIN) Tuesday
resolved to abandon the mining project following 16-month long
negotiations with Zambia's privatisation team.
</P>
<P>
CDC and AVMIN had reopened negotiations with the mines
privatisation team two weeks ago after two other members of the
Kafue Consortium -- United States' Phelps Dodge and Canada-based
Noranda Incorporated -- pulled out of the project.
</P>
<P>
Phelps Dodge and Noranda announced on May 29 their withdrawal
from the project, citing unfruitful and delayed negotiations
which had dragged on for 15 months without even a memorandum of
understanding being signed.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's privatisation team earlier in March rejected a 105
million U.S. Dollars' cash offer for the mine and a five-year
re-capitalization of one billion Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian side viewed the cash offer as being "too low".
</P>
<P>
The Kafue Consortium, however, raised their cash offer for the
country's two largest mines to 131 million Dollars including a 35
million debt assumption. But the offer was also rejected,
prompting the pullout of Noranda and Phelps Dodge from the
project.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of the negotiations currently left the Zambian
government with no alternative official bid from competing
investors except for unofficial expression of interest by
London-based Bycoon Lexmi Mittal and some Chinese corporations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
