<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Dollar Drops to 12-year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand dollar sank to
a 12-year low in trading with the American dollar Wednesday
despite the concern from the Reserve Bank over the easing of
monetary conditions.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand dollar slid below the 50 U.S. cents mark,
closing at 0.4932, a level not seen since December 1986.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank said Wednesday morning it was concerned about
the recent fall of the New Zealand dollar. But it did not say it
would take immediate actions to stop the currency's slide.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the bank was worried that a low New Zealand
dollar would push up the prices of imported goods such as petrol,
cars, clothing and factory machinery. Price rises would threaten
Reserve Bank Governor Don Brash's agreement with the government to
 keep inflation below 3 percent, they said.
</P>
<P>
The slump in the New Zealand dollar has pushed up short-term
interest rates on the monetary market, with the 90-day bill rate
topping 10 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It also brought down the share market, which fell 1.5 percent
at the close Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
