<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Chief Calls for Consensus in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Commonwealth
Secretary-General Emeka Anyaoku has urged succession arrangements
in Nigeria to reflect genuine national consensus where the new
leadership is committed to programs aimed at restoring democracy
to the sprawling west African nation.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with The Herald here Tuesday, Anyaoku said his
office was anxiously waiting for new Nigerian leader General
Abdusalam Abubakar's policy statement on the future of that
country, the daily newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar took over from former military strongman General Sani
Abacha who died of cardiac arrest in the Nigerian capital Abuja
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure that all Nigerians would want to ensure that peace
prevails... We are all waiting to hear his statement on the
future program he has for his country," he said, adding that he
hopes it will be a "program that will return Nigeria speedily to
a democratically-elected government."
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku said the new government should also have a program
that will lead to the release of political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Before his death Abacha had promised to hold elections on
August 1 as part of the process to return the country to civilian
rule.
</P>
<P>
"Given that Abubakar was in Abacha's government, we do not see
a problem of him carrying over from where his colleague left
off," Anyaoku said.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth chief said there would be no logical case for
the new leadership to ask for an extension of time before
democracy returns to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, he said, remained expelled from the Commonwealth and
will only be readmitted after a democratically-elected government
is put in place.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku was in Harare to consult with Zimbabwean Minister of
Finance Herbert Murerwa on the coming Ottawa meeting of the
Commonwealth ministers of finance.
</P>
<P>
Earlier he had been to Mozambique where he met President
Joaquim Chissano on developments in that country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
