<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Chinese Officials Consulting Economists More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Some local Chinese officials and
entrepreneurs have discovered that economists can be useful in
solving problems as some recent lectures have shown.
</P>
<P>
Six economists and scholars from the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences and the Ministry of Agriculture aroused a great interest
over the past few days in the city of Changzhi in north China's
Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
They were invited by the local government to give three-hour
lectures each on topics like China's present economic situation,
agricultural industrialization, industrial restructuring, the
share holding system of businesses, and the government's role in a
market economy.
</P>
<P>
Many of the local officials and entrepreneurs who attended the
lectures seemed to share the same view that awareness of the
country's macro-economic policies and present economic situation
could help them find practical solutions to various problems.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of the Chnagzhi City Committee of the Communist
Party of China, Yan Aiying, said that the event was a good way to
improve the quality of the work of the officials and entrepreneurs
and a way to help free them from old ideas and find new ways to
develop the economy.
</P>
<P>
China is going through a critical period of economic reforms,
and local officials and entrepreneurs are encountering various
problems in the process, which they hope can be solved with
theoretical guidance from knowledgeable people.
</P>
<P>
Jin Bei, a prominent economist from the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences, says that he has received invitations from many
places across China and has to use every weekend for the next
several months for these lectures.
</P>
<P>
Academic sources say that many prominent economists have been
invited to be economic advisors for local governments. Changzhi,
in fact, is preparing to establish an advisory relationship with
the Academy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Blamed for Student Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government army is
held mostly responsible for the Monday massacre in which dozens
of students of Kichwamba National Technical Institute were burnt
to death, said a military source.
</P>
<P>
Charles Angina, second division army commander, was quoted by
Wednesday's New Vision daily as blaming the massacre on the
cowardice by the government army at the institute who he said
never put up a fight.
</P>
<P>
Angina said detachment commander Lieutenant Rajab Kasozi had
been arrested and would be sent to the martial court.
</P>
<P>
"Any sentence passed, be it hanging or firing squad, will be
done here in Kichwamba to show that the army takes seriously the
lives of the Ugandans," he told a mass rally in western Kabarole
district Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I am disturbed by the fact that this commander was not
cooperative to the local community, that he was seen
communicating to suspected enemy forces. Maybe that's why he was
not even killed. He will face the army court," Angina added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a new commander had been posted to Kichwamba
and appealed to the masses to cooperate in fighting against the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 to 300 rebels of the Allied Democratic Front attacked
the college at 5:30 a.m. Monday, burning student' dormitories and
making abductions, inviting accusing fingers from across the
country and putting security forces on full alert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
