<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Talking of Further Assistance to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) said it is negotiating with the Zimbabwean government for
offering a concessional loan facility called the enhancement support
adjustment facility (ESAF) which may be made available next year.
</P>
<P>
IMF President Michael Camdessus, who is in Ouagadougou
attending the Organization of African Unity (OAU) summit, said in
an interview with the Zimbabwe News Agency Tuesday that the soft
loan facility will enable the financial institution to provide on
a permanent pooling support for the country's reform programs.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking soon after a meeting with Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe aside from the business of the OAU summit.
</P>
<P>
"I told the president that the IMF would like to help your
country and in view of the fall of the Zimbabwean Dollar and
impact on prices can provide support on the balance of payments
and foreign reserves which has already been approved," said
Camdessus.
</P>
<P>
He was talking about the stand facility approved which have
increased Zimbabwe's foreign reserves by two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
"We now intend to help with the ESAF arrangement to assist in
the structural adjustment and the challenges of the government,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Camdessus addressed the African leaders during the
economic session of the OAU summit, during which he suggested the
way forward for most of Africa's struggling economies.
</P>
<P>
"Trade liberalisation needed to be boosted while regional
economic cooperation needed to be fostered, good governance and
frontal attack on structural problems needed to be done," he
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
