<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peretz Reelected Israeli Trade Union Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Israel's incumbent Histadrut
(Trade Union) leader Amir Peretz was reelected with a landslide
Tuesday, according to the final tally announced by Israel Radio
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The tally gave Peretz, a lawmaker from the leading opposition
Labor party, more than 77 percent of the votes, while his
challenger, Knesset (Parliament) member Maxim Levy, of the Gesher
Party, received only 22 percent. About half of the estimated
600,000 Histadrut members cast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
This result was in line with that of the exit polls. After the
exit polls predicted a sweeping victory for him, Peretz, who
entered the election with a joint list with the ruling parties
Likud and Shas, celebrated in Tel Aviv Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
He declared that the joint list had proved that one thing that
can unite Israelis is "honest livelihood."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Gesher-Meretz candidate, Levy, received the
predicted result Tuesday night with a grim face.
</P>
<P>
The election got off to a rocky start Tuesday when several
polling stations failed to open. Some officials reported that
voting slips were missing and the parties accused each other of
fraud.
</P>
<P>
It was the first election victory for Peretz, who inherited his
position from Labor lawmaker Haim Ramon. The triumph is believed
to establish him as a prominent political figure, as well as a
leader of the nation's workers.
</P>
<P>
Under the name of the Histadrut, Peretz has launched several
countrywide labor strikes since the Likud-led coalition came to
power in 1996 to protest the government's belt-tightening policy
that drastically cut the workers' pension and other welfare
benefits.
</P>
<P>
Histadrut holds elections every four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
