<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine to Address Food Shortage in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
constituted a transition food plan for southern Mindanao to
address its food problem, which has affected more than 800,000
families or 2 million people in 10 provinces there.
</P>
<P>
In a report sent to President Fidel Ramos, acting Presidential
Management Staff chief Demetrio Ignacio said Wednesday that a
multi-agency meeting was held to discuss the short- and long-term
strategies to attend to the problem.
</P>
<P>
Ignacio said the meeting agreed to continue supplying food to
120,000 families still suffering food shortages until August 1998
in Mindanao as one of the short-term measures.
</P>
<P>
The other short-term measures include providing loan and
subsidy to some 140,000 families to purchase rice.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed to improve agricultural productivity as its
long-term strategy.
</P>
<P>
Under this strategy, the Department of Agriculture will improve
irrigation facilities and provide good quality seeds and
fertilizers to farmers.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 famine-related deaths have reported in Mindanao
since January 1998 when the massive food shortage began to hit the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
