<HEADLINE> Inspectors Being Sent To Look At Finances Of State Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-one-year-old Liu Deguang
received a letter this morning from Song Jidong, the mayor of the
city of Liuzhou in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region,
appointing him chief financial inspector of a state business.
</P>
<P>
This was the opening move in the region's decision to send
financial inspectors to large state-owned enterprises to control
the use of state assets, finances, and accounting, and to behave
as goverment property owners.
</P>
<P>
Seven other inspectors joined Liu in the work. The chief
financial inspector is a new phenomenon, Liu says, so he wants to
make a greater effort and to be better educated, to do a better
job.
</P>
<P>
The eight enterprises involved say they welcome the idea. "The
chief financial inspectors will help straighten out financial
affairs, and help enterprises avoid making mistakes in investment,
decision-making, and capital use, and will help prevent
corruption. They supervise and provide services at the same time,
so we need them badly," says Li Ziming, chairman of Liuzhou's
Yufeng Cement Group Co. Ltd., where Liu was sent.
</P>
<P>
The city's state-owned enterprises have more than 20 billion
yuan in assets, so sending finance inspectors there is a major
step by the city government to reform the state sector, Song,
the mayor of Liuzhou, comments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
