<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Parliament Begins Budget Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's Jatiya Sangsad
(parliament) started Wednesday morning its budget session amid a
political stand-off between the ruling and the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria would put the national
budget for the 1998-99 fiscal year Thursday at the third budget
session of the country's Seventh Parliament, under a decision of
the parliament's Business Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
The new budget would be adopted by June 30, when the current
fiscal year ends. Besides the budget, the session might also
consider some other bills, such as the Code of Civil Procedure
Amendment Bill, before it ends on July 10.
</P>
<P>
Members of parliament of the major opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party and the Jammat-e-Islami, who are still on way to
the Chittagong Hill Tracts in a protest march, did not attend the
Wednesday session of parliament, which was prorogued on May 13.
</P>
<P>
MPs of the opposition might attend the session Thursday after
their two-day "long march" towards the hill tracts which started
from Dhaka Tuesday in protest of the peace treaty the government
signed with the tribals last December. 
</P>
