<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Builds Water Pipes for Rural Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is building new water
supply pipes for 50,000 urban and rural families this year at an
estimated cost of 46.9 million U.S. dollars, sources at the
National Water Supply and Drainage Board said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said 280 water supply schemes are being implemented
and another 20 will be launched within this year to cover areas
urgently in need of safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
New strategies will be adopted to provide safe drinking water
to the increasing urban population and rapidly developing rural
areas, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
New water schemes are necessary to meet the expansion of urban
population, demand for safe drinking water in rural areas and the
high growth of industrial and commercial activity, the sources
noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, about 32,280 new connections were provided, of which
17,216 were for the rural sector.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the Community Water Supply and Sanitation Project
funded by the International Development Agency is making headway
in expanding the water supply coverage in rural areas, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Under this project, 172 village water supply schemes and 98
water supply schemes for schools were completed at a cost of about
9.33 million dollars last year, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
