<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Competition In China's Hotel Business Getting Fiercer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- As the competition gets more
intense in China, profit margins, room occupancy rates, and
productivity of Chinese tourism hotels drops, the overseas edition
of today's People's Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
A hotel construction boom that began in 1994 has resulted in
4,500 tourism hotels, many built with foreign funds. But, while
this growth kept abreast of the growing tourism, it also led to
room surpluses.
</P>
<P>
The office building boom, many of them located in downtown or
economically-important areas, has further intensified the
competition. By the beginning of this year, there was 2.5 million
square meters of new office space in Beijing, taking up half the
tourist hotel area of the city.
</P>
<P>
The oversupply is partly blamed on the hotel approval system,
under which the people involved in tourism in China have no say in
most of the tourist hotel projects.
</P>
<P>
In practice, the China National Tourism Administration is only
responsible for approving hotels with foreign funding. Just over
600 of the hotels now in existence were authorized by the
Administration, while the other 4,000 were approved by offices
outside the tourism business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
