<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Military Reintegration Talks Fail Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The second round of
negotiations to reintegrate armed resistance forces loyal to
deposed first prime minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh into the
government army failed Wednesday over a row on procedure.
</P>
<P>
The delegation loyal to Ranariddh insisted that firstly they
should talk about the ceasefire, then the pardoning of the
generals sentenced by Cambodian Military Court, including General
Nhiek Bun Chhay, and then the troop's reintegration.
</P>
<P>
But government negotiation team refused to talk about anything
else except the troop's integration.
</P>
<P>
General Hun Pheoung, chief of the resistance forces'
negotiation team, alleged that the government forces broke a
Japanese-sponsored ceasefire last month by attacking the
resistance stronghold of O'Smach on the Thai border.
</P>
<P>
"If they do not stop immediately, we will never have any faith
in these talks," he added.
</P>
<P>
The allegations were denied by government. Instead, General Dom
Vuthy, chief of the government's negotiation team, accused
resistance forces of trying to seek excuse to delay and refuse
handover of their forces to the government.
</P>
<P>
The first round of talks broke down after only ten minutes on
May 15, when government negotiators complained that two civilians
were among resistance negotiators.
</P>
<P>
The new five-member negotiation team of resistance forces led
by General Hun Pheoung are all military men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
