<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cut Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Compaq and Dell, two leading
computer makers of the United States, have introduced new lines of
powerful workstations and corporate computers, and cut the prices
of existing ones.
</P>
<P>
Compaq's AP400, one of its powerful and yet inexpensive new
lines, is the company's first workstation to use Intel's new 350-
and 400-MHz Pentium II processors and "bus" technology which
allows the processor to communicate with other components at high
speed.
</P>
<P>
Dell has also introduced two new lines in the OptiPlex family,
with a view to refining its strategy for corporate desktop PCs.
</P>
<P>
These workstations are targeted for use in "mainstream"
applications such as computer-aided design or Web content creation.
</P>
<P>
Compaq says it has cut prices of the existing line
of professional workstations up to 28 percent and the model 6000
workstations have price cuts of up to 20 percent. Upgrades for
dual processor systems also have price cuts of up to 27 percent
and are available starting at 795 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The most recent round of price cuts comes as the company tries
to reduce bloated inventory levels that severely hurt its earnings
of the first quarter of 1998 .
</P>
<P>
Dell has been less affected by inventory woes affecting the
rest of the industry. But it has also cut its average selling
prices by 10 percent in the most recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
One of Dell's new OptiPlex family, the E1, is the company's
first product based on Celeron, the Intel processor for "basic"
computing. Dell's three new systems with Celeron and Pentium II,
marketed between this week and mid-July, are priced at 1,326,
1,963 and 2,750 dollars respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
