<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Former State Chief Minister Charged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's former Selangor
state chief minister Muhammad Haji Muhamad Taib was charged at the
Sessions Court here Wednesday with failing to declare his and his
family's assets last year.
</P>
<P>
He was charged with committing the offense on May 26 last year
under the Prevention of Corruption Act 1961.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad, accompanied by his wife Asbi Rohani Asnan and other
family members, appeared calm when the charge against him was read
out.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad, who was acquitted last May 29 by Australia's Brisbane
District Court of two charges of making a false declaration
pertaining to the amount of money he was bringing into Australia
on December 16, 1996 and failure to declare 1.26 million
Australian dollars (about 2.9 million ringgit or 0.75 million U.S.
dollars) when he was leaving for New Zealand six days later,
pleaded not guilty at the Sessions Court here.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad's case will be heard Wednesday afternoon at the High
Court here after the Sessions Court allowed a prosecution request
to commute the case to the High Court.
</P>
<P>
Judge Mohamad K. Abdul Rahman also allowed Muhammad a bond of
10,000 ringgit (about 2,500 U.S. dollars) without surety to ensure
Muhammad's presence at the High Court.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad, 53, is charged with knowingly ignoring conditions in
a statutory declaration dated May 23, 1997 by only declaring
assets worth, at the time of acquisition, 10.82 million ringgit
(about 2.705 million U.S. dollars or 3.46 million Australian
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Public Prosecutor had required Muhammad to declare one by
one all movable and immovable assets belonging to him or owned by
his agents or trustees, wife and children.
</P>
<P>
He is alleged to have committed the offense at the office of
the Deputy Public Prosecutor at the Anti-Corruption Agency
headquarters in Pesiaran Duta here on May 26 last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the Act, Muhammad faces a maximum sentence of one year
imprisonment or a fine of 2,000 ringgit (about 250 U.S. dollars)
or both upon conviction.
</P>
<P>
Muhammad resigned as chief minister following the Australian
court case and last Monday the ruling United Malays National
Organization (UMNO) Supreme Council extended Muhammad's leave as
the party vice-president.
</P>
<P>
During the trial at the Brisbane District Court, Muhammad said
that he had purchased properties valued at more than 10.4 million
ringgit (about 2.6 million U.S. dollars) in Australia and New
Zealand under the name of his wife Asbi Rohani Asnan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
