<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection In Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shanxi Province
has made progress in its effort to protect the environment
and has brought 7 environmental indexes up to standard, according
to the Provincial Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The seven indexes include sulfur dioxide and dust discharge
amounts, which are now under control, waste water, 85 percent of
which has been treated, and drinking water, 97 percent of that for
cities having been brought up to standard.
</P>
<P>
The province began pollution treatment projects in 1996 and has
closed down more than 9,000 pollution causing small enterprises,
and has cut down industrial waste water discharges by 9.47 million
tons annually, waste gas by 17.8 billion cuber meters, and solid
waste by 7.16 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The number of coal-based producers was down 60 percent in 1997,
but their production capacity increased by 1.26 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
