<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, June 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar's crude oil and natural gas sector, which
draws the largest share of foreign investment, grew by 37.7
percent in the fiscal 1997-98 ended March.
</P>
<P>
The production of crude oil increased to 6.1 million barrels
from 3.8 million barrels in the 1996-97 fiscal year, said a latest
 official report Wednesday on Myanmar's financial, economic and
social conditions issued by the Ministry of National Planning and
 Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
The output of natural gas rose to 68,540 million cubic-feet
(1,940 million cubic-meter) from 58,579 million cubic-feet (1,658
million cubic-meter) in the previous year, it
said. (Myanmar-Oil-Growth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia's central bank has decided to take steps
to strengthen small and medium-scale businesses in the country,
The Jakarta Post Wednesday quoted a top official of the central
bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
Miranda Gultom, director of the central bank, Bank Indonesia
(BI), said that the central bank would boost its contribution of
total supply of subsidized credit to 100 percent from 65 percent
last year. (Indonesia-Small Businesses)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand's exports of tapioca rose by 49.24 percent
to 9.64 billion baht (224 million U.S. dollars) in value in the
first four months of this year, the Nation reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Foreign Trade Department,
the volume of tapioca exports fell by 9.05 percent to 1.62 million
 tons.
</P>
<P>
The value of tapioca pellet exports in the same period
increased by 30.55 percent to 4.95 billion baht (115 million
dollars), though volume declined by 13.82
percent. (Thailand-Export)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina announced on Tuesday the issue of a
12-year European Market Debt Bond, valued at one billion German
marks (570 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Economy, the term of the bond will
expire on July 6, 2010.
</P>
<P>
The yield of the bond, issued by the Deutsche Bank, will be
8.25 percent in the first four years, and 9 percent per year for
the rest of the term. (Argentina-Europe-Bond)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The number of passenger cars sold in May 1998 dropped
by a very high 55.3 percent from 6,603 units a year ago to only
2,951 units, according to the latest statistics from the Chamber
of Automotive Manufacturers of the Philippines Inc.
</P>
<P>
In a report published Wednesday, the chamber said car sales
have been on the downtrend for the past year and was aggravated by
 the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The statistics showed that for the first five months total
sales reached 17,111, down 50 percent from 33,912 units sold in
the same period in 1997. (Philippines-Car Sales)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU -- The African Development Bank (ADB) Tuesday
warned that the economic growth in Africa over the past few years
was still not strong enough to reduce poverty in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The efficiency of investment to Africa must also be improved in
poverty alleviation, ADB President Omar Kabbaj stated at the
current summit meeting of the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
The average growth rate of near five percent achieved by
African countries in recent years is fragile and vulnerable to the
problems in Africa, he noted. (Burkina-ADB-African Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON) -- Proposals to reform the structure of the London
International Financial Future and Options Exchange (LIFFE)
received overwhelming support from the Exchange's membership at an
Extraordinary General Meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Voting at the meeting represented a 77 percent turnout with 98
percent in favor of the Resolution and 2 percent against,
according to an announcement by LIFFE.
</P>
<P>
The LIFFE's strategy document states that it will develop a new
Automated Trading Platform for financial futures to be introduced
in the second quarter of 1999. (UK-Exchange-Reform)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Intel Corp. is stepping up the use of pricing as a
weapon to protect its biggest business and to expand into new
markets.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday that the giant chip
maker dropped prices by 12 percent to 32 percent on its flagship
Pentium II microprocessors Monday, the third cut this year as
Intel reacts to slowing demand for personal computers and to
rivals at the low end of the market. Microprocessors act like the
heart of PCs, and Intel dominates the field with about 85 percent
of the market. (New York-Intel-Price Cut)  
</P>
</TEXT>
