<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Nuclear Tests Create Ukraine Uncertainty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine may reconsider an agreement
over its own nuclear protection, promised by the five nuclear
nations, if India and Pakistan are accepted as world nuclear
powers.
</P>
<P>
This possibility of a policy change was stated on June 6 by the
Ukrainian representative to the United Nations, Vladimir Yelchenko.
</P>
<P>
He made the point at the U.N. Security Council's meeting on the
situation after the detonation of nuclear weapons by India and
Pakistan, an official from the Ukraine Foreign Ministry told a
press conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
If the nuclear race in South Asia continued in an escalating
manner, Ukraine would reserve its right to re-open talks with the
five recognized nuclear powers, Director of the Press Bureau
Viktor Nagaichuk quoted Yelchenko as saying.
</P>
<P>
After its independence in 1992, Ukraine inherited all the
nuclear weapons left over in its territory by the former Soviet
Union, and actually became the third biggest nuclear power at the
time.
</P>
<P>
In January 1994, Ukraine signed a treaty with Russia and the
United States, agreeing to send all its nuclear weapons to Russia
and have them destroyed there.
</P>
<P>
Upon the signing of the treaty, the five existing nuclear
nations each announced their nuclear protection for Ukraine, who
later also became a signatory to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation
Treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Becomes First Latin American Country to Chart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Colombia has become the
first Latin American country to produce a chart of hydroclimatic
risks.
</P>
<P>
The chart, which indicates risks from climatic changes ranging
from drought to flood, in various regions, will contribute to good
harvests in the country, an official said.
</P>
<P>
The chartered map was based on the survey and research of
natural disasters which frequently haunt the country by experts
employed by the Agrarian Administration, its president, Sigifredo
Ardila, said.
</P>
<P>
The chart is composed of four volumes. The first, which went
into use last Saturday, covers the Caribbean area. The other
three regions of the country will be available to the public free
within the next two months.
</P>
<P>
Canada and the United States are the only other countries in
the whole of the American continents to have utilized this system
to reduce agrarian risks, said Ardila.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the chart, Colombian farmers can plan their
crop seasons more precisely and achieve better economic results,
said Ardila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
