<HEADLINE> Two New Lots of Loans to Be Auctioned in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Two new lots of hire-purchase
loans of Thailand's 56 closed finance companies will be auctioned
along with seven previously announced ones, the Bangkok Post
Wednesday reported.
</P>
<P>
With the two new lots, worth 5.7 billion baht (132.6 million
U.S. dollars), the first sale of the core assets of the 56
companies contains virtually all the hire-purchase assets of the
companies, Financial Restructuring Authority (FRA) Chairman Amaret
Sila-On said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The nine lots comprise 336,973 auto hire-purchase loans with a
total outstanding balance of about 51.7 billion baht (1.2 billion
dollars), Amaret said.
</P>
<P>
The FRA had earlier planned to begin the core-assets auction on
June 18, but had to postpone for one week due to heavy interest
shown by investors.
</P>
<P>
After the hire-purchase loans auction, the FRA is expected to
put mortgage loans under hammer.
</P>
<P>
The FRA said it hopes to start auctioning off 5,000-6,000
mortgage loans worth 25 billion baht (581 million dollars) by
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
Asset quality for the mortgage loans portfolio was good, with
non-performing loans accounting for less than 10 percent of the
total, the authority said.
</P>
<P>
The FRA also announced Tuesday that a limited number of
vehicles would be available for auction starting at 50,000 baht
(1,162 dollars) each on June 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
