<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Oil, Gas Sector Grows in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's crude oil and natural gas
 sector, which draws the largest share of foreign investment, grew
by 37.7 percent in the fiscal 1997-98 ended March, according to
the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The production of crude oil increased to 6.1 million barrels
from 3.8 million barrels in the 1996-97 fiscal year, said a latest
official report on Myanmar's financial, economic and social
conditions issued by the Ministry of National Planning and
Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
The output of natural gas rose to 68,540 million cubic-feet
(1,940 million cubic-meter) from 58,579 million cubic-feet (1,658
million cubic-meter) in the previous year, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report added that in the 1997-98 fiscal year, Myanmar was
able to drill more gas wells in the newly-developed Kyaukhwet and
Letpando oil fields, and boost production of old ones such as
Chauk, Yenangyaung and Mann.
</P>
<P>
During the fiscal year, Myanmar was also able to complete the
laying of pipelines to prepare for the planned sale of natural gas
to Thailand later this year from the Yadana gas field in the gulf
of Mottama.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is striving to increase the production of oil and gas
to meet its domestic demand as well as to increase export by
boosting the output of old gas wells and extensively drilling more
new ones.
</P>
<P>
To help achieve the aim, the country has been undertaking joint
exploration and production of oil and gas with a number of foreign
businesses.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, investments in the oil and
gas sector from companies of Australia, Britain, France,
Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Thailand and the United States were
nearly 2.3 billion U.S. dollars in 45 related projects at the end
of February this year, making up the largest part in the country's
7 billion dollar total foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show the country's economy achieved a
growth rate of 4.6 percent in the 1997-98 fiscal year. The average
annual growth rate in the previous five years (1992-93 to 1996-97)
was 7.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
