<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moorer Refuses Confirmation of Nerve Gas in Laos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A former chairman of the U.S.
Joint Chiefs of Staff, Thomas Moorer, said Tuesday he did not know
that sarin nerve gas was used by the American troops during the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
He denied that he confirmed its use to CNN television, the
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Moorer, who was chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff during
the Vietnam War, said he had simply heard unconfirmed rumors that
the toxic gas was used by U.S. Special Forces units, including in
a 1970 operation in Laos which is now under review by the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't have the authority to release the use of (sarin) gas
and I, of course, have never seen an operation order or battle
report or anything" referring to the use of the nerve agent,
Moorer told the AP.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Moorer as saying he couldn't entirely
discount the possibility that sarin gas was used by Special Forces.
</P>
<P>
"There were rumors that this gas had been used. But I tell
everybody, if they want to know, I don't know that they used it.
I don't know that they didn't use it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The CNN and Time Magazine reported Sunday, after an
eight-months investigation and interviews with hundreds of Vietnam
War-era U.S. military officials and soldiers, including Moorer,
that U.S. troops used sarin gas during Operation Tailwind in Laos,
and other missions.
</P>
<P>
Two U.S. defectors were supposedly killed in Operation Tailwind.
</P>
<P>
Despite Moorer's denial of confirmation, the CNN said Tuesday
that it stood by its story.
</P>
<P>
"Two hundred interviews and eight months of research, including
the statement of Admiral Moorer, leads us to absolutely believe in
the truthfulness of the story," said Steve Haworth, a vice
president of news at the CNN's Atlanta headquarters.
</P>
<P>
"Our story does not completely and solely depend on Admiral
Moorer, but Admiral Moorer certainly does support our story and in
no way contradicts our story."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered an
investigation into the allegations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
