<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Having to Adjust Its Grain Production (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's wheat supplies are sufficient, but a considerable
amount is still imported. But, as a senior executive of Beijing
Hengtong Food Co. Ltd. puts it, "It's not that we can't buy wheat
in China, it's just that the variety of home-grown wheat is
limited and does not meet our specific demands." Hengtong is a big
producer of flour products, which imports 20,000 to 40,000 tons of
wheat annually.
</P>
<P>
"Some 70 percent of the bread, cakes, and biscuits sold in
Beijing's restaurants and shopping malls are made from imported
wheat," he says.
</P>
<P>
Importing wheat is not an unusual practice in China, because
other types of grain like malting barley are also imported,
according to a China National Liangfeng Grain Import &AMP; Export
Corp. official.
</P>
<P>
In addition to problems coming from the irrational planting of
grain, the marketing system also produces sales problems.
According to a State Development Planning Commission official, the
existing grain distribution system has become less and less suited
to the nation's grain production and to changes in supply and
demand.
</P>
<P>
The good news however, is that both the Chinese government and
farmers have come to realize the importance of grain production
and marketing. Premier Zhu Rongji has called for immediate reforms
in the nation's grain marketing system, to bring a new era of
grain production.
</P>
<P>
In this system, farmers would sign contracts with grain dealers
instead of relying on the government, and would only grow the
grain they could plant and sell. Again, Hubei is an example.
Farmers there have reduced the amount of rice acreage and
increased the amount used for corns, beans, and peanuts this year.
</P>
<P>
Industry insiders say that these grain sales problems will
really be solved once the market laws are obeyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export Value of Thai Tapioca Jumps in 1st 4 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports of tapioca rose
by 49.24 percent to 9.64 billion baht (224 million U.S. dollars)
in value in the first four months of this year, the Nation
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Foreign Trade Department,
the volume of tapioca exports fell by 9.05 percent to 1.62 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
The value of tapioca pellet exports in the same period
increased by 30.55 percent to 4.95 billion baht (115 million
dollars), though volume declined by 13.82 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tapioca flour exports reached 360,000 tons worth
4.68 billion baht (109 million dollars), a rise of 11.97 percent
and 75.88 percent respectively during the first four months of
1998 compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The drop of the 1997-98 output by 16.92 percent to 14.68
million tons from that of the previous year has led to a price
rise in the domestic market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
