<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Central Bank to Strengthen Small Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's central bank has
decided to take steps to strengthen small and medium-scale
businesses in the country, The Jakarta Post Wednesday quoted a top
official of the central bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
Miranda Gultom, director of the central bank, Bank Indonesia
(BI), said that the central bank would boost its contribution of
total supply of subsidized credit to 100 percent from 65 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 35 percent of last year's subsidized credit was
previously contributed by the country's commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Under the government's January 1990 deregulation package, the
central bank's role in providing subsidized credit to small and
medium-scale businesses was to be reduced gradually and replaced
by the increasing role of commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
"But it is unrealistic to expect such a thing at the moment,"
Miranda said.
</P>
<P>
She explained that it was impossible for commercial banks to
provide subsidized credit at an interest rate of 16 percent, while
they had to raise funds with an interest rate of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's banking system is currently at its lowest point,
battered by the monetary crisis, mounting bad debt and poor
management.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, BI said in a statement published Tuesday that its
net claims on the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA)
jumped to 132.12 trillion rupiah (11.49 billion U.S. dollars) on
June 5 from 124.63 trillion rupiah (10.84 billion dollars) the
previous week.
</P>
<P>
The increase was mainly caused by a rise in liquidity
injections into troubled banks being supervised by IBRA, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the central bank's net
international reserves on June 5 were reported at 14.62 billion
dollars, 8.4 million dollars less than on May 29.
</P>
<P>
Despite the decline, the statement said, the net international
reserves figure is still above the minimum level allowed by the
International Monetary Fund. But the central bank did not mention
the limit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
