<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Having To Adjust Its Grain Production(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- After several successful harvests,
Chinese farmers are finding it difficult to sell their grain and
evidence points to the fact that China is shifting from a seller's
market to the buyer's.
</P>
<P>
This has prompted the Chinese government to put adjusting grain
production high on its agenda.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of new China in 1949, the central
government's top concern has been increasing grain output to feed
the largest population in the world. But, the emphasis on quantity
instead of quality, coupled with the centrally-controlled grain
distribution system had a negative effect on the nation's grain
production.
</P>
<P>
Farmers of Hubei Province, a major grain producer in central
China, for example, had 48.6 percent more surplus grain per capita
last year than in 1996, but per capita income from grain was 73
yuan (8.7 US dollars) less simply because they couldn't sell their
grain. To make matters worse, this dampenned farmers' enthusiasm
for growing grain somewhat, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
In spite of repeated grain harvests, China's per capita grain
output still stands at less than 400 kg. The major problem in grain
sales lies in severed link between production and marketing,
according to some economists.
</P>
<P>
Grain demand has changed considerably, they point out, and
consumers no longer rely solely on rice, corn, and wheat, but have
turned instead to a greater variety of foods like meat, fruits,
and other flour products.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Endorses Partial Thai Airways Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has endorsed the
partial privatization of the national flag-carrier Thai Airways
International proposed by the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, the ministry will sell 380 million shares
of the airways, comprising the 280 million shares that it already
owns and 100 million new shares, today's Bangkok Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will retain a 67.99 percent stake in the airways
after the sale. With the three percent stake held by the Thai
private sector, the sale will be in line with the Civil Aviation
Act requiring the state to maintain control of not less than 70
percent of the airline.
</P>
<P>
"The cabinet has approved in principle the sale of the shares,
but has not yet decided on how to sell the shares and the prices,"
Supachai Pisitvanich, the ministry's permanent secretary, said
after the regular weekly meeting.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also endorsed the appointment of a committee headed
by Supachai to hire a consultant firm to underwrite the shares of
the airways.
</P>
<P>
A government source said the next step would be to reduce the
stake of the state to 50 percent so as to provide an incentive for
foreign investors to take part.
</P>
<P>
The source said the Finance Ministry expects to sell most of
the shares to foreign strategic partners such as the Star Alliance
to enable Thai Airways International to benefit from their
aviation know-how. The Star Alliance members include Air Canada,
Lufthansa and Thai Airways International.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government, confronted by a devastating economic
crisis which began with the float of the baht last July, is
committed to the partial privatization of several state
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
