<HEADLINE> Hungary Voices Concern over Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Hungarian government on
Tuesday urged the warring parties in the troubled Yugoslavian
province of Kosovo to begin talks amid concern over the escalating
tension.
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian Foreign Ministry said it feared the conflict
would spread to neighboring regions and jeopardize regional
stability.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also stressed that Hungary supported the stand
taken by the United Nations, the European Union and NATO in
pushing for a peaceful compromise and making sure basic human
rights were guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Kosovo mounted on March 1 after an armed conflict
which led to the deaths of four policemen and 16 Albanians. At
least 250 people were killed in later clashes between Serb forces
and ethnic Albanian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of the population
in Kosovo, have been seeking independence from Yugoslavia since
1981. 
</P>
