<HEADLINE> 7 Killed in Fresh Fighting in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- At least three suspected Muslim
rebels were killed Tuesday as fighting between guerrillas of the
rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) and government forces
continued in a southern Philippine province.
</P>
<P>
In a report published Wednesday, the military said suspected
rebels also killed four persons and wounded 12 others in a raid
late Monday in Ipil town in the same province, Zamboanga del Sur.
</P>
<P>
Government soldiers have overrun a training camp of Muslim
rebels in the town of Tungawan, several kilometers from Ipil, a
predominantly Christian town.
</P>
<P>
The military offensive, which started June 4, is aimed at
flushing out about 200 MILF fighters believed to be behind a
series of highway robberies and extortion activities in the
Zamboanga Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Horacio Lapinid, chief of the Southern Command Public
Relation Office, said suspected rebels lobbed homemade bombs and
strafed houses in Ipil town to ease military pressure in
neighboring Tungawan town.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF) which already signed a peace treaty with
the government.
</P>
<P>
The MILF refused to be included in the peace treaty but is
negotiating with the government for a similar peace agreement.
</P>
