<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0200 GMT, June 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Union Tuesday expressed its deep
concern at the deteriorating violence in Yugoslavia's province of
Kosovo and urged international monitoring in the region.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union said in a written statement that it
strongly condemned a new wave of ethnic cleansing in the form of
widespread house-burning and indiscriminate artillery attacks on
whole villages.
</P>
<P>
The union insisted on an immediate stop to all violent action
and called for the withdrawal of the Yugoslav special police and
army units from Kosovo. (EU-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISTANBUL -- Foreign ministers from the Balkan countries
announced Tuesday that the Kosovo issue, which has caused serious
concern in the region, has to be settled through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
In an official statement issued at the end of the two-day
Balkan Foreign Ministerial Meeting here, the foreign ministers
strongly emphasized the need for resumption of the dialog between
Belgrade and the representatives of Kosovo. (Balkan-Ministerial
Meeting-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada's spring this year was the warmest ever
officially recorded in the country, reports said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The average temperature in Canada over the past three months
was more than 3.1 degrees centigrade above normal, making it the
warmest spring the country has experienced since 1948.
</P>
<P>
The warm spring follows a mild winter as Canada experienced the
effects of a strong El Nino, which is now weakening in the Pacific
Ocean. (Canada-Spring-Warmth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South Africa's National Assembly Tuesday passed
a legislation to extend the life of the Truth and Reconciliation
Commission (TRC), according to Justice Minister Dullah Omar.
</P>
<P>
The new bill will allow the TRC to submit an interim report on
October 31 this year, and enable its Amnesty Committee to conduct
more than 1,000 outstanding amnesty application hearings, South
African Press Association quoted Justice Omar as
saying. (SAfrica-Truth Commission)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Global action is needed to reduce the ability
of criminals to hide illegal profits from drug trafficking,
according to a U.N. report released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In its report on Financial Havens, Banking Secrecy and
Money-Laundering, the U.N. Office for Drug Control and Crime
Prevention said most money-laundering schemes involve the use of
financial havens.
</P>
<P>
Finding criminally derived incomes and assets has been made
more difficult because of the dollarization of black markets,
financial deregulation, the progress of the Euro market and the
proliferation of financial havens, the 118-page report
said. (UN-Drugs-Money-Laundering)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least 56 people were killed and more than 50
others injured when a cyclone lashed coastal areas of West India
Tuesday at speeds up to 120 kilometers per hour, the Press Trust
of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The cyclone, caused by a deep depression in the Arabian Sea,
flattened homes and snapped communication links in the coastal
areas of Gujarat and Jalore District of Rajasthan. (India-Cyclone)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Improved arrangements under the oil-for-food
program for Iraq are facilitating the delivery of more
humanitarian supplies to the country, but problems still remain,
according to a new report of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report showed a general increase in the range and volume of
humanitarian supplies reaching Iraq, but supplies continue to be
erratic. The secretary-general expressed concern that the full
"food basket" was only delivered once to the Iraq's people, and
called for further coordination between the government and the
United Nations to ensure that humanitarian aid applications are
processed in order of priority. (UN-Aid-Iraq) 
