<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Turning to Intensive Agriculture in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Chongqing, who used
to rely on expanding their farmland for grain harvests, now have
learned to increase their output through scientific methods.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing in southwest China has the largest rural population
and farmland among the four municipalities directly under the
central government. However, its per capita output has been
decreasing in recent years as its population increased.
</P>
<P>
As a result, traditional farming patterns reached an
impasse. Some farmers have turned to scientific agricultural
methods and reaped better harvests on the same tracts of land.
</P>
<P>
An application of better quality seeds is one of the farmers'
favorite choices. Liu Xueping, a farmer in Shizhu County, said
that his high-yield, oil-rich corn not only survived this year's
severe drought but also outgrew all other corn crops.
</P>
<P>
By using plastic film, farmers now harvest more than 6,000 kg
of maize per hectare, compared with 3,000 kg by traditional
methods. However, the oil-rich variety of maize can yield 10
percent more in output than other varieties relying on plastic
sheeting, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
More and more farmers like Liu are becoming better off by
 introducing advanced agro-technology. The city's per capita
farmland amounts to less than one-15th hectare, but its per
hectare yield has more than doubled because of the widespread use
of scientific farming methods, which have now become the major
means for higher grain output, according to Gu Wenyu, deputy
director of the city's Agriculture Department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0327 </DOCNO>
