<HEADLINE> Indonesia Ratifies ILO Convention '87 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
has formally ratified the International Labor Organization (ILO)
Convention '87 on the freedom of association and protection of
workers' rights to set up organizations, Antara News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a press release issued by the Manpower
Ministry as saying that the president has issued Presidential
Decree No. 83/1998, signed on June 5, providing for the
ratification of the ILO convention.
</P>
<P>
The ratification will bind the signatory to carry out all the
world governing body's rulings which are basically made to
guarantee the exercise of freedom of association by workers and
employees.
</P>
<P>
The convention consists of four chapters and 21 articles that
spell out the freedom of association, protection of the right of
workers to set up organizations, other rulings and concluding
provisions.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the annual meeting of the ILO in Geneva Tuesday,
Indonesian Minister of Manpower Fahmi Idris said that Indonesia
would soon ratify separate conventions against forced labor and
discrimination, as well as the Minimum Age Convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
