<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Retracts Pro-Imelda Plea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' new chief
government lawyer has asked the Supreme Court to let stand a
12-year jail sentence on former first lady Imelda Marcos for
corruption, the newspaper Philippine Daily Inquirer said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that Solicitor General Silvestre Bello on
Tuesday withdrew a petition filed last week by his predecessor,
Romeo de la Cruz, which had sought Imelda Marcos' acquittal on
corruption charges on the ground that she had been erroneously
convicted.
</P>
<P>
De la Cruz was fired by President Ramos two days after he filed
the controversial petition to the Supreme Court. Bello, who is
also justice secretary, was appointed to replace de la Cruz.
</P>
<P>
A special anti-graft court in 1993 convicted Imelda Marcos,
widow of former president Ferdinand Marcos, of corruption in
connection with a real estate deal in which the government
allegedly lost money, and sentenced her to up to 24 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
She appealed the verdict before the Supreme Court, which upheld
the conviction but lowered the punishment to 12 years
imprisonment. But Imelda Marcos, 68, remains free on a second
appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
