<HEADLINE> China Plans To Use Internet To Shop For Hollywood Movies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- This past Monday, China opened a
Website on the Internet that it can use to place orders for
Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
The site is on Chinacue, the Internet designation for art
topics, which will be used by the Hollywood Classics Co. Ltd. The
first group of movies will be new ones from the 1990s and some
1940s classics.
</P>
<P>
The site also provides information about movies and shows not
currently available. But some Chinese surfers have been already
watching Western movies with the help of the site known as Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
Several European companies will also enter the Chinese market
through the new site, providing copyrights to Chinese film and TV
producers.
</P>
<P>
The new Website was set up by the China Federation of Literary
and Art Circles and the Beijing Telegraph Bureau and is the best
place for Chinese and foreign artists to share their views and a
place for Chinese to learn about more things from abroad,
according to the Federation's Shao Mujun.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the Website is the effect of the combination
of a market economy and technology, and China's opening up. The
commercialization of culture is now common in China, and
money-losing state film studios and artists and publishers are all
urging that an easy information channel be created.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Culture Sun Jiazheng says that contacts with
foreigners should be increased because culture has become a
popular means of improving Sino-foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the Internet will have a complicated and
profound impact on culture. But, Chinese artists and writers are
new to the electronic age, especially when compared with the
fields of commerce, education, and science, and the number of
Internet users is small.
</P>
<P>
One commentator, Yan Peng, says, "There are no walls on the
Internet. We are therefore more directly, quickly and widely faced
with various cultures in the world. That will bring happiness, and
unexpected ideological shocks." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
