<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kodak-Financed Project Starts Construction in Xiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a
365-million-U.S. dollar photographic production plant, financed by
Eastman Kodak Company of the United States, began Tuesday in
Xiamen, a port city in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The plant, located in the Haicang Investment and Development
Zone, will have an area of 430,000 sq m and produce sensitive
emulsions, color films and photographic paper for all purposes.
</P>
<P>
The plant, to be built in two stages, will begin production of
photographic paper in mid-1999 and will start producing films by
the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
George Fisher, Kodak chairman and chief executive officer, who
presided over yesterday's ground-breaking ceremony for the new
plant, said the Haicang project would become one of Kodak's
largest production plants in the world.
</P>
<P>
The project is part of a deal struck earlier this year between
Eastman Kodak Company, the world leader in imaging, and the
Chinese Government. Under the agreement, the American partner will
invest one billion U.S. dollars in building a first-rate
photographic industry in China in cooperation with Chinese
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The investment will be used to increase Kodak's production
capacity in China, establish distribution networks, conduct
marketing activities, and assist technology upgrading of its local
imaging partners.
</P>
<P>
In late March, two other joint ventures -- Kodak-controlled
Chinese limited-liability companies of Kodak (China) Company
Ltd. and Kodak (Wuxi) Company Ltd -- were launched in Shanghai,
and in Wuxi of Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
According to Kodak estimates, China will become the largest
market for imaging products by 2010 or earlier. Three years ago,
China ranked the 17th largest market for Kodak, and it moved into
second place last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalian Machine Tools Group Striving to Increase Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Dalian Machine
Tools Group tried hard to overcome adverse effect of the financial
crisis inflicting East Asia by expanding international market and
achieved success marked by a sharp rise of 36.3 percent in exports
in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Previously, most of the conglomerate's exported commodities
were meant for Southeast Asia, but the financial crisis, which
first occurred in Southeast Asia late last year and has soon
spilled over to East Asia, made the Dalian group suffer a drop of
60 percent in its exports in three quarters of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, in the first three months of this year, the Dalian
group has received no orders from Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
To counter this situation, Dalian Machine Tools Group adjusted
its overseas marketing strategy and concentrated more efforts on
opening up new international market.
</P>
<P>
While increasing research on market demands and potential
competitors, the Dalian group has set up business offices or
marketing agent offices in places including South Africa, the
United States, and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
It has also adjusted product mix according to market demands
and practiced a wide range of measures to improve enterprise
recognition and improve capacity to react to market changes.
</P>
<P>
So far, sales volume of the group's export commodities to the
United States exceeded 120,481 U.S. dollars in the first quarter,
while sales volume of the group's export products to South
America surpassed 216,867 U.S. dollars during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Dalian Machine Tools Group delivered 41 million yuan (one
U.S. dollar equals to 8.3 yuan) worth of commodities for exports
in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
