<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges All Villages to Embrace Democracy (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The circular also demands that all CPC village branches and
villagers' committees across the country hold regular democratic
elections according to the law and Party regulations, and never
try to delay the elections when their terms of office come to an
end.
</P>
<P>
"The will of the voters must be respected," the circular
stresses. "No one is allowed to make any attempt to manipulate the
elections, or to canvass votes by any unjust means, especially
through various forms of bribery."
</P>
<P>
While ensuring the extensive democratic rights of the farmers,
it is also necessary to guide them to learn through practice how
to exercise their democratic rights in a correct way and in
accordance with the law, the circular adds.
</P>
<P>
During the 15th CPC National Congress held in Beijing last
September, Chinese President and CPC general-secretary Jiang Zemin
said in his keynote report that China would further expand
grassroots democracy and safeguard the direct exercise of
democratic rights by the people.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Chinese government has attached greater
importance to farmers' democracy, regarding it as a major issue
that will help promote reform, development and stability in the
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, at the 10th anniversary of the enforcement
of the Law on the Organization of the Villagers' Committee, the
State Council adopted a draft amendment to the law, which will
soon be submitted to the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, China's top legislature, for further
examination.
</P>
<P>
At its end, the circular also gives a message that China will
make bolder experiments in expanding democracy and increasing
government transparency.
</P>
<P>
"While promoting the open and democratic management of village
affairs in the countryside, we will also make active efforts to
seek proper ways to introduce the practice of open administration
to government bodies at the township level," it states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
