<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges All Villages to Embrace Democracy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Determined to promote democracy in
every corner of its vast countryside, the Chinese central
authorities are demanding that all officials in the country's
nearly one million villages manage village affairs in an open and
democratic way and subject themselves to the villagers'
supervision.
</P>
<P>
"Open and democratic management of village affairs is conducive
to developing grassroots democracy in the rural areas, and will
guarantee the direct exercise of democratic rights by the
farmers," says a circular jointly issued by the Central Committee
of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and the State Council, the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The circular, which was publicized here today, describes the
Chinese farmers, who account for more than 70 percent of the
country's 1.3 billion population as the "reliable force" for the
CPC in the countryside and the "most extensive and solid
foundation" for the political power of the nation.
</P>
<P>
In November of 1987 China adopted the Law on the Organization
of the Villagers' Committee which abolished the long practice that
village officials were hand-picked by governments at higher
levels. The law requires all members of the Villagers' Committee,
the formal village leadership, to be directly elected by the
entire village.
</P>
<P>
During the past decade, most villages across China have held
three direct elections on their villagers' committees. More than
60 percent of the villages have adopted a system called
"villagers' self-government," which means that the farmers not
only elect their own village leadership but also monitor its
operation and have a say in all major village affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980610.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Furniture Quality Good </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A sample survey indicates that
nearly 73 percent of furnitures made in Beijing, Shanghai, and
Guangdong are up to quality standards.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of a housing construction boom, furniture
manufacturers have been mushrooming in China, with the number
topping 30,000. However, the quality of the products often becomes
a focus of complaints from consumers.
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted by the State Bureau of Quality and
Technology Supervision examined 74 varieties of complete-set
bed-room wooden furniture and 58 varieties of single sofas, with
47 and 49 varieties meeting standard, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Major problems revealed by the survey include substandard level
of heat and humidity resistance and poor adhesion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
