<HEADLINE> EDS-Retransmission hke -- Former U.S. Secretary of State on Sino-U.S. Relations (Part I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Secretary of State
Alexander M. Haig has urged China and the United States to enhance
cooperation, while addressing differences through frequent high
level exchanges.
</P>
<P>
"China, as the largest developing country, and the United
States, as the largest developed country, merit a relationship
that is multi-dimensional -- each facet as important as the other
and no one strand held hostage to the other," General Haig said in
a written interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Describing Chinese President Jiang Zemin's trip last October to
the United States as a "triumphant visit," the general said the
visit was a major step in building on the momentum of positive
high level exchanges between the leaders of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Across the full breadth of my country, President Jiang
garnered the admiration and respect of the people with whom he
met," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The visit to China by President Bill Clinton later this month
should contribute to a better appreciation of the true value of a
strong U.S.-China relationship," Haig added.
</P>
<P>
"Most importantly during the Summit meeting in Washington,
D.C. between Presidents Clinton and Jiang, it was reaffirmed that
the interests between our two peoples are converging. We share
interests in regional and international peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
He said it was also important that the U.S. president once
again affirmed that there is but "One China" and that, "we, too,
have an interest in seeing the emergence of a China that is a
great power, stable, open and enjoying peaceful relationships with
like-minded countries worldwide."
</P>
<P>
Since Jiang's visit, there is a growing appreciation among more
Americans that the U.S. administration's policy of "constructive
engagement" with China is a sound policy.
</P>
<P>
By working together, the two countries can make possible new
opportunities for economic growth exceeding that which was
initially contemplated when China's late Chairman Mao Zedong,
Premier Zhou Enlai and former U.S. President Richard Nixon opened
the relationship.
</P>
<P>
Haig was a member of President Nixon's international security
team in the 1970s when Nixon proposed establishing a dialogue with
China.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the significance of a "constructive strategic
partnership," the general said the establishment of such a
partnership is the acknowledgment that the Sino-U.S. relationship
is more than the sum of its parts.
</P>
<P>
"The political, economic, and security dimensions combined
confirm the importance of a positive bilateral relationship," Haig
said. "However, when the multiplicity and breadth of U.S.-China
interests are put in context, the relationship takes on a
strategic character."
</P>
<P>
Since the summit last fall, Chinese and American government
agencies have been working to add greater substance to every facet
of their relationship, he said.
</P>
<P>
"With the economic dimension, our financial, monetary and trade
experts have worked to facilitate China becoming an even more
active member of the global market system," he said.
</P>
<P>
Similarly in the defense sector, there has been a multiplicity
of high level exchanges between members of the armed forces of the
two countries, he said. "Through the dialogues, our respective
militaries are working to enhance understanding and promote
cooperation all towards the preservation of peace and stability in
Asia and elsewhere."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
