<HEADLINE> Toronto Launches Internet Program for the Homeless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada's largest city of Toronto has
launched an Internet program, offering e-mail service to help
those living on the streets.
</P>
<P>
The inner-city initiative, called Voice to Screen, allows the
homeless to log on to the Internet, learn how to surf Websites for
places to live or work and send or receive e-mail for a small fee.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the homeless around the three community centers that offer
the service were reported to be unconvinced that logging on to the
Internet would make any difference in their daily struggle to
survive.
</P>
<P>
"I am interested in getting more money from the rich and making
them pay for the poor," a homeless woman was quoted as saying by
reports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new Internet program is funded jointly by the Industry
Department of Canada, the city of Toronto and non-government
organizations.
</P>
<P>
It is "an extraordinary innovation that will have an impact,"
said one proponent of the program.
</P>
<P>
But critics argue that such a plan fail to address the No.1
problem facing the homeless, a lack of affordable housing.
</P>
</TEXT>
