<HEADLINE> Riley Calls for Efforts for Safe, Drug-Free Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Education Secretary Richard
Riley on Tuesday called for more efforts to help curb school
violence and drugs in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Schools are being asked to pick up the pieces" from a society
that glorifies violence, accepts drugs and makes it easy for young
people to get guns, Riley told a Education Department conference
on the federal Safe and Drug-Free Schools program.
</P>
<P>
Although schools are generally safe, Riley said, a number of
fatal shootings by youngsters have raised concern.
</P>
<P>
He urged lawmakers to pass spending increases for drug and
violence prevention coordinators, delinquency and truancy
prevention and after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Congress to pass bills to improve literacy, build
schools and hire more teachers.
</P>
<P>
He said, prisons are full of high school dropouts who cannot
read, Riley said, yet Congress "continues to dilly dally and
dawdle" rather than enact a 2-year old, 2.4 billion U.S. dollars
proposal by President Bill Clinton to build a corps of reading
tutors.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Riley asked the National Rifle Association (NRA) to
help keep children from becoming victims of gun violence in
schools, in homes and in the street.
</P>
<P>
"I challenge the NRA to direct its attention to getting guns
out of the hands of unsupervised children."  
</P>
