<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Futures Plunge Further in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Crude oil futures prices fell
sharply Tuesday, threatening to topple more than 9-year lows on
the New York Mercantile Exchange, affected by continuous weak
demand and big supply.
</P>
<P>
Crude plunged after the International Energy Agency cut its
estimate for 1998 world oil demand because of the Asian economic
crisis. Daily demand was estimated at 75 million barrels a day,
down 100,000 barrels from earlier estimates.
</P>
<P>
Demand in Asian countries, excluding Japan and China, has
fallen some 750,000 barrels a day since October, according to the
Paris-based group's figures.
</P>
<P>
Asia, with its once booming regional economy, had been an
important area for absorbing heavy crude output by most of the 11
members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and
non-OPEC members such as Russia and Norway.
</P>
<P>
Analysts pointed to the International Energy Agency's estimate
that only 1.017 million barrels of the 1.245 million pledged by
OPEC countries in the first round of cuts were taken out of the
market in May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
