<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Retreats Against yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar on Tuesday soared
above 141 yen for the first time in seven years, but fell below
the previous day's close at profit taking by traders.
</P>
<P>
The dollar closed barely higher against the German mark in New
York trading, as investors paid more attention to dollar-yen
tradings.
</P>
<P>
At the closing, the dollar was quoted at 140.30 yen, down from
140.71 yen late Monday. During the trading day, the dollar rose to
141.35 yen, a level not seen since June 18, 1991.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was changing hands at 1.7805 marks in New York,
up from 1.7794 Monday.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday:
1.4762 Swiss francs, down from 1.4788; 5.9710 French francs, up
from 5.9680; 1,754.00 Italian lire, up from 1,753.50; and 1.4578
Canadian dollars, up from 1.4575.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6367 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6337 U.S. dollars.  
</P>
