<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says no Lifting of Sanctions against DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said
on Tuesday that he would be prepared to support South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung's "policy of reciprocity" toward the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), but would not
endorse his proposal to ease sanctions on the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remarks at a joint news conference with
President Kim after their talks at the White House.
</P>
<P>
"The United States applauds President Kim's efforts toward
reconciliation," he said. "Now we hope North Korea will respond
further to President Kim's gestures."
</P>
<P>
He said Kim had asked him to work with him to support the
"policy of reciprocity", and "I would be prepared to do that."
</P>
<P>
But when asked about the lift of sanctions, Clinton dodged a
direct answer, saying that would "require ... some legislative
change to be modified."
</P>
<P>
The South Korean leader, who is making his first state visit to
the United States since his inauguration in February, said before
his trip that he would ask the United States to ease sanctions
against the DPRK, which he believed would help ease tensions on
the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
He told the joint news conference what he wanted was to "forge
an atmosphere in which we can induce the North Koreans to open
up."
</P>
<P>
"To induce them to open up will be beneficial to the interests
of our two countries, and to the peace of the peninsula and
Northeast Asia in general," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he said any decision on easing sanction would be up to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"If the United States should ease sanctions against North
Korea, the when and how and the content would be a decision for
the American government to make, but we would not oppose, and we
would cooperate," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
