<HEADLINE> Pakistan Advocates Cooperation in Drug Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan said on Tuesday
that drug consuming, transit and producing countries should work
together and put equal emphasis on reduction of drug demand and
harsher penalties on drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the U.N. special session on drugs, Pakistan's
representative Ahmad Kamal said that there is little room for
double standards in law enforcement and the approach toward
penalties needs a review.
</P>
<P>
"It is odd that strong punishment is urged in the developing
countries when in the industrialized countries there is a
relatively more lenient view of the drug problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, one of the biggest casualties of the drug scourge
with 4 million addicts, passed a comprehensive legislation in 1997
and all of its heroin laboratories have been destroyed, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
