<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's External Debt up to 315 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Africa's stock of external
debt is estimated to have reached some 315 billion U.S. Dollars
at the end of last year, the African Development Bank (ADB)
announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the heavy burden, the continent has to use about a
quarter of its export earnings for debt servicing, said ADB
President Omar Kabbaj at the on-going summit meeting of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
A major positive development in this regard, however, is the
wide international consensus that now exists on the need to
broaden existing international initiatives to help resolve the
debt burden of African countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is especially true of the debt of the 33 countries,
which are classified as heavily indebted poor countries (HIPCs),"
the bank president noted.
</P>
<P>
To enhance the debt alleviation effort, he said, his bank is
working actively with the Bretton Woods Institutions and
bilateral donors to mobilize resources to reduce the external
debt of African countries to sustainable levels.
</P>
<P>
A latest achievement is the signing of the agreement for
Uganda in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire last May. Under the agreement,
Uganda has received debt relief amounting to 30 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
To ease the debt of its low-income member countries, the bank
has also established the supplementary financial mechanism to
provide concessional assistance to eligible low-income countries
with outstanding ADB debt for the payment of interest due on such
loans.
</P>
<P>
An initial amount of 180 million U.S. Dollars has been
allocated for financing the program, the bank president told the
three-day summit which is scheduled to close Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
