<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Modernize Army with More Computers Less Tanks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Army announced on
Tuesday that it will modernize and mobilize its heavy combat
divisions with more computers, less personnel and fewer tanks to
prepare for 21st century battle.
</P>
<P>
"We need physical agility. We need smaller forces," General
William Hartzog, commander of the U.S. Army Training and Doctrine
Command and the architect of the new design, said at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
Each heavy division will be shrunk from 18,000 troops to 15,700
and the amount of some types of heavy equipment will be reduced,
from 58 tanks to 45 per battalion, for example, he said. But it
will have more long-range rockets, better intelligence and air
defense and new computers in both vehicles and the backpacks of
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The new Army division, Hartzog said, will be "smaller, more
agile and more lethal," to handle threats ranging from terrorism
to regional conflicts such as the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
According to the general, unit commanders will be able to
dominate an even larger battlefield, knowing where they are, where
their troops are and where the enemy is in real time.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, the Army's Fourth Infantry Division at Fort Hood,
Texas, will become the first to operate under the redesign,
creating a more flexible fighting force that can cover a larger
battlefield including quick-changing threats on multiple fronts.
The remaining units would be ready by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The Army has cut its size from 780,000 to 480,000 soldiers and
from 18 to 10 divisions since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Hartzog said that among other advantages, the new high-tech Army
will include night vision systems that "allow soldiers to see as
far as their weapons can fire".
</P>
<P>
He said the Army is also working on plans to revise its four
other "light" divisions and on organizing permanent strike forces
of 3,000 to 5,000 troops, which in today's Army are generally put
together to go into hot spots such as Bosnia and Haiti.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Hartzog said, the new division's equipment is
designed to answer the three main questions soldiers and
commanders need answered while fighting: "Where am I? Where are my
subordinates? And where is the enemy?"
</P>
<P>
The new division will rely more on digital battlefield maps and
orders and less on telephones and radios, the Army said.
</P>
<P>
Hartzog said the plan was drawn from five years of intense
study.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
